<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Welfare     05-11 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Welfare,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Foundation Urges Changes In Social Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ford Foundation, saying the U.S. social
welfare system is out of date, has recommended comprehensive
changes that include treatment on demand for drug and alcohol
problems.
   The Ford report, entitled ``The Common Good: Social Welfare and
the American Future,'' concedes that many of its recommendations
face uphill political and monetary battles.
   The report was scheduled for release Thursday in Washington, D.C.
   Details were reported in Thursday editions of The New York Times
and The Washington Post.
   The Times said the Ford proposals would cost $29 billion beyond
the $500 billion the federal government spends on social programs.
   The report recommended a tremendous expansion of the Head Start
program to reach 900,000 more 3- and 4-year-olds, and that the
government pay for long-term care for the elderly.
   The proposals would also cost the private sector an estimated
$10 billion for employers to extend health insurance coverage for
workers.
   The panel recommended paying for the additional programs by
taxing Social Security benefits. Such a tax would raise more than
half of the $29 billion annual cost of the recommended programs,
the report said.
   The $3 million study was prepared by an 11-member panel of
business, civic, labor and civil rights leaders and educators.
   ``We are on the right track calling attention to the country's
social deficit,'' said Irving S. Shapiro, chairman of the panel and
former chief executive of the Du Pont Company. ``We know we have a
hell of a fight ahead arousing people to do what needs to be done.''
   One of the most ambitious proposals advocated by the panel is to
provide drug and alcohol treatment ``on demand'' at an estimated $1
billion per year.
   It also called for expanding a food program, Women, Infants and
Children, which now reaches half of the 6.5 million to 7.5 million
people who are eligible.
</TEXT>
