<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Eddie Murphy is being sued for $75
million by an actress who contends he fired her from a film because
she spurned his advances.
   Michael Michele Williams, a 22-year-old New York City actress
who performs under the name Michael Michele, also sued Paramount
Pictures over her dismissal from the soon-to-be released Murphy
picture ``Harlem Nights.''
   Ms. Williams claimed that she was removed from the proposed
television version of Murphy's hit film ``Coming to America,'' so
she could appear opposite him in ``Harlem Nights,'' a film that he
is also producing and directing.
   On the set of ``Harlem Nights,'' Murphy ``made consistent,
personal overtures'' that Ms. Williams ``did not desire,'' the
lawsuit said.
   Murphy tried ``to fondle and otherwise caress'' Ms. Williams and
had her fired ``when it became clear'' that she ``would not accede
to his sexual demands,'' the lawsuit said.
   ``There's absolutely no basis'' to the allegations, said
Murphy's manager, Bob Wachs. ``She was let go because of artistic
differences.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Bill Cosby says misunderstanding lies
at the heart of most marriages.
   ``If the amusement park called Great Adventure had been created
by me, it would have no slides or rides. ... It would simply have
one married couple trying to sustain the glow of their love,''
Cosby wrote in his new book, ``Love and Marriage,'' excerpted in
June's Good Housekeeping.
   Cosby says philosophers have long debated whether a husband and
wife should go to bed angry at each other, but he has found two
good reasons for making up at bedtime:
   ``It feels like the right moment for reconciliation and a fight
is harder to sustain when one of the fighters falls asleep.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Academy Award winner Gene Hackman and actress
Anne Archer will battle bad guys aboard a speeding train in a
remake of the 1950's RKO thriller ``The Narrow Margin.''
   Hackman will play a Los Angeles district attorney trying to keep
a murder witness _ Miss Archer _ safe from hit men.
   Hackman received the 1971 Oscar for best actor for his role as
the cop Popeye Doyle in ``The French Connection.''
   He was nominated as best supporting actor for ``Bonnie and
Clyde'' and ``I Never Sang for My Father,'' and was nominated as
best actor this year for his portrayal of an FBI agent in
``Mississippi Burning.''
   Miss Archer was nominated for best supporting actress last year
for her role as the wronged wife in ``Fatal Attraction.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Director Barry Levinson says Dustin
Hoffman ``was terrific to work with,'' despite warnings he had
received to the contrary.
   Levinson, who won a best director Oscar for ``Rain Man,'' said
Hoffman and his wife went to the hospital with Levinson and his
wife when Mrs. Levinson gave birth during filming in Cincinnati.
   ``It caused a lot of commotion in the hospital,'' he said.
   ``A lot of friends of mine said it would be tough'' working with
Hoffman, but that wasn't the case, Levinson said. ``He was terrific
to work with.''
   Levinson also said it was fun going out on the town in Baltimore
with Danny DeVito during the filming of ``Tin Men'' because DeVito
``is not afraid to get out among the people.''
   Even though ``Rain Man'' won him an Oscar, Levinson said
``Diner'' is probably his personal favorite ``because it was the
first one'' and because he was able to write it, direct it and then
film it in Baltimore, where he grew up.
   The director said he hopes to begin filming his newest movie in
Baltimore this summer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Version moved on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SADDLE BROOK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has acquitted New York Giants
linebacker Lawrence Taylor of drunken driving charges that were
filed after police found him slumped behind the wheel of his car.
   ``The justice system works and I'm happy for myself,'' the
eight-time All-Pro said.
   Municipal Court Judge John Conte found Taylor innocent based on
testimony from two doctors who said the NFL star suffered from
acute food poisoning on the night of his arrest.
   Authorities alleged Taylor was found sleeping at 3:30 a.m. March
24 behind the wheel of his Jeep, which was parked on the shoulder
of the Garden State Parkway. He was charged with drunken driving
despite two blood alcohol level readings of 0.09 percent. Under New
Jersey law, 0.10 percent is considered drunk.
