<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Grumpy'sTravels     05-11 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grumpy's Travels,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stolen Lawn Dwarf Returned with Pictures From His Travels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAUGERTIES, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grumpy the traveling lawn dwarf is back
where he belongs, concrete feet planted firmly on the porch,
following his whirlwind tour of Washington, New York City, Florida
and elsewhere.
   He even has pictures from his vacation.
   The 20-inch, 80-pound concrete statue of the character in the
Walt Disney movie classic ``Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs,''
disappeared March 16 from Carol and Gene Horne's front porch.
   ``I couldn't set my finger on it, but I felt something was
missing,'' Mrs. Horne said. ``The next morning my daughter said,
`Mom, there's somebody missing.'''
   Bashful, Doc, Sneezy, Happy, Sleepy, Dopey and the 400-pound
Snow White were safe and sound but Grumpy was gone.
   On April 26, a freshly scrubbed Grumpy returned, with a sign
dangling from his shoulders that said ``I'm home.'' Along with the
sign was an envelope with 35 photographs from his journey, many of
them with captions on the back.
   Among the photos were snapshots of Grumpy ogling bikini-clad
women from a Florida sand dune, standing in front of the Lincoln
Memorial in Washington, D.C., and dining at McDonald's.
   ``My husband and I, we were laughing so hard at these pictures.
My husband was late for work,'' Mrs. Horne said.
   Grumpy's travels also included visits to Yankee Stadium,
Colorado, North and South Carolina, St. Louis and Texas.
   Mrs. Horne said Grumpy has vanished before, turning up once in
front of an ice cream store and in the back seat of a restaurant
manager's car.
   ``She saw somebody looking over her shoulder and started
screaming. He was just standing there with his arms folded and that
snarl on his face,'' Mrs. Horne said.
   She said neither she nor the police had any idea who took
Grumpy. She theorizes that ``it's someone with an engineering
background. The printing on the back of the pictures is very
similar to the type you see on blueprints.''
   This year's vacation could be Grumpy's last. Mrs. Horne said she
planned on having all the dwarfs cemented in place. Nevertheless,
she admits to envying Grumpy's wandering ways.
   ``He gets to go everywhere. I never get to go anywhere.''
</TEXT>
