<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-11 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State police are going to use Mustangs to
corral speeders this summer.
   Ford Mustangs, that is. The high-powered variety that can reach
140 mph.
   The customized cars can travel about 20 mph faster than standard
patrol cars and have concealed flashing lights and antennas so they
can travel incognito.
   ``We have people who tell us they're driving the speed limit and
they're getting blown off the road,'' said State Patrol Chief Roger
Ledding. ``We're hoping these cars slow things down.''
   The $13,000 cars feature 5-liter, V-8 engines and special tires
and wheels for stability at high speeds. They will have a State
Patrol emblem only on the driver's door, but motorists won't be
able to recognize them as police cars unless they are alongside
them.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris Feldman and his bride, Jean, believe
love is timeless and ageless.
   Timeless because their courtship lasted only two weeks. Ageless
because they're both octogenarians.
   Feldman, 80, and his 81-year-old wife were living separate lives
at Victory Village, one of two retirement communities operated by
the Jewish Homes for the Aging of Greater Los Angeles.
   They met in the dining room in March.
   ``We just started talking to each other. I did like her. I
figured she was just about the size I wanted _ not too tall and not
too fat,'' said Feldman.
   ``He was just a nice person to talk to,'' his wife said.
``That's all I was looking for.''
   On their first and second dates, they attended Victory Village
dances, just ``old-fashioned waltzes,'' Feldman explained, because
``my legs are not as fit as they used to be.''
   Their courtship lasted two weeks and they were married March 26.
   Mrs. Feldman said she was ``surprised when he proposed and I
accepted. He caught me at the right moment.'' He noted it ``was a
little hard to propose but she made it easy for me.''
   They still haven't had an argument. ``We don't have any money to
fight for,'' Feldman quipped.
</TEXT>
