<DOCNO> AP890511-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ImmigrationReform     05-11 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Immigration Reform,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Say Thousands Exploited, Forced Into Underground Existence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration reforms have created a
``vulnerable underclass living in the shadows of our communities,''
immigration rights activists told a House panel.
   Thousands of undocumented aliens who do not qualify for amnesty
are ``being forced into a fearful underground and impoverished
existence,'' said Muriel Heiberger, executive director of the
Massachusetts Immigrant and Refugee Advocacy Coalition.
   The Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986 act allowed
undocumented aliens who could show they entered the United States
before 1982 to apply for amnesty and prohibited employers from
hiring undocumented aliens.
   But witnesses told the House Judiciary subcommittee on
immigration, refugees and international law the law has left many
harshly exploited and with nowhere to turn.
   ``As the undocumented are forced further underground, the
immigration law is creating everything it was supposed to eliminate
_ a vulnerable underclass, living in the shadows of our
communities, facing increased poverty and exploitation,'' Ms.
Heiberger testified.
   Unscrupulous employers ``often exploit undocumented workers
fearful of reporting subminimum wages, sexual harassment and unsafe
working conditions,'' she said.
   Muzaffar A. Chishti, director of the Immigration Project for the
International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union, said the law has had
a deep impact on the so-called ``sweatshop sector.'' Employers are
``finding it easier to exploit these workers and further depress
wages and working conditions,'' she said.
   INS spokesman Verne Jervis countered that those who don't
qualify for amnesty do not have to remain in the United States.
   Jervis said the law was not intended ``to benefit the most
recent arrivals. ... The law is doing what it intended to do'' by
keeping undocumented aliens out of the work force.
   Cecilia Munoz of the National Council of La Raza testified that
spouses and children of legalized family members have had
deportation proceedings initiated against them in Chicago, Dallas,
Oklahoma City, Albuquerque, San Antonio and elsewhere.
   Jervis called that charge ``ridiculous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
