<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-11 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
moderately on Thursday, and the dollar rebounded against the
Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
39.52 points the previous day, recouped 89.14 points, or 0.26
percent, to finish at 34,081.49.
   The dollar ended trading at 134.55 yen, up 0.11 yen from
Wednesday's close of 134.44 yen. Opening lower at 134.18 yen, the
currency rose while moving between 134.17 yen and 134.60 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's lower opening in Tokyo followed its
similar downtrend on overseas markets.
   Japanese market players were inclined to make technical
adjustments without making major moves, said a trader with a
commercial bank in Tokyo, who declined to be named.
   The scheduled release of the U.S. producer price index Friday
also prompted the market's wait-and-see mood, the trader added.
   Other traders said the yen would not continue to rise further
because of the market's fundamental demand for the dollar.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the Nikkei average, which
rose moderately after a slight gain in the Dow Jones industrial
average in New York overnight, did not rise further as market
players stepped off to the sidelines later.
   Nikko Securities' Yoshio Shimoyama said trading became thin in
the absence of market-affecting incentives.
   ``Participants' buying interest was still strong after
consecutive gains last week, but they couldn't determine a
direction of trading,'' he said.
   Sellings for profit-taking also resulted in the index's small
gain Thursday, Shimoyama said.
</TEXT>
