<FIRST>r i PM-PEN-Soviets     05-11 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PEN-Soviets,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Writers' Group Accepts Russian, Lithuanian Chapters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAASTRICHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-five years after the Soviet
Union first tried to gain membership, the PEN international
writers' association has accepted a Russian and a Lithuanian
chapter.
   Members of the 10,000-strong PEN, whose charter speaks out
strongly against censorship, voted unanimously Wednesday to admit
the two groups.
   ``We have at last obtained something we have been fighting for
for decades ... the great Russian literature with its great
traditions ... is finally among us,'' said the group's
international secretary, Alexandre Blokh.
   The association also criticized Turkey, Czechoslovakia and seven
other nations for imprisoning literary figures and journalists,
including a founder of the Charter 77 Czechoslovak human rights
group, playwright Vaclav Havel.
   Soviet participation has been an issue ever since PEN _ Poets,
Playwrights, Editors, Essayists and Novelists _ turned down an
application by the Soviet state in 1924, three years after PEN was
founded.
   PEN had kept out the Soviet Union because of its persecution of
writers and other intellectuals, and Moscow had regarded the
authors' group as anti-communist.
   The approval of the two chapters in the Soviet Union clears the
way for the opening of up to four more PEN chapters there,
including Latvian and Estonian chapters operating in exile, said
PEN's outgoing chairman, Francis King.
   In a speech made before the vote, Soviet novelist Anatoly
Rybakov told delegates that ``all worthy writers can become members
of our PEN center, including those living outside the Soviet
Union.''
   ``We want our country to have its literature, regardless of the
writer's place of residence, regardless of his beliefs and ideas,''
Rybakov said.
   ``Thirty years of Stalin's tyranny, 20 years of (Leonid)
Brezhnev's incompetent rule is long enough to ruin any society,
particularly a society that has no democratic traditions,'' Rybakov
said.
   PEN leadership and Soviet authorities agreed the new chapter
would operate independently of the official Soviet Writers' Union.
   Soviet poet Andrei Bitov conceded ``there can't be any
guarantee'' that the Soviet PEN chapters won't be suppressed or
taken over by authorities.
   But Bitov added: ``There's a kind of belief that everything's
been going in a progressive way,'' referring to President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or increased openness, which has
been credited for more freedom in intellectual pursuits.
   PEN criticized Turkey for jailing at least 24 dissident
intellectuals and banning two novels, including Henry Miller's
``Tropic of Capricorn.''
   PEN also called on Czechoslovakia to release Havel, who in
February was sentenced to nine months in prison. Havel had been
involved in a demonstration to commemorate the 1968 Soviet-led
invasion of his country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
