<FIRST>r w PM-Fernald-Medical     05-11 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fernald-Medical,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Plant's Medical Director Was A Veterinarian, Union Complains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union leaders representing workers at an Ohio
uranium-processing plant complained to Congress that an animal
doctor, rather than a people doctor, led an important medical
division at the government-owned plant.
   Until recently, a veterinarian was the manager of medical
services at the Feed Materials Production Center near Fernald,
Ohio, the labor leaders told the House Education and Labor
Committee Wednesday.
   ``To me it is an obvious example of the casual attitude the
(Department of Energy) and their contractors took when dealing with
the health and very lives of the men and women who worked at these
facilities,'' said Elmer Chatak of the AFL-CIO's industrial union
department.
   A plant spokesman confirmed that David Howell, who holds a
degree in veterinary medicine, held the job until April 13.
   Howell holds several other degrees, including a bachelor's
degree in health sciences with minors in chemistry and mathematics
and a master's degree in pathology, said William Kelley, a
spokesman for the plant's operator, Westinghouse Materials of Ohio.
   Kelley said Howell did not ``perform medical evaluations,'' was
not considered the supervisor of the three physicians who work at
the plant on a subcontract basis, and ``has not been a practicing
veterinarian at all since his affiliation with Westinghouse.''
   The medical services job involves overseeing medical records and
technologists, Kelley said. A new administrator has not yet been
named, he added.
   Howell was moved to another department as part of major
reorganization in which many department heads were changed, the
spokesman said.
   The Fernald plant, about 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati,
processes uranium for use in nuclear weapons or as fuel for
reactors.
   The plant is the subject of a $300 million lawsuit on behalf of
14,000 people who live or work nearby and believe their health has
been threatened by radioactive discharges into the air and water.
The government has admitted ignoring or undermining efforts to
reduce pollution there.
   The government has estimated that as much as 552,000 pounds of
radioactive uranium dust may have escaped into the air from the
plant.
   Workers have been complaining they weren't adequately protected
from or told about the dangerous substances. Most of those
complaints have been directed against the plant's former operator,
NLO Inc., which ran the plant until 1985.
   ``It seems to me that what we have at Fernald is a work force
that has been excessively exposed to radioactive and other toxic
materials over an extended period of time,'' Chatak testified.
   ``For at least the last few years they relied on a medical
program that was directed by a veterinarian and they were studied
by DOE researchers whom they did not trust and could not believe,''
he said.
</TEXT>
