<FIRST>u a PM-LabFire Bjt   05-11 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lab Fire, Bjt,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire That Killed 500,000 Lab Mice Seen as Scientific Setback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS X. QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire killed about 500,000 research mice
at the Jackson Laboratory, and the loss will set back scientists
around the world who depend on its purebred strains, officials said.
   Four construction workers who were remodeling the building where
the blaze broke out Wednesday afternoon were hospitalized, and at
least two firefighters were treated for smoke inhalation, officials
said.
   ``We managed to save what are called the foundation stocks ...
the original genetically defined strains'' of mice, said
Director-designate Kenneth Paigen. ``It will take us time but we
will be able to reproduce what was there.''
   Earl Green, a former Jackson director, said it would take six to
eight generations of mice, or about two or three years, to replace
the animals.
   It was unclear what effect on research the short-term mouse
shortage could have.
   With an annual budget of $27 million, the lab produces between 2
million and 3 million mice a year and provides them to scientists
throughout the country, Europe, Africa and the Soviet Union.
   Its major customers include mammalian genetics researchers at
the National Institutes of Health, Harvard, and Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, as well as major hospital research
centers, said Barbara Trevett, a Jackson spokeswoman.
   During years of breeding, the lab has produced 1,700 strains of
mice by genetic accident. The mice carry odd physical traits, some
caused by mutant genes. Studying those genes can provide clues to
human disorders, such as heart disease, diabetes, cancer and AIDS.
   Sales of the mice generate $10 million a year, which is put back
into research and other programs at the laboratory, Trevett said.
   The fire would not delay Jackson Laboratory's research because
mice used in its own experiments already had been transferred to a
different building, Paigen said.
   But he said he was concerned about preserving the jobs of 230 of
the more than 500 employees of the laboratory, the major employer
in the town of about 2,400 people.
   ``It's going to be a hard blow to the town's economy,'' said
Fire Chief Royal Higgins.
   The fire destroyed a block-long one-story brick and metal
building; 27 other lab buildings were untouched.
   The cause of the fire was under investigation. A sealant used by
the construction workers apparently helped spread the flames,
Higgins said.
   The four injured construction workers were listed as stable,
said Jeanne Dulong, of Mount Desert Island Hospital. The most
seriously burned worker was transferred to Maine Medical Center's
burn unit in Portland, she said.
   Jackson Lab, which was founded in 1929, was destroyed in a 1947
forest fire that swept across Mount Desert Island. After it was
rebuilt, the lab grew rapidly to become the world's largest center
for the study of mammalian genetics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
