<FIRST>r w PM-Lucas-CivilRights     05-11 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lucas-Civil Rights,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liberal Organization Prepares to Fight Lucas Civil Rights Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major liberal organization is gearing up for
a full-dress lobbying campaign to challenge the nomination of
William Lucas as the Justice Department's civil rights chief.
   ``We made a commitment to oppose and we won't go into it
halfheartedly,'' Arthur J. Kropp, president of People for the
American Way, said Wednesday.
   ``It is the most important civil rights position in the
government and we believe Lucas isn't qualified for that top
position,'' he said.
   The group, along with the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights,
an umbrella coalition of 180 organizations, and the NAACP
Educational and Legal Defense Fund Inc. announced this week it
would join the NAACP in opposing Lucas.
   These civil rights organizations contend that Lucas, a black
Republican who ran unsuccessfully for governor of Michigan in 1986,
lacks the necessary experience to be assistant attorney general for
civil rights.
   Kropp said his organization must ``figure out how to get our
case out to the American public'' and members of the Senate who
will ultimately vote on Lucas' nomination.
   No date has been set for Lucas' confirmation hearing before the
Senate Judiciary Committee.
   Kropp would not rule out an advertising campaign similar to one
the group waged in 1987 to help defeat Robert Bork's nomination to
the Supreme Court.
   Despite mounting opposition among civil rights groups, David
Runkel, a top aide to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, predicted
that Lucas would not encounter serious opposition in the Senate.
   The nomination has split the civil rights movement, with such
prominent figures as Jesse Jackson and the Rev. Joseph Lowery, head
of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, supporting Lucas.
   Lucas, a former Democratic sheriff and chief executive of Wayne
County, Mich., is also backed by Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., and
the Detroit chapter of the Urban League.
   Kropp acknowledged that the split will make the fight more
difficult.
   ``Certainly Jesse Jackson brings a lot of prestige, symbolic
validation, we'll need to deal with it,'' Kropp said. ``It is not
something anyone feels comfortable with.''
   Lucas, a former Democrat, became a Republican the year before
his unsuccessful gubernatorial bid. He opposes racial quotas but
generally supports affirmative action.
   Besides his lack of experience in civil rights, opponents cite
Lucas' record as sheriff of Wayne County, which includes Detroit.
   A panel of state judges once cited Lucas for contempt of a court
order to reduce overcrowding and improve conditions at the Wayne
County Jail. A federal appeals court also criticized Lucas for
failing to investigate allegations of brutality against several
deputies.
   Lucas has said jail conditions were out of his control because
of a fiscal crisis in local government and he only learned of the
brutality charges years later.
   Runkel said Lucas ``has a very impressive record of achievement
in the civil rights area.
   ``When he became sheriff of Wayne County less than 1 percent of
the detective force was black. After 12 years as sheriff that had
increased to 20 percent of the detective force.
   ``Bill Lucas' experience is not significantly less than other
people,'' said Runkel, who noted that other civil rights chiefs
``did not have significant litigating experience in civil rights.''
   He called Lucas a conciliator whose approach to civil rights
issues was well suited to the Bush administration's policies.
   ``Our intention is to try to move forward on contentious civil
rights issues in a constructive way and not get involved in
contentious legal disputes that might only delay the providing of
civil rights,'' Runkel said.
</TEXT>
