<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     05-11 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissidents Allege Police Involved in Torture Death of Student</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto Available</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident groups charged today that a
radical student was tortured and killed by police interrogators and
they called for peaceful protests to demand the fall of President
Roh Tae-woo's government.
   About 5,000 students rallied today at Chosun University in the
southeastern city of Kwangju to denounce police for the death of
Chol-kyu Lee, according to Yonhap, the South Korean news agency.
   Some cut their fingers and wrote anti-government slogans in
blood.
   Lee, a 24-year-old student at Chosun, had served almost two
years in jail for violating national security laws and was being
sought by police for writing articles praising communist North
Korea.
   His body was found Wednesday in a reservoir near Kwangju, police
said.
   The United National Democratic Movement, the main dissident
alliance, alleged Lee was tortured and killed by police
investigators assigned to suppressing dissident groups.
   Dissidents and Lee's family claimed the body showed signs of
electric torture and beatings.
   Police denied involvement in Lee's death and officials said
leftists may have killed the student as part of an attempt to cover
up anti-government activities. An initial autopsy showed no signs
of torture, but it appeared Lee was slain, they said.
   Dissident groups charged that a special police unit, the Joint
Investigation Team, set up earlier this year to suppress violent
anti-government groups, may have been involved in Lee's death.
   The unit had announced Wednesday it arrested 234 dissidents
since April 3 for anti-government activity.
   The discovery of Lee's body came after six riot troopers were
killed May 3 in a clash with radical students in the southern port
of Pusan. The government ordered a major crackdown on violent
dissidents after the troopers were killed.
   South Korea has been hit by a wave of violent anti-government
protests and labor strikes in recent months. Police have rounded up
dozens of suspects as part of efforts to crush dissident groups.
   The National Student Council, the main alliance of South Korea's
radical students, charged that Lee was tortured and it demanded
that police officers involved be arrested and punished.
   ``We will fight to the end if there is any attempt to cover up
or fabricate the truth,'' said council head Lim Chong-suk.
   Thousands of riot police were on alert for demonstrations Friday
in the central city of Taejon and in Kwangju on Saturday to mark
the anniversary next week of a 1980 anti-government uprising in
Kwangju in which at least 192 people were killed.
   Some dissident and radical student groups have said they will
stop violent protests because of the deaths of the riot troopers in
Pusan. But Lee's death could provoke new unrest, especially if
police attempt to block protests.
   Radical students and the anti-government dissident groups have
little support because of their violent tactics and extreme
political views. The radicals have been calling for the overthrow
of Roh and the creation of a leftist state ruled by workers and
farmers.
   The government has warned that efforts by radicals to build an
alliance with workers threatens stability. Strikes have cost the
economy almost $4 billion in lost production so far this year,
officials say.
</TEXT>
