<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill     05-11 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Envisions Gradual Buildup Of Cleanup Crew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon vowed to put 1,600 more workers on
Alaska's shores, but said it would take up to six weeks to get them
to the front lines of the nation's worst oil spill.
   Exxon's promise came Wednesday after the Coast Guard ordered it
to expand its cleanup. State and federal officials have repeatedly
criticized Exxon for moving too slowly to clean up the March 24
spill.
   An Exxon spokesman said the number of shore-based workers would
reach 5,000 by late June.
   Exxon said the buildup had to be gradual to provide training and
housing.
   ``You've got to house all these people, you've got feed these
people, you've got to train them,'' said spokesman Henry Beathard.
   Coast Guard Adm. Paul A. Yost told a Senate hearing in
Washington that despite the increased manpower he considers it
almost impossible for Exxon to clean all the oil from more than 300
miles of shoreline by its Sept. 15 target date.
   As part of its cleanup plan, Exxon also has requested that some
environmental laws be waived so it can burn off the oily wastes and
process oily water at the Valdez treatment plant normally used by
oil companies to clean bilge water from their tankers.
   Both options were scorned at a hearing Wednesday night. Speakers
expressed concern about air pollution from the burning, and said
the terminal plant was inadequate for Exxon's needs.
   Exxon expects to collect more than 55,000 tons of contaminated
material, from tainted water to soiled clothing worn by cleanup
workers.
   ``I feel the people of Valdez, the people of Cordova and the
people of Prince William Sound have given their fair share of blood
in this situation,'' said James Winchester, a local
environmentalist. ``I think you boys ought to go home and work this
through again.''
   Earlier, the Coast Guard ordered Exxon to beef up its cleanup
operation and provide federal officials with weekly, detailed
operations schedules of cleanup work outside Prince William Sound,
where the Exxon Valdez tanker ran aground and spilled its load.
   The order, announced in Valdez by Vice Adm. Clyde Robbins, was
the Coast Guard's official response to the Exxon cleanup plan
submitted May 1 for Coast Guard approval.
   The oil, spreading steadily, has fouled beaches along Alaska's
coast as far south as Wide Bay, about 450 miles southwest of
Valdez. Authorities said Wednesday they also discovered oil patches
on the west coast of Kodiak Island.
   The crippled tanker is being repaired at Naked Island in Prince
William Sound. According to the Coast Guard, Exxon plans to move
the 987-foot vessel to Portland or the Far East next month.
   The hull was ripped open by the crash and there are huge
boulders inside the cargo hold, scooped up as the craft scraped
against the reef, said Robbins, the Coast Guard's on-site commander
of the spill cleanup.
   He said it appeared doubtful that Exxon could meet its Sept. 15
cleanup deadline. ``I am seriously concerned that the investment of
resources you describe will not be able to clean the 300-plus miles
of shoreline in the time alloted,'' Robbins said in a letter to
Exxon general manager Otto Harrison, the company's ranking
executive in the spill zone.
   Workers, meanwhile, toiled on the four islands hardest hit by
the spill in the sound, hoping to clean the shores a few days
before seals begin their annual birthing cycle about May 20.
   There are about 10,000 seals in the sound, and between 25 and 50
percent may have been in areas affected by the spill, said Mary
Sigman, a biologist with the Alaska Department of Fish and Game.
   No seal deaths have been attributed directly to the spill,
although biologists say they have seen heavily oiled seals.
   As of Tuesday, the U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife Service said there had
been 613 confirmed sea otter deaths and 9,918 bird kills.
</TEXT>
