<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-LatinAmerica     05-11 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Latin America,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latin America Concerned Over Panama Vote Fraud Allegations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Latin American leaders say allegations
of election fraud in Panama and violence against the opposition
could further isolate that country from the region's democracies.
   Late Wednesday, Panama's electoral commission nullified the
presidential election after Guillermo Endara, the opposition
candidate, and his two vice presidential candidates were beaten by
government supporters. Officials said one of Endara's bodyguards
was killed in an ensuing gunfight.
   In a statement released in Brasilia and Montevideo, Uruguay,
seven Latin American foreign ministers said the turbulence ``could
distance even further the Panamanian government and democratic
community of Latin America, during a historic moment in which free
and popular expression is advancing in a way never before seen in
our region.
   ``We believe the best defense of the interests of nations and
peoples of Latin America can be achieved only through free
expression and the popular will.''
   The statement was signed by the Group of Eight nations, which
actually has seven members _ Peru, Argentina, Uruguay, Brazil,
Venezuela, Colombia and Mexico. Panama was suspended after Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, the nation's de facto ruler, engineered the
ouster of elected President Eric Delvalle in February 1988.
   The Group was formed in 1986 to analyze methods of reducing
Latin America's $400 billion foreign debt.
