<FIRST>r w PM-AcidRain     05-11 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Acid Rain,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Chairman Says Acid Rain Bill Would Unfairly Burden Nine
States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel chairman, demonstrating that the
acid rain debate will again pit blocks of states against one other,
says proposed legislation to cut sulfur dioxide emissions would
place an unfair burden on nine states.
   Rep. Philip R. Sharp, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee's energy and power subcommittee, wrote President Bush on
Wednesday that the nine states account for 52 percent of sulfur
dioxide emissions, considered the leading cause of acid rain.
   But Sharp said three congressional proposals introduced so far
would require the nine to achieve 77 percent of the nation's
required reductions. The affected states are Ohio, Indiana,
Missouri, Pennsylvania, Kentucky, Illinois, Tennessee, West
Virginia and Georgia.
   Sharp, D-Ind., wrote Bush because the administration is
developing its own acid rain proposals, which could be submitted to
Congress this month.
   ``Nine states in the nation should not be cleaning up both their
own and somebody else's portion of the national reduction,'' Sharp
told Bush in the letter.
   Sharp said the proposed legislation would emphasize reduction of
sulfur dioxide emitted from older, coal-fired electric power plants
rather than from industrial facilities. The nine states, because of
their geography, use coal-fired plants largely because they do not
have access to hydro-power and natural gas, Sharp said.
   ``A pound of sulfur dioxide, removed from the air, is of equal
benefit to the environment whether it is removed from a small
industrial facility in Texas or a large power plant in the
Midwest,'' the letter said.
   In the past, the Northeast, the primary victim of acid rain,
sought immediate action while Midwestern states feared controls on
their coal-fired plants would boost electric bills.
   States that produce large amounts of high-sulfur coal _ Indiana,
Illinois, Ohio, West Virginia and Pennsylvania _ worried that
controls would cause massive job losses in the coal industry.
   The West, where low-sulfur coal is mined and acid rain is a less
serious problem, has been reluctant to pay the cost for new
controls.
   Acid rain is formed when sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide are
converted in the atmosphere into acids, which travel far from their
starting points to pollute lakes and forests and, according to
health experts, cause serious respiratory problems for asthmatics,
children and the elderly.
   The leading sources of sulfur dioxide are coal-burning power
plants and industrial facilities. Nitrogen oxides are emitted in
approximately equal amounts for asthmatics, children and the
elderly.
</TEXT>
