<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-11 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rebounds Against Yen, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rebounded today against the
Japanese yen while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index gained
moderately.
   The dollar closed at 134.55 yen, up 0.11 yen from Wednesday's
134.44 yen finish. It opened at 134.18 yen and ranged from 134.17
yen to 134.60 yen.
   The U.S. currency had declined 0.56 yen on Wednesday after
closing Tuesday at 135.00 yen, its highest closing in eight months.
   Today, speculative investors bought the dollar near the day's
lowest levels, said Minori Takeuchi of Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   ``It's not much of a rise considering it hit a high of 134.70
yen in New York overnight, but still, Japanese investors'
fundamental demand for the dollar remains the same,'' she said.
   Ms. Takeuchi said reports of two economic indicators today and
Friday also are likely to boost demand for the dollar because
market players expect no slowdown in the U.S. economy in April.
   The United States is to announce April figures for retail prices
this monring and for producer prices on Friday.
   On the stock market, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a
39.52-point loser Wednesday, climbed 89.14 points, or 0.26 percent,
closing at 34,081.49.
   ``The Nikkei rose moderately, but trading was thin because a
majority of market players remained on the sidelines due to
uncertainties over foreign exchange rates and Japan's discount rate
hike,'' said Yoshiro Inouye, an analyst at Nomura Securities.
   Media and market players have speculated that the Bank of Japan
will raise its official discount rate by at least 0.5 percentage
point to 3.0 percent late in May, but the central bank has not made
any official announcement.
   ``Scheduled releases of two major U.S. economic figures later
today and Friday also made participants feel reluctant to make
major moves,'' Inouye said.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 750 million
shares, down from Wednesday's 900 million. Among gainers were
steel, shipbuilding and construction issues.
</TEXT>
