<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Mott     05-11 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Mott,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second-Generation Philanthropist C.S. Harding Mott Dead at 82</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   C.S. Harding Mott, who teamed with his
father to develop and sustain what is now the nation's 12th largest
charitable foundation, has died. He was 82.
   Harding Mott, chairman emeritus of the Flint-based Charles
Stewart Mott Foundation, died in his sleep Wednesday at a nursing
home in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. He had maintained a permanent
residence in Delray Beach, Fla., and maintained a summer home in
Flint.
   Harding Mott played a low-key but crucial role with the
foundation begun in 1926 by his father, who served 60 years on the
General Motors Corp. board of directors and once was the
automaker's largest individual shareholder.
   ``They shared an office for close to 30 years and he (Harding
Mott) adored his father,'' said Harding Mott's son-in-law, William
S. White, who was named foundation chairman when Mott became
chairman emeritus last year.
   ``He, for many years, stayed out of the limelight,'' White said.
``He was a quiet, humble leader.''
   Charles Mott supported the foundation decades after its
formation. But it burgeoned when Harding Mott, an original
foundation trustee, persuaded his father in 1963 to donate 1.8
million GM shares worth $129 million at the time.
   When Charles Mott died in 1973 at age 97, the foundation
received all but $1.3 million of his $43.3 million estate.
   Last year, the foundation awarded grants amounting to $34
million to projects focused mainly on community and individual
improvement, spokeswoman Judy Samuelson said.
   Harding Mott graduated in 1931 from Yale University and served
as a Mott Foundation vice president from 1944 to 1965, when he was
named its president. Mott held that post until 1976, when he was
named chairman.
   After being named chairman emeritus, Mott remained a board
member and held ad-hoc positions on each board committee.
   Survivors include Mott's wife Isabel; son, C.S. Harding Mott II;
and daughter, Clair M. White.
   There will be no funeral service.
</TEXT>
