<FIRST>r a PM-NBC-AbortionMovie     05-11 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NBC-Abortion Movie,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Vows to Run `Roe Vs. Wade' Without Ads, If Necessary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed with reviews from TV critics praising the
made-for-TV movie ``Roe Vs. Wade,'' NBC is asking advertisers to
stand up to pressure groups seeking to block the film about the
case that legalized abortion.
   In a May 8 letter to advertisers, NBC President Robert C. Wright
vowed to air the movie as scheduled Monday without advertising if
advertisers pull out.
   ``I'm not writing this letter to simply sell commercial time,''
Wright wrote. ``We will underwrite this project without support, if
necessary. We're very proud of `Roe Vs. Wade.'''
   NBC said the status of advertising time sold during the two-hour
film was still unsettled and probably would be until the broadcast
date.
   The fact-based movie stars Holly Hunter as a character based on
Norma McCorvey, the then-anonymous ``Jane Roe'' plaintiff who sued
Dallas District Attorney Henry Wade in the case that went to the
Supreme Court. Amy Madigan plays attorney Sarah Weddington.
   The abortion battle heightened when the high court heard
arguments April 26 in a Missouri case that could affect the 1973
decision.
   The movie is about the pro-choice advocates who prevailed in
1973, but also portrays sympathetically the prosecutors who argued
the other side, though they get much less attention.
   ``This is discriminatory programming against an entire class of
people in the United States,'' said John C. Willke, president of
the National Right to Life Committee.
   ``It is clearly strong pro-abortion propaganda. There is
absolutely no claim that can be made that this is balanced, not
remotely.''
   He said his group was calling on NBC affiliates to refuse to
show the movie, or provide anti-abortion groups with at least 30
minutes of time to refute the views they believe the movie
represents.
   In an unusual move, NBC allowed advertisers to screen the film
before deciding whether to sponsor it.
   ``A few have withdrawn. Others have been added,'' said NBC
spokesman Curt Block. ``We haven't identified any of the names of
advertisers in or out and expect it will be fully sponsored. The
next couple of days are going to be crucial.''
   Wright's letter quoted favorable reviews of the movie and said
advertisers should be concerned about threats of boycotts as a way
for pressure groups to control program content.
   ``NBC firmly believes the decision about where your messages
appear rests with you and your marketing people _ not with those
who have a predisposition to judge a program's merits based on
their own agenda and no information,'' said Wright's letter.
   NBC News' Tom Brokaw will anchor a 30-minute special later in
the evening to discuss abortion, but Willke wasn't impressed.
   ``Baloney,'' he said. ``They are controlling the discussion.''
   In his letter, Wright referred to recent cases of advertisers
pulling out of TV programs because of pressure from groups and
individuals who find them offensive. He mentioned no specifics, but
shows that have been targeted recently include Fox's raunchy sitcom
``Married ... With Children'' and NBC's cuttingly satirical
``Saturday Night Live.''
   ABC recently canceled two ``reality-based'' specials, ``Crimes
of Passion II'' and ``Scandals II'' due to lack of advertiser
support because of their expected lurid content. Both were sequels
to previous specials that garnered good ratings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
