<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0523EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Panama-Scene     05-11 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Scene,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>An Iron Bar Just Misses Opposition Candidate, Then Chaos</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition vice presidential
candidate Ricardo Arias Calderon said he froze when he saw the iron
bar coming.
   ``But at the same time my assistant pulled me away and the bar
missed my head by a few inches.''
   Arias Calderon was describing how he was attacked Wednesday by a
gang of thugs loyal to Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   His presidential running mate Guillermo Endara and second vice
presidential candidate Guillermo Ford suffered head injuries during
the clash.
   The violence put an end to a peaceful demonstration that
escalated into a confrontation and an exchange of gunfire.
   Four security men were wounded and one of the candidates'
civilian bodyguards killed, officials said.
   The demonstrators were protesting government attempts to
``steal'' an election they say Endara won. Both sides claimed
victory.
   The opposition cavalcade had wound through the streets of Panama
City until it stopped in front of a group of riot troops.
   ``We were talking with an officer in charge about withdrawing,''
Arias Calderon said. ``We were told to wait. At that moment the
paramilitary broke through the ranks of the riot police and started
shooting.''
   Witnesses said the candidates' bodyguards leaped out of cars and
started returning fire, although Arias Calderon denied his men had
weapons.
   Witnesses also said the demonstrators had thrown rocks and
bottles at the paramilitary ``Dignity Battalions,'' who were
standing behind the riot police.
   ``I ran into an alley with other people,'' Arias Calderon said.
   ``People were falling into each other. I fell and then about
five people fell on top of me. I could not breathe. Then I heard
someone say `my vice president', and he and others picked me up and
took me inside a store.''
   The man who picked him up, Gilberto Cardenas, said he and others
also picked up Endara and put him in a truck to take him to a
hospital.
   The Dignity Battalion is made up of civilians recruited into
armed groups with the expressed purpose of defending Panama in case
of a U.S. invasion, which Noriega has been saying could happen.
   Noriega, head of the Defense Forces, has been de facto leader of
Panama since 1983.
   ``The world knows ... that what's at stake here is not Panama
Canal (as the government claims) but the desire of a people to be
free,'' said Arias Calderon.
</TEXT>
