<FIRST>r i PM-Poland     05-11 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miners Return to Work after Agreement Reached; Bug Found In Solidarity
Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miners at four southwestern copper mines
ended a six-day strike today and returned to work after winning 30
percent pay increases plus higher bonuses, a Solidarity spokesman
said.
   In another development, Solidarity called on the Interior
Ministry to investigate the planting of an eavesdropping device in
one of its campaign offices after local officials refused to look
into the matter.
   Preparatory work to reopen the mines began with the first shift,
following the acceptance of the agreement by workers on Wednesday
night, said Jan Sugalski of Solidarity, a member of the strike
committee.
   Normal work at the mines was to start in the afternoon, he said.
   The strike which began May 5 and involved up to 20,000 miners
had been the first major instance of labor unrest since the April 5
signing of a broad agreement between Communist authorities and the
Solidarity-led opposition.
   The agreement led to the reinstatement of Solidarity after a
seven-year ban and a government promise to allow the opposition to
run for one-third of the seats in Parliament's lower house and all
the seats in its new Senate.
   The June elections are to be the first open balloting in the
East bloc.
   The free trade union movement said the strike was inspired by
the official OPZZ unions but joined by Solidarity members
frustrated by high inflation, which has reached an 80 percent
annual rate this year.
   Sugalski said the miners won a 30 percent increase in basic
wages plus a 30 percent bonus if production goals are met. They
originally demanded a 50 percent increase in basic pay.
   The increase in basic wages averages about $1.40 a day, he said.
The miners now earn $112 to $169 a month.
   ``Solidarity helped miners win pay for the period of the strike,
and we are very happy about it,'' said Sugalski.
   The agreement also calls for ``urgent changes'' in the pay
system, he said. Miners have long complained that the pay structure
undervalues labor performed during the normal five-day work week,
forcing miners to work weekends to make ends meet.
   The strikes were at four mines near the city of Lubin, about 200
miles southwest of Warsaw. The official PAP news agency said the
strike reduced output by 100,000 tons of ore daily.
   Poland is the world's eighth-largest producer of refined copper.
In 1987, it exported to the West more than 161,000 tons, worth
about $233 million.
   Solidarity workers found the electronic eavesdropping device in
campaign offices in the northern provincial capital of Slupsk,
union spokesman said Jacek Moskwa said Wednesday.
   Hew told a Warsaw news conference that the device was found
Tuesday in a wall in the Solidarity Citizens Committee office the
city about 50 miles east of the port of Gdansk.
   Government spokesman Pawel Byra said he knew nothing about it.
   ``The Slupsk case sheds a clear and worrying light on methods
applied by the coalition-government side in the election campaign.
It was proved again that the Polish state is still an instrument of
a political monopoly,'' said a statement released by Solidarity's
national citizens committee.
   The committee is coordinating the free trade union movement's
campaign for June's partially democratic elections.
   Moskwa said the Slupsk committee asked the local prosecutor's
office to investigate, but it refused. The national committee then
complained in Warsaw at the Interior Ministry, which oversees the
police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
