<FIRST>r a PM-PrincetonControversy     05-11 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Princeton Controversy,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Professors Leaving English Faculty; Alleged Sexual Incident
Cited</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Princeton University's
English department says his recent resignation was prompted in part
by lenient treatment of a professor accused of making sexual
advances on a student.
   Emory Elliott is one of four members of the English faculty to
resign since a controversy erupted over the September incident,
which involved a male English professor and a male graduate student.
   The professor, Thomas McFarland, 62, was suspended that month
for one year. Faculty members had hoped he would be eased out
altogether, Elliott said.
   The student who allegedly was the target of the advance reported
it to police last week, but it was unclear if charges would be
filed.
   Kim Otis, a lawyer representing the student, said his client
told police it was a ``criminal assault of a sexual nature'' but
denied the student was alleging rape or sexual assault.
   Otis said there was a ``definite reason'' the student did not go
to police sooner, but the attorney refused to elaborate.
   Robert Wills, McFarland's lawyer, said the student's delay cast
doubt on his allegations.
   University officials have refused to comment on McFarland's
suspension or on the alleged incident. The Princetonian, the
student newspaper, reported that the episode occurred after an
English department party.
   Elliott, who is leaving for the University of California,
Riverside, said his disillusionment with the Ivy League school's
administration mounted after it notified the faculty in January it
would allow McFarland to return in the fall.
   ``We had been given hope early on in the fall there would be a
resolution, that the professor would accept some kind of other
position or early retirement, that we would not be looking forward
to his return to the classroom,'' Elliott said.
   Several English students said in interviews that the dispute
over McFarland was part of a deeper morale problem in the
department that stemmed partly from insufficient financial support.
   Another of the departing professors, Margaret Doody, said the
university's handling of the matter was ``a very serious factor''
in her decision.
   The other English faculty members reportedly leaving Princeton
are Sandra Gilbert and Valerie Smith, both feminist literary
critics. Neither returned messages left Wednesday on their home
answering machines.
</TEXT>
