<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSTesting     05-11 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Testing,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Urges Routine AIDS Testing for All Adults</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All Americans under age 60 should be encouraged by
their doctors to be tested for the AIDS virus, regardless of their
risk of being infected, two physicians recommend today.
   Currently, most experts recommend limiting routine AIDS testing
to people who are at obvious increased risk of the disease.
   In their report in the New England Journal of Medicine, Drs.
Frank S. Rhame of the University of Minnesota and Dennis G. Maki of
the University of Wisconsin said doctors should take a more active
role in promoting AIDS testing for their patients.
   ``Our greatest concern is to reach the great number of persons
infected with HIV who are not availing themselves of any current
options in testing and who are not confronting their risk for HIV
infection,'' they wrote.
   Testing reveals infection with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
People may carry this virus for many years before becoming sick.
   They said that doctors might raise the subject with patients by
saying: ``I recommend an HIV test to all my patients because some
people who have risked exposure to HIV don't realize it, and many
persons whose activities put them at risk find it difficult to
disclose them.''
   Among the benefits of widespread testing that they cited:
   _People who know they are infected will benefit from earlier
treatment with the AIDS drug AZT as well as therapy for infections
associated with AIDS. Such medicines can prolong people's lives but
not cure the disease.
   _People who know they are infected may be more careful not to
pass the virus on to others.
   _Taking the test would remind people that AIDS is potentially a
problem for anyone.
   _Candidates for research studies of new AIDS drugs would be
identified.
   ``We are recommending HIV testing vigorously to all U.S. adults
under the age of 60 regardless of their reported risk history,''
the doctors wrote.
   The doctors said they doubted that aggressive testing programs
would drive people away from the medical care system, as some have
argued. They said that falsely positive results _ another argument
against widespread testing _ would be rare.
   They said the suggestion that infected people should be
protected from the bad news is ``somewhat paternalistic'' and
counter to the trend toward a patient's right to know.
   ``In essence, we are arguing that HIV infection should be
treated as much as possible like another infectious disease,'' they
wrote.
</TEXT>
