<HEAD>Dollar Rises in Active Trading; Gold Loses Luster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in active European trading this
morning. Gold firmed in stagnant trading.
   Traders said demand for the dollar resumed after a pause
Wednesday. ``Demand for the dollar is quite sustained,'' said a
trader in Milan, Italy.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.11 yen to a closing 134.55. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 134.80 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _ 1.9105 West German marks, up from 1.9047
   _ 1.7030 Swiss francs, up from 1.6925
   _ 6.4578 French francs, down from 6.4645
   _ 2.1505 Dutch guilders, up from 2.150
   _ 1,393.00 Italian lire, up from 1,390.12
   _ 1.1843 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1849
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6660, compared to $1.6717
late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $377.25 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $377.70.
   In Zurich at noon, the bid price was $377.80, from $376.75 bid
late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold dropped 98 cents to close at a bid
of $377.96.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.65 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $5.68.
