<SECOND>PM-People-Bible Belt,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Fan To Stay Away From `Father Of Bluegrass Music'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALLATIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who dismissed a charge against
Grand Ole Opry star Bill Monroe for allegedly hitting a woman in
the face with a Bible also ordered the woman to stay away from the
bluegrass pioneer.
   Sumner County Judge Jane Wheatcraft dismissed the assault and
battery charge on Wednesday and expressed her sympathy for Monroe.
   ``I know this warrant has been an embarrassment to you,'' the
judge told Monroe.
   ``I'm so happy,'' he said outside the courtroom. ``It's been
difficult with people bothering me. I'm glad it's over.''
   When Wanda Huff arrived Wednesday for the hearing, Sheriff
Richard Sutton confiscated a loaded .25-caliber pistol from her
pickup truck.
   Monroe's lawyer Bob Ingrum said he requested the search because
Mrs. Huff said several times she had received word someone wanted
to kill Monroe.
   Prosecutors told the judge they had witnesses who said Mrs. Huff
called Monroe's office and home, sometimes up to 15 times a day and
often using aliases.
   A tearful Mrs. Huff denied making the harassing phone calls.
   ``You can pay people to tell all kind of lies,'' she said as she
left the parking lot.
   ``I've been deceived. I've been betrayed. I got beat up,'' she
said. ``I did not threaten to kill him. If I wanted to, I could
have when we were alone.''
   The Bible incident allegedly took place after Mrs. Huff, 51,
asked Monroe, 77, to swear on it that he hadn't been seeing other
women. Mrs. Huff has been described only as a fan of the musician.
   Before the May 1 Bible incident, she had called the farm to warn
workers she was coming to see Monroe to retrieve some gifts she
gave him, Assistant District Attorney Dee Gay said.
   Ingrum said Mrs. Huff wanted to take back some blue jeans, a tie
tack, a hatband and $27 for garden seeds she had given Monroe.
   ``She threw the britches in the yard, the hatband in the mule
yard and the $27 in Mr. Monroe's face,'' Ingrum said. ``We never
did find the tie tack, and she threw her glasses on top of the
roof.''
   Monroe called Goodlettsville police to throw Mrs. Huff off his
farm, Gay said. She asked them to arrest Monroe, but they refused
to file charges against him.
   Mrs. Huff went to a magistrate, who issued the assault warrant.
Monroe was arrested May 2, and released on $500 bond.
   Ingrum obtained a temporary restraining order Wednesday
instructing Mrs. Huff to stay away from Monroe. Mrs. Huff agreed to
comply, Gay said.
   Monroe, known for the song ``Blue Moon of Kentucky'' and many
bluegrass hits, said he didn't like publicity about the incident,
``but my good friends and fans know it was wrong.''
</TEXT>
