<FIRST>r a PM-FinancialFlight     05-11 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Financial Flight,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gherman Gets Stiff Sentence in Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A financial planner who bilked clients of millions
of dollars was sentenced to 30 years in prison and ordered to pay
$12.9 million in restitution.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Marcus sentenced Henry Gherman on
Wednesday on seven embezzlement and mail fraud convictions.
   Marcus said the reason for the stiff sentence was because there
were many victims, ``real people, not large institutions,'' who
lost money as a result of Gherman's fraud.
   ``As the fraud unveiled, he took almost $5 million of these
people's money,'' Marcus said. ``To this day, vast amounts of money
remained unaccounted for.''
   Many of the dozens of clients bilked were doctors and nurses who
entrusted Gherman with their pension plans. They believe he
swindled some $20 million since starting his ``one-stop shopping''
investment and financial planning firm in 1970.
   Gherman, charged with misusing $10 million of his clients'
money, claimed that most of it was wiped out by the 1987 stock
market crash.
   ``I never schemed, I never planned it,'' Gherman told the judge.
``I never set out to do this. I never converted other people's
money to my own benefit or that of my family.''
   He showed no reaction as the sentence was read. Gherman's
relatives, including his wife of 33 years and their two daughters,
were in tears.
   Gherman was arrested last October in Tokyo and was returned to
Miami by federal marshals Dec. 28.
</TEXT>
