<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-11 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Continues to Soak Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain drenched the Northeast early today, with as much as an inch
reported in the past 24 hours, and the mercury dipped into the 20s
in the northern Great Lakes.
   A low pressure system off the mid-Atlantic Coast was pumping
moist air into the region and triggering rain from New England into
the upper Ohio Valley.
   Some of the rain was heavy. Islip, N.Y., received more than 1}
inches of rain in the six hours that ended at 2 a.m. EDT.
   By early today, rainfall over the past 24 hours had totalled
nearly 1} inches at New York's John F. Kennedy Airport and over 1\
inches at Pittsburgh.
   Flood watches were in effect throughout the day for southeast
New York state and much of southern New England.
   Behind the rain, overnight temperatures dropped into the 20s and
30s over the northern Great Lakes.
   Further west, showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered
across the Rockies.
   A low pressure area off the California coast scattered rain
across portions of the state, with the heaviest rainfall in the San
Joaquin and Sacramento valleys.
   Winds were strong and gusty across the desert regions of
Southern California.
   Today's forecast called for rain and thunderstorms from the
northern and middle Atlantic Coast states across the lower Great
Lakes and upper Ohio Valley; afternoon and evening thunderstorms
across the northern and central Rockies, parts of Utah and Nevada
and western Texas; scattered showers over the northern Pacific
Coast; and strong, gusty winds from the northern Plains to the
central and southern Rockies.
   Highs were expected to be in the 50s from the northern and
middle Atlantic Coast across much of the Ohio Valley and Great
Lakes, the northern Rockies, Idaho, and parts of Nevada and Utah;
the 80s from much of the Florida Peninsula across southern
Louisiana, southern Texas, the southern Rockies and southern New
Mexico and Arizona; and the 60s and 70s in much of the rest of the
nation.
   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EDT ranged from 26 degrees at Marquette,
Mich., to 78 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 48 fair; Boston 45 rain; Buffalo 45 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 55 fair; Cincinnati 48 fair; Cleveland 47 cloudy;
Detroit 48 cloudy; Miami 71 fair; New York 47 rain; Philadelphia 48
drizzle; Pittsburgh 45 rain; Portland, Maine 47 rain; Washington 50
cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 62 windy; Chicago 43 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
58 fair; Denver 49 fair; Des Moines 53 fair; Indianapolis 44 fair;
Kansas City 51 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 51 fair; Nashville 49
fair; New Orleans 65 fair; St. Louis 49 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 63 partly cloudy; Anchorage 45 cloudy; Las
Vegas 58 windy; Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 73 fair; Salt Lake
City 57 fair; San Diego 57 partly cloudy; San Francisco 51 partly
cloudy; Seattle 44 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 48 rain; Toronto 45 partly cloudy.
