<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary     05-11 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Groups Reject Party Offer For Round-Table Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's leading opposition groups
have rejected the ruling Communist Party's offer to negotiate the
details of a transition to a multiparty system, opposition
spokesmen said today.
   The party's governing Central Committee proposed earlier this
week that procedures for next year's promised multiparty elections
and other reforms take place in a round-table setting.
   But the opposition spokesmen said the leaders of eight groups
met Wednesday night and decided they wanted to present their views
as a single entity.
   The Communists have demonstrated increasing willingness to share
power with other political groups following a severe economic
crisis and demand for greater democracy.
   The Central Committee said the negotiations could be conducted
in a setting similar to the series of meetings held recently in
Poland, where the government agreed April 5 to reinstate the
outlawed trade union Solidarity and allow opposition participation
in parliamentary elections.
   Balint Magyar of the League of Free Democrats said the
opposition groups want a two-sided negotiating table and a broader
agenda.
   ``We do not want to negotiate on concrete issues but on the
political rules of the game,'' he said.
   Magyar said the talks would have to include a new law on
political parties and a new constitution as well as the reforms
needed before the June 1990 vote, which is to give voters a choice
of parties for the first time in 40 years.
   According to the daily newspaper Magyar Nemzet and a communique
distributed by the state-run news agency MTI, the opposition groups
called on the Communist leadership to make a new proposal within 48
hours.
   Central Committee secretary Gyoergy Fejti told Hungarian
television he was surprised by the opposition's swift negative
reply.
</TEXT>
