<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--ShipSeized     05-11 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Ship Seized,0152</SECOND>
<UNK>Coast Guard Seizes Russian Vessel Near `Doughnut Hole'</UNK>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard seized a Soviet fishing
vessel caught with its nets in the water inside the U.S. 200-mile
fishery limit, authorities say.
   A Coast Guard cutter patrolling near an international fishing
zone in the Bering Sea known as the ``Doughnut Hole'' stopped the
trawler Novoelnya on Tuesday.
   A boarding party found 940 metric tons of pollock on the ship,
Chief Petty Officer Ed Moreth, a Coast Guard spokesman, said
Wednesday.
   The vessel was cited for fishing inside the U.S. zone without a
permit, Moreth said. The Coast Guard said the Novoelnya was four
miles inside the zone.
   The ship was accompanied by two other Soviet trawlers, which
retreated into international waters, Moreth said.
   The vessel was to be taken to Kodiak and turned over to the U.S.
Marshal's office for court proceedings.
</TEXT>
