<FIRST>r a PM-SwastikaFoe     05-11 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swastika Foe,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Dropped Against Man Who Alleges He Painted Over Swastikas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has dismissed criminal mischief
charges against a man who claims he painted over swastikas scrawled
in his apartment building, but city officials maintain his story is
a lie.
   The city housing authority asked Municipal Judge Joseph N. Falbo
to drop the charges against Jack Stahl on Wednesday. If convicted,
Stahl, 59, could have faced six months in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   Stahl said in March that he painted over swastikas in an
elevator and a hallway in his housing project because the authority
had ignored his seven months of complaints.
   A three-member mayoral commission concluded earlier this week
that it would be hard to prove Stahl intentionally damaged the
building. But the panel said a paint expert and a commission member
found no evidence of swastikas.
   ``The truth in this case is that Mr. Stahl fabricated a story in
order to play upon the people's fears of ethnic hatred to justify
his own actions,'' Mayor Robert Menendez said Wednesday.
   ``Furthermore, Mr. Stahl took advantage of the media's
sensitivity to such divisive issues by using the swastika _ one of
humanity's most horrible symbols of vicious hate and violent crimes
_ as a shield to protect himself from further prosecution.''
   Stahl does not have a telephone and could not be reached for
comment.
</TEXT>
