<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0852EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LostBomb-Witness     05-11 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lost Bomb-Witness,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailor Recalls Accidental Loss Of H-bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a Navy jet carrying a hydrogen bomb rolled
off an aircraft carrier into the Pacific Ocean, William Lane feared
he and others aboard the Ticonderoga were moments away from death.
   ``They were very nervous minutes,'' Lane said, recalling the
long-suppressed accident, which happened in 1965 about 80 miles off
a Japanese island and 200 miles from Okinawa. The bomb mounted
under the A-4 Skyhawk jet was lost in 16,000 feet of water.
   ``At the time, my feelings were that if that atomic bomb goes
off, this is all going to be vapor _ we're just going to disappear
off the face of the Earth,'' he said in an interview in Wednesday's
The (San Diego) Tribune.
   The pilot and plane also were lost despite the desperate efforts
of sailors who clawed at the single-seat attack jet to try to keep
it from rolling off the deck.
   ``The word was passed that they would appreciate it _ they
didn't say don't or anything else _ if you didn't mention it in
your letters home and just kind of kept it quiet,'' Lane said. ``In
those days, you more or less did everything you were told. There
was a great deal of patriotism on that ship.''
   The Pentagon confirmed the accident earlier this week, and
government officials have told Japan they don't know of any danger
posed by the one-megaton H-bomb, which they said had not been armed.
   Lane, a resident of Santee in San Diego County, was a
20-year-old bomb handler on the Ticonderoga at the time.
   The carrier was on a break from war duty and holding a
nuclear-weapons loading exercise, he said. Lane said the pilot had
climbed into the cockpit when the carrier listed, sending the jet
rolling backward.
   ``We saw (the pilot) look at the handlers as if to say, `There
are no brakes,' or, `I can't reach them,' or something like that,''
Lane said.
   When the plane hit the water, the bomb separated from the
fuselage, Lane said. ``(It) was bobbing around with smoke coming
out of it _ probably from the batteries,'' before it sank, he said.
   The Ticonderoga on which Lane served was decommissioned in 1973.
Another ship now carries the name.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
