<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-US     05-11 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-US,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Communist In Slaying of U.S. Colonel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested a Communist
rebel in connection with the killing last month of an American
colonel, the military said today.
   Col. Ramsey Ocampo, provincial commander on the Bataan
peninsula, said Ricardo Prestosa, 29, was arrested Wednesday at his
home in Dinalupihan, about 40 miles west of Manila.
   No charges have been filed, Ocampo said.
   Manila newspapers quoted military sources as saying Prestosa was
one of two rebels sought in the April 21 slaying of Col. James
``Nick'' Rowe.
   Communist rebels claimed responsibility for the slaying, citing
U.S. ``interference'' in the government's counterinsurgency
campaign.
   Rowe, 51, of McAllen, Texas, was a Vietnam War hero whose book,
``Five Years to Freedom,'' detailed his five years of imprisonment
by the Viet Cong and his escape.
   Rowe was gunned down on his way to work in Quezon City at the
Joint U.S. Military Assistance Group, which provides training and
logistical support to the Philippine military.
   Ocampo said Prestosa denied involvement in the killing and
claimed he was working elsewhere at the time.
   Ocampo said intelligence officers do not believe Prestosa was
directly involved in the attack on Rowe but is ``in the know''
about details of the killing.
   He added that Prestosa is a political officer of the banned
Communist Party of the Philippines. Communist rebels have been
fighting to overthrow the government since 1969.
   Prestosa was arrested in 1983, but subversion charges against
him were dropped. He was arrested again last December but was
released without charge.
