<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugPolicy     05-11 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Policy,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorneys Criticize Plan Requiring Drug Offenders to Name Suppliers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   County judges have enacted a policy
requiring drug offenders to name their suppliers or face additional
time in jail for contempt.
   Some defense attorneys say the measure is unconstitutional.
   ``Forced and coerced information is suspect, unreliable and
potentially dangerous. It raises serious constitutional
questions,'' said Herb Moncier.
   The policy violates the Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination ``because it could indirectly be used to produce
additional charges against the defendant,'' said Bob Ritchie,
another defense attorney.
   Knox County's three Criminal Court judges adopted the measure
Friday at the suggestion of Scott Dean, chairman of the area's
Metropolitan Drug Commission.
   At least one judge said he would use the policy immediately. In
addition, a Juvenile Court judge agreed to use the policy, Dean
said.
   The policy is modeled after one in Columbus, Neb., which is used
with juvenile offenders, he said.
   Under the program, people convicted of drug offenses can be
jailed for contempt of court for not naming their suppliers.
   Anyone who wants to plead guilty in exchange for a lesser
sentence will be told of the policy. If the defendant refuses to
name the supplier, the judge may reject the plea agreement, said
Criminal Court Judge Randy Nichols.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
