<HEAD>Troops Kill Teen-Ager; Fourth Day of Curfew in Gaza</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to clarify that not many clashes today. Pickup
3rd graf, `Yediot Ahronot...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops killed a 17-year-old Palestinian
and wounded three others today, Arab reports said. The army
confined 700,000 Palestinians to their homes in the Gaza Strip for
a fourth day.
   The teen-ager was reported killed in a stone-throwing clash that
erupted as Palestinians staged a general strike in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip in memory of their brethren killed in the
17-month-old rebellion against Israeli rule. At least 470
Palestinians and 21 Israelis have died in the uprising.
   Yediot Ahronot, a daily newspaper, reported that Transport
Minister Moshe Katsav of the right-wing Likud bloc plans to urge
that troops seal off the occupied territories for three months and
quash the uprising.
   A more conciliatory approach came from former Israeli President
Efraim Katzir, who today suggested not ruling out peace talks with
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``I wouldn't hasten to do it,'' Katzir told Israel radio in
discussing President Yitzhak Shamir's proposals to hold elections
in the occupied territories and negotiate a peace settlement with
victors. ``Only if it (the election plan) fails, other paths shourvision
of the
balloting.
   Israeli leaders reportedly have been unable to come up with a
complete formula for the balloting.
   Among other problems, Shamir opposes participation of the
140,000 Palestinians of east Jerusalem in elections, said his
spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir.
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres and Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin
of Labor want east Jerusalemites to join the balloting to make the
election plan more appealing to Palestinians, said a government
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Shamir presided over state affairs today from Jerusalem's
Hadassah Medical Center, where he underwent a battery of tests,
doctors said.
   Presidential spokesman Avi Pazner said the 73-year-old Likud
leader had complained of ``weariness and weakness,'' but he refused
to be precise about his condition. Doctors said Shamir would be
released Friday.
   In the Gaza Strip, violence persisted despite a 4-day-old
curfew. Sixty-year-old Farhana Hassan Kawarea was struck in the
head by a bullet in a clash with soldiers in Khan Yunis, Arab
hospital officials said. She was reported in moderate condition.
   In the West Bank town of Hebron, soldiers fired at rock-throwing
youths, fatally shooting Salmi Ibrahim Abu Kaff, 17, in the chest,
hospital officials said.
   Two Palestinians were reported wounded in the Gaza Strip refugee
camp of Nuseirat and the West Bank village of Beita.
   The army said it was checking casualty reports.
   A spokesman also announced that troops captured a group of
Palestinians suspected of making homemade guns to shoot at
soldiers. They were arrested at the West Bank refugee camp of
Dheishe.
   The military said they were alerted when a group member suffered
a fatal gunshot wound April 15 when a makeshift pistol went off.
The spokesman said that at the time, Palestinians claimed soldiers
shot the man.
   In southern Israel today, several dozen angry Israelis staged a
protest on a main highway north of the Gaza Strip over the alleged
kidnapping and killing of soldiers by Palestinians.
   Earlier this week, soldiers discovered the body of one soldier
in the area and a search continued for another soldier missing for
eight days. Authorities alleged the soldiers were kidnapped by
Palestinians.
