<FIRST>r a PM-AerostatDamaged     05-11 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aerostat Damaged,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swirling `Dust Devil' Damages, Deflates Radar Balloon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIERRA VISTA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swirling wind deflated and damaged a
mammoth, $18 million radar balloon used to detect drug smuggling
across the Mexican border, but the Customs Service says radar
coverage continues.
   The Aerostat was damaged Wednesday while moored at the Fort
Huachuca Army base, said Customs spokesman Charles Conroy. A dust
devil, or mini tornado, struck the helium balloon, which has
sophisticated look-down radar, he said.
   The 6{-ton balloon crashed to the ground. No one was injured and
there was no damage to other property.
   The extent of damage to the balloon was not immediately known,
but Conroy said, ``Certainly it can function again. I'm pretty sure
of that.''
   A second Aerostat is at Deming, N.M., with another scheduled to
go into operation at Yuma in Arizona next month. The Customs
Service plans six over the Southwest and four over the Caribbean.
   Partial overlapping coverage provided by the Aerostat in Deming
plus radar at military installations, air traffic control sites and
Customs ground and airborne stations will help make up for the
downed balloon, Conroy said.
   The Aerostat, deployed in June, is 245 feet long and 72 feet in
diameter with a hull of high-tech, highly resistant, thin materials.
   The Aerostat was moored close to the ground because of strong
wind before the accident, Conroy said, and there was speculation
debris in the dust devil damaged the balloon.
</TEXT>
