<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan     05-11 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita Trying to Persuade Ito to Succeed Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita met senior
statesman Masayoshi Ito today but failed to persuade the
reform-minded politician to succeed him when he steps down over an
influence-peddling scandal, sources said.
   Local news reports said Takeshita and Ito, a former foreign
minister, are at odds over Ito's call for an end to party factions.
Ito, in naming his terms for leading the scandal-tainted party and
becoming Japan's next prime minister, also has demanded the
resignations of all party officials connected to corruption cases.
   After meeting more than three hours today, the two Liberal
Democratic Party leaders said their discussions focused on reform
of the party, whose popular support has been deeply eroded by the
so-called Recruit scandal.
   ``My feeling has not changed,'' Ito said. ``I believe Mr.
Takeshita hasn't got a good impression'' of the conditions under
which he would accept the country's top post.
   Though Takeshita was expected to ask Ito to accept the party
presidency, he told reporters after the meeting: ``We entered
today's talks after confirming between each other that I'm not in a
position to make any request today.''
   Takeshita leads the largest of six major factions that make up
the Liberal Democratic Party. Balancing factional strength is an
important factor in determining appointments to the Cabinet and has
become a widely accepted feature of the ruling party organization.
Political fundraising _ a key issue in the current scandal _ is a
major part of factional competition.
   The discredited prime minister has admitted receiving more than
$1 million in donations from the information conglomerate Recruit
Co. and announced April 25 he will resign to take responsibility
for the loss of public trust.
   ``Revolutionary changes in the party's way of thinking are
needed,'' Itotold reporters Tuesday.
   Ito, 75 and diabetic, has rejected a series of informal offers
to replace Takeshita, citing his age and poor health. But party
leaders appear ready to negotiate with him because he is one of a
handful of senior politicians untainted by the scandal, which also
involved insider trading.
   Three of Takeshita's Cabinet ministers have resigned and 14
businessmen and ex-bureaucrats have been arrested for bribery or
other charges related to the affair.
