<FIRST>r w PM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0441 05-11 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Says it is Reserving Military Aid Option in Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Updates with 7 grafs, pics up 2nd graf pvs, If it..., cuts last
6 grafs to edit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the U.S. observer team that
visited Panama said today there are ``disturbing parallels''
between Panama before last weekend's election and the voting
scheduled for next February in Nicaragua.
   ``Having just returned from Panama our reflections are fresh,
and the lessons we have drawn have important applicability to
develoments in Nicaragua,'' Keith E. Schuette told the privately
financed Commission on Free and Fair Elections in Nicaragua.
   Schuette is president of the National Republican Institute for
International Affairs, which, with its Democratic counterpart,
sponsored the Panama observer team headed by former Presidents
Carter and Ford. The balloting was branded as fraudulent by
observers and the Bush administration.
   ``Our experience in observing a variety of elections around the
world is that the quality and intention of an electoral law is but
one element of the critical determinants of whether an election
will be free and fair,'' Schuette said. ``The other two points of
analysis are the caliber and organization of the opposition and the
over-all organization of government.''
   ``There are disturbing parallels, too frequent to be considered
accidental, between these three elements in the cases of Nicaragua
and Panama,'' he said.
   ``My own analysis of the current environment _ and I should note
that the Republican institute has just concluded a seminar in
Managua with opposition parties on the electoral process _ is that
sufficient freedom of organization, expression and activity does
not currently exist to ensure a free and fair election,'' he said.
   On Wednesday, an official of the National Security Council said
the Bush administration reserves the right to seek renewed military
aid to the Contra rebels if the Sandinista regime holds power by
fraudulent means in next year's election.
   ``If it is perceived that they have stolen the election, then
our policy subsequently will reflect that,'' NSC Counselor Peter
Rodman told the conservative-backed Commission on Free and Fair
Elections in Nicaragua.
   ``The wider this perception, then the stronger consensus there
will be for an appropriate policy afterward,'' Rodman said.
   The official was asked his reaction to the testimony of Senate
Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas, who told the privately funded
group on Tuesday he would favor ``significant military aid'' to the
Contras if Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega fails to hold free
elections as promised.
   ``I have nothing to add to what was part of the bipartisan
accord a couple of months ago, that the administration does reserve
the right to ask for such aid in the future if circumstances
change,'' Rodman said. ``That's not part of our present policy, but
the administration has not given away its future right to ask for
such things if it seems appropriate.''
   The bipartisan agreement, reached in the face of congressional
resistance to administration requests for immediate military aid to
the Contras, calls for continued non-lethal aid only.
   Asked by former Sen. Gaylord Nelson, D-Wis., commission
co-chairman, what U.S. policy would be if a fair election resulted
in an Ortega victory, Rodman replied: ``I hesitate to prejudge
everything we would do. I think there is a presumption that if
there is a fair election and we accept it as a fair election, that
makes a big difference in our attitude toward Nicaragua and
certainly our policy.''
   Carl Gershman, president of the National Endowment for
Democracy, a private grant-making organization that receives an
appropriation from Congress, testified that the Nicaraguan election
process ``will not work, and indeed will be a farce, if there is
not concerted effort by the Central American presidents and by
others who are concerned about the situation to insist upon fair
rules.''
   ``So far, the fear is that there have been certain cosmetic
steps that have been taken, perhaps to improve the standing of the
government in Europe and elsewhere, but that there has not been any
real effort to sit down and establish an agreement,'' Gershman
said. ``Unless there is agreement on rules, it will undermine the
legitimacy of the whole process.''
   Elections are to be held in Nicaragua next February under an
agreement Managua made with the governments of Costa Rica, El
Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras.
</TEXT>
