<SECOND>PM-Second Abduction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0541,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sims Buries Child, Faces Grand Jury</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with woman arriving for grand jury
appearance; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Police say ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose daughters died three years
apart under mysterious circumstances arrived at court today to
appear before a grand jury, one day after burying the second infant
next to the firstborn's unmarked grave.
   Paula and Robert Sims are the primary suspects in the
suffocation of Heather Sims, whom they reported abducted on April
29, investigators said. Their firstborn, Loralei, died under nearly
identical circumstances.
   Mrs. Sims, 29, and four relatives arrived at the Madison County
courthouse in Edwardsville today to face a grand jury. Her husband,
37, was not subpoenaed.
   Police say Sims told them that he believed his wife accidentally
killed Heather and Loralei.
   The Simses, accompanied by more than a dozen family members,
attended a private half-hour funeral service for Heather on
Wednesday at the First Baptist Church in Bethalto.
   The infant, whose body was found in a trash can on the Missouri
side of the Mississippi River on May 3, was buried in nearby
Woodland Hills Cemetery.
   Two police detectives stood about 150 feet from the cemetery
where they shot photographs and scribbled notes.
   At the church, the Rev. Charles West urged reporters and
photographers to stay far away from the building ``out of respect
for the baby.''
   Heather's body was in a tiny white coffin, and an employee of
the Gray Funeral Home in Wood River served as the lone pallbearer.
The Simses held hands as they walked into the church.
   Cemetery manager Bill Helvie said the Simses requested that
Heather be buried next to the unmarked grave of their firstborn
daughter, Loralei, who was 13 days old when they reported her
abducted on June 17, 1986.
   The Simses seem ``just like normal parents to me,'' Helvie said
as he dug Heather's grave Wednesday morning. ``That's why it's hard
to believe all that's going on.''
   Helvie recalled that the Simses visited the other child's grave
several times and put flowers there.
   Remains believed to be Loralei's were found near the Simses'
home in nearby Brighton _ where the couple was living at the time _
about a week after the couple reported her abducted.
   The case was never solved, though the couple are suspects in her
death also, Jersey County authorities said.
   The Simses' attorney, Donald E. Groshong of Alton, had no
comment Wednesday. He said earlier that the Simses denied any
wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
