<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FDA-Corruption 2ndLd-Writethru a0598 05-11 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FDA-Corruption, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0598,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Generic-Drug Co. Chief Accuses FDA of Retaliating for Bribery Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 6th graf, FDA spokesman, with agency reax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a generic-drug company told
Congress today that the Food and Drug Administration is retaliating
against his company for having started an investigation into
alleged bribery at the agency.
   Roy McKnight, chairman of Mylan Laboratories in Pittsburgh,
testified to a a House investigations subcommitttee that the FDA is
holding up approvals of the company's products because ``this was
one way to retaliate.''
   ``Discriminatory treatment or wholly unjustified inaction
continues to be the rule rather than the exception'' at the FDA's
generic drug division, McKnight said.
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., the subcommittee chairman, said he
will inform FDA Commissioner Frank Young personally ``that any
retaliation by any FDA employee against the firms or individuals
who testify before us will not be tolerated.''
   Dingell also said he will ask Young to explain the steps he will
take to assure that Mylan and other companies testifying before the
subcommittee will not be discriminated against by the FDA.
   FDA spokesman Jeff Nesbit said of the retaliation charge, ``No
one has had a chance to look into that.'' He also said the agency
has asked the inspector general for the Department of Health and
Human Services to audit the management and supervisory practices of
the generic drug division.
   Nearly a year ago, McKnight took his complaints about arbitrary
and discriminatory treatment by FDA generic-drug officials and his
allegation that bribes and payoffs were being accepted by FDA
employees to the House Energy and Commerce investigations
subcommittee.
   The panel began an inquiry and turned over its evidence to the
U.S. attorney's office in Baltimore for a criminal investigation.
   So far, two FDA employees and a drug company executive have been
charged in a wide-ranging investigation. More charges are expected.
   ``You would think that news like this and the increased scrutiny
the division has faced as a result of this subcommittee's
investigation would produce a new atmosphere at the generic-drug
division,'' McKnight said. ``On the contrary, the agency's response
has been business as usual.''
   McKnight said his company has been trying for more than 18
months to get FDA approval to make several drug products at its new
plant in Puerto Rico. The company already has approval to make the
drugs at its Morgantown, W.Va., plant, he said.
   He said the company was told by an FDA employee ``that we would
never get approvals for Puerto Rico.'' The employee, Walter Kletch,
appeared before the subcommittee under subpoena last week but
exercised his Fifth Amendment right and declined to answer any
questions.
   Investigators have said that while the investigation has turned
up serious problems with the FDA's process for approving generic
drugs, they have found no evidence that unsafe or ineffective drugs
have been put on the market.
   Generic drug sales amount to $8.9 billion annually.
   On Wednesday, Charles Y. Chang, a former generic-drug division
supervisor who has been charged with taking bribes, said in an
affidavit submitted to the subcommittee that favoritism was common
in the division.
   Special handling of applications resulted partly from pressure
by the larger, more sophisticated companies, said Chang, a key
figure in the investigation.
   Favoritism that helped speed the processing of applications, he
said, ``was not necessarily the result of illegal behavior, but
reflected, in part, highly personal, arbitrary and often arrogant
management.''
   He also referred in the document to examples of special
treatment and said they ``were the result of continuous pressure
put on the division, at all levels, by the industry through
lobbying, conducted by executives, lawyers, consultants, and
occasionally through political channels inside and outside the
FDA.''
   Chang was charged earlier this week in U.S. District Court in
Baltimore with two counts of interstate travel in aid of
racketeering. He was accused of accepting a free trip to Hong Kong
and furniture as bribes from American Therapeutics Inc., a Bohemia,
N.Y., generic drug manufacturer.
   He has agreed to plead guilty and has been cooperating with
investigators, said his attorney, Barry Leibowitz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
