<FIRST>u a PM-DupontPlaza-Settlement     05-11 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dupont Plaza-Settlement,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>$100 Million Settlement Reached in San Juan Hotel Blaze, Lawyers
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The DuPont Plaza Hotel in San Juan, Puerto Rico, has agreed to
pay about $100 million to settle lawsuits stemming from the New
Year's Eve 1986 fire that killed 97 people, newspapers reported
today.
   The Telegram of Bridgeport, Conn., and The Hartford (Conn.)
Courant attributed the figure to unidentified sources today.
   The Star Tribune of Minneapolis quoted James Fetterly, a
Minneapolis lawyer for the hotel, as saying the settlement would be
substantially less than the $200 million in settlements from the
1980 MGM Hotel fire in Las Vegas.
   A former hotel maintenance worker pleaded guilty to setting the
DuPont Plaza fire during a labor dispute at the 22-story hotel,
which was packed with almost 1,000 tourists. More than 140 people
were injured.
   About 2,300 plaintiffs sued for a total of $1.8 billion. The
hotel was cited for 25 violations by the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration, including lack of emergency exits from the
casino, where 84 victims died.
   Richard Bieder, whose Bridgeport law firm represents the
families of the nine Connecticut people killed in the blaze,
confirmed Wednesday that a settlement had been reached, but he
refused to discuss the amount.
   The agreement, reached Tuesday, is subject to approval by two
federal judges, the newspapers said.
   Fettery said if the agreement is approved, about 170 defendants,
including those who provided furnishings and services in the hotel,
still would have claims against them.
</TEXT>
