<FIRST>r a PM-Hightower     05-11 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hightower,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas House Waters Down's Ag Commissioner's Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Agriculture Commissioner Jim
Hightower, under fire for his enforcement of farm chemical rules,
would lose much of his power to regulate pesticide use under
legislation passed by the House today.
   The legislation sets up a pesticide regulatory board headed by
the commissioner, meaning he will be only one of six votes.
   The board, consisting of experts in chemistry, agriculture,
public health and the environment, would take ``emotionalism and
politicism'' out of pesticide regulation, said Rep. Rick Perry, a
Democrat.
   The measure was an amendment to a bill extending the life of the
Agriculture Department. State departments and agencies must undergo
a review every 12 years and are abolished unless the Legislature
decides to keep them.
   The amendment was approved 88-54 on Wednesday after a bitter
debate. The overall bill goes back to the Senate for consideration
of the amendment.
   ``This is an amendment that hurts farmers. It helps chemical
companies. It weakens the pesticide protections of the people of
the state of Texas,'' Hightower said.
   Hightower, a Democrat, has been criticized by some farm and
chemical groups for enforcement of pesticide regulations and for
advocating the sale of hormone-free beef to European countries that
want it.
   The Texas Farm Bureau, the state's biggest agriculture group,
has even urged abolition of the elected commissioner post in favor
of an appointed panel.
   The pesticide board would give the commissioner ``the
intellectual expertise, the scientific expertise'' to make
pesticide decisions, Perry said.
</TEXT>
