<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EPANominee     05-11 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EPA Nominee,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Habicht Pledges to Act Against Polluters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Justice Department official, once the
target of Environmental Protection Agency protests that he
undermined cleanup of federal facilities, pledged on Thursday to
take strong steps against U.S. government polluters if he is
confirmed for EPA's No. 2 position.
   F. Henry Habicht II, the deputy administrator-designate, told
the Senate Environment Committee that he would be an ``aggressive
advocate'' to see that federal facilities ``meet or exceed''
anti-pollution measures in the private sector.
   As chief of the Justice Department's Land and Natural Resources
division, Habicht in 1986 and 1987 admittedly helped write the
Reagan administration policy that forced EPA to negotiate with U.S.
government polluters, instead of handing them orders to clean up
their pollution.
   Internal EPA memos at the time called the plan ``unlawful''
because it was more lenient toward government than private
polluters, and warned the double standard could ``severely damage''
EPA's credibility.
   In more recent interviews, EPA officials said the policy has
allowed the Defense and Energy departments to stall negotiations
involving their facilities, thereby delaying agreements to clean up
some of the nation's worst pollution sites.
   Asked at his confirmation hearing how he would enforce federal
cleanup, Habicht said, ``We in the federal government have to do
what is necessary to bring the federal agencies in compliance. If
that involves ... the administrative enforcement process, I would
support that kind of action.''
   He said in disputes among federal agencies, EPA must be able to
``call the shots.''
   Under questioning from Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., Habicht
acknowledged he could not speak for the White House on federal
facilities cleanup, testifying, ``This is my personal position. I
can't say whether that's the administration's position.''
   But Habicht said federal agencies are more willing than before
to clean up their facilities, and singled out Energy Secretary
James D. Watkins as one who is interested in a strong environmental
program.
   He promised the Bush administration will ``formulate and
communicate to Congress'' a program to bring federal facilities
into compliance with anti-pollution laws.
   Habicht went to work after 1987 for a private consulting firm
headed by former EPA Administrator William D. Ruckelshaus. He is
now at EPA, with the title of consultant to EPA Administrator
William K. Reilly.
</TEXT>
