<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     05-11 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senior Cabinet Minister to Resign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 6 p.m. EDT _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet minister in charge
of largely unsuccessful efforts to draw black leaders into
negotiations announced his resignation Thursday.
   Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis gave no reason
for his decision, announced a week after he made a ground-breaking
speech in Parliament proposing that blacks be given a role in
Parliament, in the Cabinet and in the selection of a president.
   On Wednesday, another senior Cabinet member and National Party
leader, Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha, announced his
resignation, saying he wanted to return to private life. Botha has
overseen the enforcement of press censorship during the 3-year-old
state of emergency.
   Heunis, the leader of the governing National Party in Cape
Province, will resign from the Cabinet on July 1. Botha, the party
leader in Natal Province, will resign Sept. 6, when a general
election is scheduled.
   There will be at least six vacancies on the 17-member Cabinet
when it meets after the election, providing an opportunity for a
major overhaul by F.W. de Klerk, the favorite to succeed P.W. Botha
as president. Heunis unsuccessfully competed against de Klerk in
February for the position of National Party leader.
   Two ministers of agriculture and economic affairs previously
announced they would not seek re-election, and the minister of
manpower quit after being linked to allegations of financial
impropriety. De Klerk's portfolio as national education minister
also probably will be vacant.
   Heunis, 62, joined Parliament in 1970 and has been a close
associate of P.W. Botha during the president's 11 years in power.
Heunis often was mentioned as a possible successor to Botha, but
political commentators said his chances were hurt by his lack of
progress in persuading prominent blacks leader to enter
negotiations about power-sharing.
   Some blacks were deterred by the government's insistence the
white minority retain veto power over major decisions made in any
new form of government. Other blacks say they will enter
negotiations only if jailed African National Congress leader Nelson
Mandela is freed and bans on militant black groups are lifted.
   Heunis announced this week that a group of black mayors and town
councilors had agreed to begin negotiations on power-sharing. But
the 1988 local election that put these officials in office was
widely boycotted by blacks, and black leaders of national
prominence have shown little interest in the so-called National
Forum.
   Under South Africa's system of apartheid, the 5 million whites
control the government, while the 28 million blacks have no role in
Parliament and no voice in national affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
