<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     05-11 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas' Election Preparations Criticized, Parallels Seen in
Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nominee to be ambassador to
the Organization of American States said Thursday that Nicaragua's
Sandinista government has ``not met what we would consider
standards of legitimacy'' in the first phase of preparations for
elections next year.
   ``There were in fact no direct negotiations between the
Sandinistas and the internal opposition groups over the content of
the reforms that were to be made,'' Luigi Einaudi, director of
policy planning for the State Department's Bureau of Inter-American
Affairs, testified at a hearing.
   ``Rather, these were in effect imposed by the Sandinistas,''
Einaudi said.
   Einaudi was among final witnesses in three days of hearings by
the Commission on a Free and Fair Election in Nicaragua, a
bipartisan panel supported by private donations that will come up
with suggested guidelines for the February balloting. The
commission was established by the conservative World Freedom
Foundation.
   The commission also heard from Keith E. Schuette, president of
the National Republican Institute for International Affairs, which,
with its Democratic counterpart, sponsored the Panamanian election
observation team headed by former Presidents Carter and Ford.
   After observing the elections in that country, Schuette said,
``the lessons we have drawn have important applicability to
developments in Nicaragua.''
   ``Our experience ... is that the quality and intention of an
electoral law is but one element of the critical determinants of
whether an election will be free and fair,'' he testified. ``The
other two points of analysis are the caliber and organization of
the opposition and the overall organization of government.''
   ``There are disturbing parallels, too frequent to be considered
accidental, between these three elements in the cases of Nicaragua
and Panama,'' he said.
   He said he had concluded that ``sufficient freedom of
organization, expression and activity does not currently exist to
ensure a free and fair election'' in Nicaragua.
   That view was echoed by Einaudi, who said the United States was
``very concerned'' that the first stage of preparations for the
election ``has in fact not met what we would consider standards of
legitimacy.''
   He said the Sandinistas appeared to have shown ``a complete
unwillingness to open the system further'' when they empowered
President Daniel Ortega to name all five members of an electoral
commission made up of two Sandinista members, two opposition
members and a neutral member.
   Ortega's naming of a neutral member in reality will make the
commission ``an automatic Sandinista rubber stamp,'' Einaudi said.
   He added, however, that he is ``cautiously optimistic'' that the
Sandinistas may make changes to make the electoral system more
palatable.
   Curtin Winsor, former Reagan administration ambassador to Costa
Rica and co-chairman of the commission, said that although Einaudi
is the ambassador-designate to the OAS he was testifying in his
current State Department capacity.
   The Nicaraguan elections are to be held under an agreement
Managua made with the governments of Costa Rica, El Salvador,
Guatemala and Honduras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
