<FIRST>r a AM-SmellyGrain     05-11 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smelly Grain,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Claim Grain Fumes Killed Loved One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARGO, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foul-smelling gases from two rancid grain
piles near a grain elevator caused the death of a 24-year-old
pregnant woman who lived nearby, according to a lawsuit filed by
her family.
   Renee Oland, who was seven months pregnant, died in September
1987 from an accumulation of fluid in her lungs, according to the
lawsuit filed in federal court in Fargo.
   Mrs. Oland lived in Lidgerwood less than 200 yards from two huge
grain piles maintained by Harvest States Cooperative of St. Paul,
Minn., the lawsuit said. The piles were begun in 1986 after the
company's elevator ran out of space.
   David Karpinski, a spokesman for Harvest States in St. Paul,
declined comment on the lawsuit Thursday.
   The grain piles were drenched by rain before they were covered
and began to spoil, according to the lawsuit. Residents of
Lidgerwood, in North Dakota's southeastern corner 60 miles south of
Fargo, began to complain of the odor in the summer of 1987.
   Harvest States removed most of the grain later that year.
   The lawsuit maintains the odor from the spoiling grain caused
medical complications that led to the death of Mrs. Oland and her
fetus, according to Galen Vaa, a Moorhead, Minn., attorney
representing the family.
   Storing grain outdoors and using chemicals to cut spoilage is
``an abnormally dangerous business activity,'' said the lawsuit,
filed by Mrs. Oland's father, husband and surviving son.
</TEXT>
