<FIRST>u w PM-US-Panama 8thLd-Writethru   05-11 1270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama, 8th Ld-Writethru,a0651,a0653,a0657,1200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Ordering Troops To Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines urgent series, edits and updates with military units,
deletes older military information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today decided to order up to
3,000 U.S. military troops to Panama and evacuate some American
dependents from that volatile country, informed sources said. He
urged allied nations to condemn Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega for
election fraud.
   Adminstration sources said the Pentagon was preparing to sending
the troops from two bases, Fort Ord, Calif., and Fort Polk, La. The
sources said one group of about 1,000 would be dispatched
immediately from the 7th Light Infantry Division from Fort Ord. The
other, he said, would be drawn from the 5th Infantry Divsion at
Fork Polk and would not arrive in Panama ``for days'' because that
is a mechanized infantry division and the men and their equipment
will be transported by ship.
   The actions would beef up the 10,000-strong U.S. troop strength
in Panama with additional forces as one of a series of actions in
response to the nullification of the Panamanian election results by
Noriega and the post-election violent attacks against opposition
politicians, said the sources who had knowledge of Bush's decision.
   In addition, some of the dependents of U.S. personnel in Panama
were to be returned to the United States while others were being
relocated for safety reasons from Panama City and other locations
to the U.S. bases in Panama, a source said.
   Further, Bush was continuing talks with leaders of Latin
countries to support various intiatives they were undertaking in
the aftermath of what many condemned as an election blatantly
rigged by Noriega, officials said.
   For example, the president backed the call by Venezuela for an
urgent meeting of the Organization of American States, the sources
said.
   ``The president is going to take a whole series of actions,''
said one administration official who spoke on condition of
anonymity. The official characterized the moves as ``prudent
measures to asure the safety of Americans and assuare the United
States can fulfill its commitment to the Panama Canal treaties.''
   Earlier today, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush
had ordered U.S. military forces to prepare for possible
deployment, as he weighed a series of options against Panama, where
rioters attacked opposition leaders.
   ``Our miltary forces that are involved are being readied for any
possible changes in their status,'' White House Press Secretary
Marlin Fitzwater said in describing the administration stance a day
after Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega nullified elections that U.S.
officials condemned as fraudulent.
   ``We have an obligation to the safety and security of the U.S.
citizens in Panama and we have substantial military commitments in
that country. We intend to meet our obligations.''
   ``There are also steps to be taken on the diplomatic front,'' he
sid.
   The spokesman would not elaborate on U.S. plans. Bush scheduled
an announcement later in the day to announce his plans.
   ``Panama's electoral tribunal last night perpetrated the
ultimate electoral theft in nullifying the elections,'' Fitzwater
said.
   He said Bush and the State Department today were ``conferring
with leaders of Latin American countries'' on the actions he plans
to take. ``We know they share our concern and that shared interest
moves us to define the course of actions that will protect American
citizens in Panama and register our intention to stand up for
democracy in the wake of Sunday's fraudulent election,'' Fitzwater
said.
   The spokesman said U.S. objectives in Panama were to protect the
51,000 American citizens living there, to maintain the terms of the
Panama Canal treaties, maintain U.S. interest in its defense
establishments in that country and promote democracy and the rights
of the Panamanian people.
   Fitzwater also decried the Soviet position stated in the news
agency Tass that Panama was justified in nullifying the election.
The spokesman said that ``tends to throw cold water'' on the Soviet
talk of a new openness.
   Congressional leaders who attended a strategy session with the
president predicted there would be near unanimous support on
Capitol Hill for Bush's decisions.
   ``The president is proposing constructive steps in concert with
other countries,'' said Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif. ``The
president and his people are still consulting with leaders of other
countries that are concerned.''
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., described Bush's
measures as ``preliminary,'' adding: ``Who knows what may happen
tomorrow, or the next day, or next week. That will depend on the
conduct of Noriega.''
   House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., said the American
response ``has got to be something more than just something
symbolic. You either mean business or you don't.''
   House Speaker Jim Wright told reporters after the White House
session, that Bush, ``expressed the absolute determination to
protect American lives. In that we certainly do support him.''
   Ambassador Arthur Davis, concerned for the safety of the
Americans, asked the 152 dependents of diplomats to move to
military bases, and embassy spokeswoman Cynthia Farrell said from
Panama that the move was underway.
   Cranston said it would be ``leaping to a conclusion'' to assume
the U.S. actions would involve military response, although Pentagon
officials said earlier that Bush was ``leaning toward'' beefing up
the U.S. forces in Panama.
   ABC News reported that Bush planned to send 3,000 U.S. troops to
Panama and was working toward a joint measure with Latin allies.
   Pentagon officials who asked not to be identified told The
Associated Press the Defense Department has been told Bush ``is
leaning toward'' deployment of 2,000 to 2,500 combat troops to
Panama to reinforce the American military presence there. But the
sources stressed today that no final decision had been made and
that no ``execute order'' had been received.
   ``It looks like its going to go that way; sending down some more
troops,'' the source said. ``But there is nothing definite and
we're not saddling up the ntire 82nd Airborne.''
   Administration sources said the 5th Infantry Division units will
probably be dispatched with armored personnel carriers and only a
small number of tanks. One official said a mechanized force would
be sent as a precaution in case the situation deterioriates and
additional protection is needed to help dependents evacuate.
   The sources also disclosed that a ``very small'' unit from the
Marine Corps at Camp Lejeune, N.C., might be dispatched via ship
transport, but declined to elaborate.
   And the officials further noted that Bush had the option of
ordering an aircraft carrier battle group to the region. By sheer
coincidence, the carrier America and six escorts departed Norfolk,
Va., and two other ports Thursday, bound for a routine deployment
in the Mediterranean Sea.
   ``The group was told to stay loose, they might have to hang a
right turn,'' said one official.
   The America battle group's deployment was planned months ago and
its departure announced publicly last Monday.
   One military official called the plan ``a show of force that is
being orchestrated at the White House. We're not sure about the
goals from a military standpoint besides our continuing concern
about American dependents.''
   Rioting broke out in Panama following Sunday's presidential
elections, branded as fraudulent by observers and the Bush
administration. The opposition claimed victory and Noriega tossed
out the election results late Wednesday, hours after armed
civilians mobbed and beat several demonstrators in the streets,
including presidential candidate Guillermo Endara..
   U.S. military forces in Panama are on heightened alert. There
are 10,000 troops based at installations along the 50-mile long
Panama Canal.
   In Panama, tribunal head Yolanda Pulice de Rodriguez blamed the
nullification on ``the obstructionist action by many foreigners,''
alluding to the team of observers Bush sent to monitor the
elections.
</TEXT>
