<FIRST>r a AM-People     05-11 0986</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,1023</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Liza Minnelli has been
charged with smuggling for illegally bringing her dog Lilly into
Sweden, a court clerk said Thursday.
   The cairn terrier had been threatened with arrest and
imprisonment in a kennel last month, but was freed on bail and
deported to France after negotiations with Ms. Minnelli.
   Criminal charges were filed Wednesday in the district court of
Helsingborg, the port where Ms. Minnelli brought in Lilly on a bus
during her world tour with Frank Sinatra and Sammy Davis Jr.
   Ms. Minnelli faces a stiff fine because it normally is pegged to
income, court clerk Ingalill Falkman said. She refused to speculate
on how high it could go.
   ``We regard smuggling of animals very seriously because of the
risk of spreading rabies,'' Ms. Falkman said.
   Ms. Minnelli has denied intentionally violating Sweden's strict
quarantine laws and said she was misinformed.
   No date was set for the trial, which will be held in
Helsingborg, 420 miles south of Stockholm. Ms. Minnelli, who put a
$2,000 deposit with the court before leaving Sweden, was not
expected to attend.
   Customs agents were alerted by an anonymous caller who saw Lilly
sniffing among the gilded chairs at Stockholm's Grand Hotel.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Garrison Keillor, the creator of ``A
Prairie Home Companion,'' is considering a return to Minnesota
Public Radio.
   ``We are talking to him about returning to MPR on a semiregular
basis, but what that is, when and to what extent is very much under
discussion,'' said Chris Langer, public relations director at
Minnesota Public Radio.
   Keillor recently has expressed interest in doing more radio
appearances than his current four or five specials a year.
   ``A Prairie Home Companion'' is a joint property of Keillor and
Minnesota Public Radio. If Keillor wants to resume ``Prairie Home''
broadcasts, it would have to be through MPR. Keillor left the show
in June 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version also moved on the sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben Johnson, world record-holder in the 100-meter
dash, suffered minor injuries in a scuffle with five men early
Thursday, chased one of his alleged assailants and held him until
police arrived.
   Johnson, 27, was treated for a broken tooth and swollen lip.
   Johnson had just left a nightclub and was driving his mother's
car when he slowed to allow some pedestrians to cross the street in
the city's swank Yorkville district. One of the men banged on
Johnson's car, police said.
   When Johnson got out of the car to challenge the men, he was
punched in the face, police said. Another man then jumped on the
hood of the car and kicked in the windshield, causing $700 in
damage.
   The man captured by Johnson, John Cesar, 24, was charged with
mischief over $1,000, said police Sgt. David Donald. Police were
seeking the man who assaulted Johnson.
   Johnson's lawyer said the suspects knew it was Johnson in the
car.
   ``I think what most members of the public don't realize is what
this young man goes through on a daily basis _ the verbal abuse and
the physical harassment,'' Ed Futerman said.
   Johnson was stripped of the gold medal in the 100-meter dash at
the 1988 Olympics after testing positive for a banned anabolic
steroid. He set the 100-meter record of 9.83 seconds in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The success of Barry Manilow's Broadway concert
engagement has forced the Tony Awards to find another theater.
   The awards show, which was scheduled to be broadcast June 4 from
the Gershwin Theater, will now be done from the Lunt-Fontanne
Theater, a spokesman for the Tonys said Thursday. Manilow's concert
engagement at the Gershwin was to have ended May 14 but its
producers extended the show through June 3 because of a strong
demand for tickets.
   The move also means a more pressing demand for tickets to the
event. The Gershwin, the largest Broadway house, has 1,933 seats,
compared with 1,478 for the Lunt-Fontanne.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Judy Davis was growing up in Australia,
she thought it would be fun to be an actress, although hard to make
a living at it.
   After receiving Oscar and Emmy nominations and winning two
British Academy Awards, the star of such films as ``A Passage to
India'' and ``My Brilliant Career'' has found the opposite to be
true.
   ``I thought it was easy, that you got a part and did it,'' said
Miss Davis, currently making her U.S. stage debut in Tom Stoppard's
intellectual thriller ``Hapgood'' in Hollywood. ``I didn't realize
there would be all this agony.
   ``I think the emotional commitment's pretty hard, to take on
someone else's emotional journey or turmoil, to take it inside you
and put yourself through it,'' she said. Perhaps, she said, that's
why actors sometimes seem temperamental to outsiders.
   ``Actors are very vulnerable creatures,'' she said. ``You have
to keep the child alive in you, alive and well.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Miss America Kaye Lani Rae Rafko says a
dying cancer patient inspired her to continue her nursing career
despite offers of acting and modeling jobs.
   ``Nothing has come close to tempting me away from this career,''
Miss Rafko, 25, said Tuesday while visiting north Georgia on a
speaking tour to promote cancer awareness.
   Miss Rafko, who was Miss America 1988, said she entered her
first beauty pageant to win scholarship money that would pay off
her nursing-school loans. But after failing to capture the Miss
Michigan crown, she quit trying.
   A cancer patient named Janie, who had become a good friend,
later persuaded her to try again, she said, and she went on to win
the Miss America crown.
   ``Within four hours after I received the title, Janie died,''
she said, adding that ``she made me promise to enjoy life to its
fullest, but to never forget nursing.''
</TEXT>
