<FIRST>u i PM-Panama 6thLd-Writethru a0635 05-11 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0635,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embassy Dependents Being Moved onto Military Bases; Opposition Defiant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 20 grafs to UPDATE with sources saying Bush to order
troops to Panama; Venezuela calling for OAS meeting. Pickup 23rd pvs, `In
announcing...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAN1,2, LaserColor PAN3, LaserGraphic NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's bloodied opposition leaders
today rejected nullification of presidential elections and clung to
the claim they won the vote. Dependents of U.S. diplomats began
moving onto military bases to ensure their safety, an embassy
spokeswoman said.
   President Bush decided to order additional U.S. military forces
to Panama and evacuate some American dependents from the country,
informed sources in Washington said.
   Panamanian soldiers patrolled the capital, and U.S. personnel
were advised to stay off the streets if possible and to wear only
civilian clothes in public.
   International condemnation of Noriega intensified following
attacks on opposition candidate Guillermo Endara and his two
running mates by bat- and pipe-wielding thugs Wednesday.
   ``We won and we will continue to fight,'' said Guillermo Ford,
the second vice presidential candidate who suffered a beating. He
said Endara ``is still president.''
   Ford said he was taken to Modelo Prison where a judge sentenced
him to a year in jail for inciting riot and attacking soldiers. But
he was freed a few hours later. He had stitches over his left eye
and cheek.
   Ford said the opposition wants to talk with the military but
that would require getting rid of Noriega ``because Panama cannot
have two presidents.''
   Noriega is head of the 15,000-member Defense Forces and the
country's de facto ruler.
   Endara suffered a scalp wound Wednesday requiring eight
stitches. His doctors issued a statement today saying his condition
was stable and there were no neurological complications.
   Soldiers did not interfere during the beatings, which broke out
after troops halted an opposition demonstration to protest what
international observers have called the government's theft of
Sunday's vote.
   Davis and other officials said one of Endara's bodyguards was
killed and about 20 demonstrators injured. The military said four
soldiers were wounded.
   Opponents had hoped to rally international opinion against
Noriega and prevent the proclamation of his hand-picked candidate,
Carlos Duque, as president.
   U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis asked the 152 dependents of
diplomats to move to military bases, and embassy spokeswoman
Cynthia Farrell said the move was under way.
   ``You have these dignity battallions moving around town and
targeting people. We're not sure who they're next targets are going
to be. So rather than leave people exposed to possible attacks by
these roving mobs, they're moving people onto the bases just as a
precaution,'' she said.
   At the Pentagon, officials said the U.S. Southern Command and
Defense Department had not issued similar orders affecting
dependents of servicemen. There are about 14,000 military
dependents in Panama, of whom about 3,100 live away from U.S. bases.
   Sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said Bush planned to
announce he was sending additional U.S. troops to back up the
10,000 American soldiers already in Panama.
   In Moscow, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said Noriega
``has done everything he could to steal that election. And when it
became extraordinarily difficult to accomplish,'' he declared it
null.
   ``Either way you look at it, it is a perversion and a subversion
of the will, the freely expressed will, of the Panamanian people,''
Baker said.
   Spain, Peru, and Argentina today condemned the annulling of the
elections, and Britain demanded that Noriega resign.
   Venezuelan President Carlos Andres Perez for an emergency
meeting of the Organization of American States to consider actions
against Noriega.
   In announcing the nullification, Panama's official electoral
commission cited vote-stealing, vote-buying, missing tally sheets
and international interference in voiding the election. The
commission said nothing about rescheduling the vote.
   More than 300 international observers, including former
President Jimmy Carter, backed opposition claims that Endara won by
a 3-to-1 margin. Official results, however, had shown Duque leading
by about 2-to-1.
   Yolanda Pulice de Rodriguez, head of the Electoral Tribunal,
charged in a nationwide broadcast that the outcome of the vote was
``altered by the obstructionist action by the many foreigners.''
   Bush sent an uninvited U.S. delegation to monitor the elections,
and the CIA reportedly contributed $10 million to the opposition
campaign.
   Washington began its campaign to remove Noriega after he
orchestrated President Eric Delvalle's ouster. Delvalle had tried
to fire Noriega after the general was indicted in Florida on
drug-trafficking charges in February 1988. Noriega denies the drug
charges.
   Noriega claims the United States wants to get rid of him so it
can renege on the Panama Canal treaties, which cede the canal to
Panama by the year 2000.
</TEXT>
