<FIRST>r a AM-Judge-Homosexuals     05-11 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Judge-Homosexuals,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorneys Agree To Make Public Formal Allegations Against Dallas
Judge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for a judge and the state Commission on
Judicial Conduct agreed Thursday to make public the contents of
formal proceedings against the judge stemming from remarks he made
against homosexuals.
   The allegations cite comments state District Judge Jack Hampton
made in December to the Dallas Times Herald and The Associated
Press as well as remarks a court official in Hampton's office
allegedly made to callers protesting his statements.
   The commission charges allege that Hampton's remarks violated
the Code of Judicial Conduct, which prohibits a judge from publicly
commenting on a pending case. Hampton also is charged with
violating the code that requires a judge to conduct himself in a
manner that promotes public confidence in the impartiality of the
judiciary.
   The agreement came during a brief hearing before special master
Robert Murray, a retired judge from San Antonio appointed to handle
the case. Hampton was not present.
   In an interview published in the Dallas Times Herald in
December, Hampton said he gave a lighter sentence to convicted
killer Richard Bednarski, 18, in part because his two victims were
``queers.''
   Bednarski was sentenced to 30 years in prison. He could have
received a maximum life sentence.
   ``I don't care much for queers cruising the streets picking up
teen-age boys,'' Hampton told the newspaper. ``I've got a teen-age
boy.''
   On the same day Hampton's comments were published in the Times
Herald, he told the AP, ``The victims were homosexuals. They were
out in the homosexual area picking up teen-age boys. Had they not
been out there trying to spread AIDS around, they'd still be alive
today.''
   The charges against Hampton also state that when people who had
read the Times Herald report and heard an AP radio network
broadcast called Hampton's office to complain, they were referred
to an attorney's office and told to ``have a gay Christmas.''
   The commission alleges the court officials' response was
``cavalier, disdainful and undignified.''
   The commission announced in February its decision to initiate
formal proceedings against Hampton.
   Murray will report to the 11-member commission, then the panel
could dismiss the complaint, issue a public censure or recommend
the judge's removal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
