<FIRST>r w AM-F-14     05-11 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-F-14,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Navy Will Have 110 Fewer F-14s Than It Says It Needs By
1996</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy will have 110 fewer F-14 fighter
planes than it says it needs by 1996, according to a study released
Thursday by a congressman seeking to save the Grumman-built jet.
   ``No matter how you slice the Bush-Cheney budget, it comes up
dangerously short in Navy aircraft,'' said Rep. George
Hochbrueckner, D-N.Y., who requested the study by the Congressional
Research Service of the Library of Congress.
   The report, described in its introduction as ``a quick, rough
analysis,'' concludes that the Navy will have 417 F-14 Tomcats at
the end of fiscal 1996, 110 fewer than it has said it will need.
   The study assumes there will be an increased demand for F-14s as
two aircraft carriers are converted from airwings which carry no
F-14s to airwings which carry 20 each, and projects a loss of 70
F-14s during the period due to peacetime accidents.
   Battle lines were drawn last month when Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney submitted his fiscal 1990 budget to Congress, which saved
$360 million by cutting orders for 12 new F-14Ds.
   The F-14D is the largest airplane program of the Grumman Corp.
of Bethpage, N.Y., and company officials say if funding is not
restored, it will be forced to lay off 5,600 employees.
