<HEAD>AM-Prom Blues,0446</HEAD>
<HEAD>Girl Sues Prom Date Who Didn't Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old girl who says she was
stood up on prom night now wants to get even: She's suing her date
for $49.53 for her shoes, flowers and hairdo he never got to see.
   Palm Beach Lakes High School junior Marlon Shadd says he called
off the date a week before the dance. And besides, he says, he had
a good excuse.
   ``She didn't believe me when I told her I fractured my ankle,''
Shadd said.
   ``This is so stupid. I'm so sick of all this. I've never heard
anything so disgraceful in my whole life,'' his mother, Joan
Bryant, said Thursday. ``I offered her the money. You know what she
tells me? She tells me the boy has to be punished.''
   The teen-agers appeared Wednesday in Palm Beach County Court
after Tomontra Mangrum's mother filed a claim for the cost of the
shoes, flowers and hairdo. A $280 dress with black and white
ruffles was returned unworn.
   There is some dispute over the facts of the case.
   Ms. Bryant said her 17-year-old son, a high school basketball
player, told Miss Mangrum a week before his school's April 7 formal
that he would be unable to attend because he was on crutches with a
fractured ankle. On prom night, he was out of town seeing a college
recruiter.
   But Miss Mangrum says she was stood up without notice.
   ``I talked to him on April 2 and he said he already had his tux
and the tickets,'' said Miss Mangrum, a Berean Christian School
student. ``I was very upset when he didn't show up.''
   Valerie Mangrum of Royal Palm Beach tried to track down her
daughter's date on prom night.
   ``I called and called and called until I got his mother,'' she
said. ``She was very upset about this.''
   Ms. Bryant can't understand why the broken date has wound up in
court.
   ``The problem is everybody looks to her like she's a poor little
innocent girl,'' she said. ``He's a kid, too. He shouldn't be put
to this shame.''
   The Mangrums are demanding $26 for shoes that couldn't be
returned, $23 for a hairdo and 53 cents for flowers in the
teen-ager's hair. Filing the claim cost $31.75, but if they win the
July trial, Shadd may have to pay that, too.
   ``I don't have any money. I'm poor. Why is she doing this?'' his
mother asked.
   County Judge Howard Berman is taking the case seriously.
   ``The issue is, was there a valid contract? We had an offer and
we had an acceptance,'' Berman said. ``Could she have gotten
another date to the prom?''
</TEXT>
