<HEAD>Man Makes Coast-to-Coast Trip to Become Citizen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marcus Dimagio was determined to
become a U.S. citizen, even though he had to take a whole day off
from work at the last minute and travel more than 6,000 miles by
plane, bus and taxi.
   And he was late.
   The native of Chile arrived in a courtroom panting and trembling
Wednesday just as a judge finished swearing in a group of citizens.
   ``He came in shivering, almost in tears and looking very
exhausted,'' Sonoma County Clerk Eeve Lewis said. ``He was about a
half-hour late and the others had already been sworn in.''
   But Superior Court Judge William Bettinelli rewarded Dimagio's
determination by administering the oath of citizenship to him
individually.
   Lewis said Dimagio applied for citizenship in Sonoma County but
moved to Massachusetts before the Immigration and Naturalization
Service set a date for his naturalization.
   Notice of the ceremony's date was mailed two weeks ago, but
since it was forwarded from Dimagio's old Santa Rosa address to
Boston, he didn't get it until Tuesday.
   Dimagio said he didn't know how to change the location, so he
took the day off from work and headed for Santa Rosa on Wednesday
morning. That meant a plane from Boston to San Francisco, a bus to
Santa Rosa and a taxi to court.
   ``He said his first flight this morning was canceled and the
second flight was two hours late,'' Bettinelli said. ``He said he
had to catch a 6 o'clock flight back home because he had to be at
work Thursday.''
