<FIRST>r a AM-PigDeaths     05-11 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pig Deaths,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Stymied on Pig Deaths, Could It Be Drought Related?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers have been struggling for
more than a year trying to find what malady is killing baby pigs,
and one veterinarian says he believes the deaths may be
drought-related.
   Pathologist George Daniels at the Iowa State University
veterinary diagnostic laboratory said the failure of laboratory
tissue studies to indicate a culprit is a strong point in favor of
his theory the deaths are related to bad feed.
   It is possible the deaths come from poor quality grain
containing toxins being fed to the pigs' mothers, he said.
   ``The dollar cost goes into the millions. It's a tremendous
cost,'' said Daniels.
   He said the number of deaths has increased with the drought and
with the related decline in quality and rise in contamination of
grain. The outbreak in Iowa has been in isolated pockets, not
widespread, and no figures for the number of pig deaths was
available.
   Others believe a virus or a new strain of disease is to blame.
   Gene Erickson of the National Animal Disease Center at Ames said
that while researchers have been unable to pinpoint the cause of
the deaths for more than a year, ``This is not something to panic
about.''
   Purdue University has been studying a mysterious outbreak of
baby pigs in Wabash County, Ind., where hundreds of pigs are
reported to have died on a dozen farms.
   Neal Wollen, a veterinarian-pathologist at Kansas State
University, said a new strain of disease may be involved.
   ``You find a group of hog farmers locally having a problem, but
it is not spreading across the state,'' said Iowa State University
extension veterinarian James McKean.
   McKean said scientists, including those at the University of
Minnesota, think the deaths are caused by a virus.
</TEXT>
