<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1654EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NASAAmes'50th     05-11 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NASA Ames' 50th,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Ames Research Center Marks 50 Years of Achievements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOFFETT FIELD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty years ago, long before
satellites, space shuttles and planetary probes, work began on a
national research center that would help make all those things
possible.
   NASA's Ames Research Center is celebrating its first
half-century, beginning with an aerial photograph Friday of 2,000
employees arranged into a giant ``50.''
   Over the years, thousands of top scientists and engineers have
worked at Ames, developing swept-wing planes and supersonic flight,
contributing to the Mercury, Gemini and Apollo programs and
tracking Pioneer's voyages through the solar system.
   They have searched for the chemical building blocks of life,
experimented with plants, insects and eggs in space, studied the
effects of weightlessness and looked for holes in the atmosphere's
ozone layer.
   ``The two prominent features of Ames have been outstanding
people and the development of major, unique, national aerospace
facilities,'' said William F. Ballhaus Jr., director of the $500
million-a-year center.
   Space exploration was hardly a hot topic in 1939, when the
National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, predecessor of the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration, founded Ames
Research Center, named for NACA chairmen Joseph P. Ames.
   When tensions mounted before World War II, the government's
Langley Field lab in Virginia was seen as vulnerable to attack by
Germany, and a second facility was proposed 3,000 miles away at the
Army's Moffett Field base, 45 miles south of San Francisco.
   The threat from Japan was considered, but the site also had
low-density air traffic, good flying weather, adequate electricity
and access to the growing western aircraft industry, Stanford and
the University of California.
   Today, Ames is in the heart of high-tech Silicon Valley, and has
grown into a maze of dozens of laboratories, wind tunnels and
offices.
   ``When I first started working here (in 1971), during lunchtime
I'd wander around in the various wind tunnels and laboratories and
ask people what they were doing,'' Ballhaus said. ``It's
fascinating, like a technical Disneyland.''
   The Flight Research Building was put into operation in August
1940. By the fall, three wind tunnels were under construction to
work on problems of theoretical aerodynamics.
   When the United States entered World War II, the basic research
NACA emphasized was phased out while labs concentrated on immediate
problems.
   Research on deicing airplane wings had started at Langley as
early as 1927. But the problem was licked at Ames in 1944, proving
the effectiveness of the new laboratory.
   In 1952, Harvey Allen, a specialist in high-speed theoretical
aerodynamics, was working on missile research when he developed the
``blunt-body theory,'' which would later solve the problem of
heating during a spacecraft's reentry into the atmosphere.
   That theory would shape Project Mercury's reentry capsule and
play a key role in the design of the Gemini and Apollo crafts and
their heat shields.
   Ames work on high-speed flight helped lead to Capt. Charles
Yeager's first supersonic flight in the Bell X-1 on October 14,
1947. Eight years later Ames researcher R.T. Jones came up with the
``supersonic area rule,'' which minimized drag on supersonic craft
and allowed still faster planes.
   In 1958, Ames invented the lifting body, wingless craft able to
fly back into the atmosphere from space, survive entry heating and
land. That idea eventually led to the space shuttle.
   Ames was given responsibility for basic research in life
sciences in 1961 and began studying the chemical evolution of life.
   In the 1970s, Ames broke new scientific ground with its Pioneer
series of space probe. Pioneer 10, launched in 1972, became the
first craft to go through the asteroid belt and returned the first
close-up pictures of Jupiter.
   Four years later, the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence
began at Ames, a program that listens for radio signals from other
civilizations.
   ``Ames has had a big impact on the space program and on other
sciences and it still is very important,'' said Ballhaus. ``The
work here is helping us understand the universe and our
environment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890511-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1701EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolFinance     05-11 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Finance,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Asked to Reset Property Tax Bases to Ensure School Survival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES E. BEGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Neil Goldschmidt and legislative leaders
are asking voters statewide to approve a property tax formula that
opponents say would take control of school financing out of local
hands.
   Supporters say the measure will aid about 100 public school
districts with inadequate property tax bases, some dating to the
early 1900s. A property tax base is an amount a school district can
levy each year without seeking voter approval.
   Measure 1, on the ballot Tuesday, would reset all districts' tax
bases to include whatever extra levies local voters have approved
to make ends meet in 1988-89.
   Under the state constitution, the tax base can automatically
increase by up to 6 percent a year. So broadening the base will
make for bigger automatic increases each year.
   Supporters say this change is the next step in getting Oregon
out of a crisis that had schools closing for lack of money a few
years ago.
   The first step, a ``safety net'' law passed in 1987, allowed
schools in danger of shutting down to fall back on the previous
year's tax levies without additional voter approval. However,
school officials trying to make budgets on 2-year-old tax levies
say they don't have enough money to cope with inflation, enrollment
increases and other needs.
   Goldschmidt, a Democrat, and legislators from both parties argue
that Measure 1 will bring some stability to school financing until
a new source of funds can be developed.
   ``This is just a step, as was the safety net, toward equity,''
said Senate President John Kitzhaber. ``There are no losers in
this, only degrees of winners.''
   Only about a third of the state's 303 school districts are
potentially affected by the Legislature's ballot proposal. They are
mostly rural and relatively small, meaning voters from the large,
urban districts are likely to determine the fate of their tax bases.
   ``It tests whether people view schools as a statewide or local
responsibility,'' said John Danielson, lobbyist for the Oregon
Education Association, the state's largest teachers union.
   Clyde Brummell of Portland, a long-time tax critic and president
of the Oregon State Homeowners Association, said the issue is
whether taxpayers want ``remote voters'' to determine their taxes.
   ``The main thing we object to in the property tax is it's simply
no longer fair,'' he said. ``Until the system is changed, there's
no need to go through with this mediocre approach.''
   Passage of Measure 1 automatically would enact a companion bill
with $112 million in special school aid and property tax relief. It
includes $35 million for educating handicapped students, $35
million for districts with high property tax rates and $22 million
to ensure no districts get less basic aid under the Legislature's
actions this year than they now receive.
   The bill also provides $20 million with the aim of limiting
homeowner property tax bills for schools to no more than 5 percent
of income.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
