<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionMovie-Wildmon     05-11 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Movie-Wildmon,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mspi Preacher Claims Success in NBC Woes with Abortion Film Sponsors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC's inability to attract advertisers for
a made-for-TV movie on abortion demonstrates that big business
listens when consumers take a stand, a crusader said Thursday.
   ``I alerted advertisers about the pro-choice stance of NBC's
`Roe vs. Wade' movie and asked them not to sponsor it,'' said the
Rev. Donald Wildmon.
   The United Methodist minister heads the Tupelo-based American
Family Association, an organization that has successfully
challenged what it sees as profane and morally objectionable
material in magazines, television and movies.
   Wildmon's comments follow a statement by NBC President Robert C.
Wright in New York urging advertisers not to bow to pressure groups
seeking to block the film that is based on the 1973 U.S. Supreme
Court case that legalized abortion.
   In a May 8 letter to advertisers, Wright said he would broadcast
the movie as scheduled Monday without advertising, if advertisers
pull out.
   Wildmon, whose association was credited with ABC's decision May
2 to drop ``Crimes of Passion II'' from its prime-time schedule,
said the latest action by corporate sponsors marked a trend to rid
television of excessive sex and violence.
   He said the association, which has chapters scattered around the
country, was voicing similar opposition to other television
programs, and ``one coming up on NBC Friday night, `Amityville: The
Evil Escapes,' is in trouble.''
   The fact-based ``Roe vs. Wade'' stars Holly Hunter as a
character based on Norma McCorvey, the then-anonymous ``Jane Roe''
plaintiff who sued Dallas District Attorney Henry Wade. Amy Madigan
plays attorney Sarah Weddington.
   The abortion battle heightened when the high court heard
arguments April 26 in a Missouri case that could affect the 1973
decision.
   The movie is about the pro-choice advocates who prevailed, but
it also portrays sympathetically the prosecutors who argued the
other side, though they get much less attention.
   Wildmon said Wright's letter to advertisers asked ``them not to
be bullied. I am in agreement with that _ I don't think these
advertisers ought to let NBC or any other network bully them into
any program.''
   ``NBC has every right to air that movie and the advertisers have
every right to help sponsor it. And more and more consumers are
learning they have every right to spend their money where they want
to and that, I think, has Mr. Wright very upset,'' he said.
</TEXT>
