<SECOND>AM-Bush-Tass,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Criticizes Tass for Blaming US for Panama's Election
Disruptions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's chief spokesman on Thursday
criticized the official Soviet news agency Tass for a dispatch
blaming the United States for election disruptions in Panama. The
spokesman said it raised new questions about Soviet intentions on
improving relations with the West.
   Marlin Fitzwater, Bush's press secretary, called the Tass
account ``very disappointing.''
   ``It certainly tends to throw cold water on many of the claims
of a new thinking, a new openness in foreign relations,'' Fitzwater
said.
   Tass, in a dispatch from Panama City reporting on Sunday's
nullification of elections in Panama, said the action was necessary
because the opposition, ``directly instigated by the United
States,'' violated election laws and tried to rig the results
through ``subversive actions.''
   Fitzwater said, ``these statements reflect a lack of changes
that we all would do well to keep in mind.''
   ``While we welcome and encourage glasnost and perestroika'' the
Bush administration intended ``to keep in the back of our minds a
very healthy skepticism about these kinds of things.''
   Fitzwater said the Soviets have yet to match words with deeds.
   Panama's election tribunal invalidated the election results,
saying the stealing of ballots, vote-buying and missing tally
sheets made proclamation of a new president impossible.
   The Tass report asserted that supporters of opposition
presidential candidate Guillermo Endara had violated election
procedures.
   ``They blockaded polling stations, preventing ballot boxes from
being taken to the commission's headquarters in good time,'' Tass
said. ``A considerable number of ballot papers were stolen or
destroyed and several ballot boxes were burned.''
   Tass said the decision to nullify the election ``appears to be
extraordinary, but the only correct one.''
   The Tass story, and Fitzwater's comments, came as Secretary of
State James A. Baker III was in Moscow meeting with his Soviet
counterpart to discuss arms talks, and on the eve of a commencement
speech by President Bush at Texas A&amp;M expected to focus on the
results of his administration's review of East-West relations.
