<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Moldavia     05-11 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Moldavia,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moldavian Party Chief Backs Language Law, Hits Party Laggards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party chief of Moldavia on Thursday
backed a proposed language reform in the republic and lambasted
local party leaders for lagging behind the Soviet Union's fast pace
of change, Tass reported.
   Semyon Grossu ``spoke about the need to grant the status of
official language to the Moldavian language,'' Tass said, but
cautioned that the reform should not infringe on the rights of
other nationalities in the republic.
   Speaking at a plenary meeting of the Moldavian Communist Party,
Grossu said change in Moldavia is not coming fast enough and ``the
causes for this lag are shortcomings in the work of the party
organization,'' the official news agency said.
   He also criticized leaders of some grass-roots political
organizations for stirring up emotions, Tass said.
   Thousands of Moldavians demonstrated this spring in the
republic's capital of Kishinev, demanding changes in official
policy on language, the economy and the environment as well as a
crackdown on widespread crime and corruption.
   In March, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda criticized the
Moldavian party leadership for adjusting too slowly to the
republic's changing political life and letting the protests get out
of hand.
   Grossu in February condemned nationalist activitists for going
too far but endorsed some of their demands to make their native
language closer to Romanian.
   Moldavian and Romanian are the same spoken language, but
dictator Josef Stalin imposed the Cyrillic alphabet after Soviet
troops occupied the region during World War II.
   Grossu said work is under way to gradually reinstate the Latin
script still used in neighboring Romania.
   A draft law on the reintroduction of the Latin script will soon
be put out for public discussion, Tass said.
