<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap     05-11 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonn Advises Relief Workers to Leave Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German government has advised two
of its nationals to leave Lebanon after their colleague was
kidnapped last week, a Palestinian official said Thursday.
   Lt. Col Wajih Abu Ali, commander of the Palestine Liberation
Organization military police in Sidon, also said the PLO has
decided to stop protecting relief workers Heinrich Sruebig, 48, and
Petra Schnitzler, 26.
   ``But I do not believe Struebig and Schnitzler will leave before
their colleague Markus Quint is freed,'' Abu Ali said.
   It could not be confirmed independently that the two were told
to leave. No one was available to comment at the West German
Embassy in Beirut.
   The three work for ASME-Humanitas, a private organization that
provides medical aid, mainly to Palestinian refugees in Ein
El-Hilweh and Mieh Mieh camps on the outskirts of Sidon.
   Stuebig, an administrator, and Schnitzler, a nurse, said five
gunmen kidnapped them with Quint on May 4. The two said they were
released 10 hours later to transmit the demands of the kidnappers
holding Quint to West German authorities.
   The two disappeared and reappeared under similar circumstances
last year, and an official in Bonn termed the latest incident
``strange.'' Ms. Schnitzler has denied insinuations ``that we have
sort of stage-managed or engineered the affair.''
   She and Struebig refused to spell out the kidnappers' demands,
but ASME-Humanitas spokeswoman Dagmar Nackunstz said Monday they
include a sentence not longer than five years for confessed TWA
hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is on trial in Frankfurt for
air piracy and murder in the June 1985 hijack of a TWA flight
during which U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed and 39
Americans were held hostage for 17 days.
   Prosecutors are demanding life imprisonment for Hamadi, who will
be convicted May 17.
   Abu Ali said the PLO in Sidon has relayed to PLO chairman Yasser
Arafat its decision to suspend protection of the West German
workers. He refused to say why the command made the decision.
   The PLO military police is in charge of protecting
ASME-Humanitas personnel in the Sidon region which is the guerrilla
movement's stronghold in Lebanon.
   In addition to Quint, 15 foreigners are held hostage in Lebanon.
They include nine Americans, three Britons, an Irishman, an Italian
and a Belgian.
</TEXT>
