<FIRST>r a AM-EagleTrial     05-11 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eagle Trial,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Acquits Man in Bald Eagle's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing a bald eagle has
been acquitted by a jury after a federal trial that was conducted
much like a murder case.
   Jurors decided Wednesday there was insufficient evidence linking
Steven Lindell to the death of the bird, whose carcass was found
last fall in a ditch about a mile from Lindell's home.
   Lindell was prosecuted under the 50-year-old Bald Eagle
Protection Act, which protects the species as a national symbol and
provides for a sentence of up to a year in prison and a $250,000
fine.
   Two acquaintances testified Lindell had bragged about shooting
the eagle out of an oak tree. Defense attorney Douglas Thomson
charged that the men were making up the story for revenge.
   As in many murder cases, experts testified about the cause and
circumstances of the death. The bird allegedly was shot in
September, but the carcass was not examined by authorities until
several months later.
   Kent Oakes, a chemist with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service,
testified that he found evidence of lead on one of the eagle's
ribs, suggesting it had been shot with a small-caliber weapon. But
Oakes said he did not know enough to say how the bird died.
   Lindell, who did not testify, said he could not have brought
himself to kill a bald eagle. ``I have feeders all over my
property. I spend $40 a time buying feed,'' the 32-year-old truck
driver said.
</TEXT>
