<SECOND>AM-Cemetery Warning,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Official Goes to Cemetery to Warn of Unhealthy Diets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's health director had a grave
warning for residents, so he went to the cemetery Thursday to
announce it: Cut down on fatty Cajun and Creole food before it cuts
you down.
   Cholesterol levels have dropped only slightly since last year
when a citywide cholesterol screening program began, Dr. Brobson
Lutz told reporters gathered among the above-ground tombs at
historic Lafayette Cemetery No. 1.
   ``Similar cemeteries are filling up because people in the city
are dying of cardio-vascular disease,'' Lutz said.
   Lutz said cardio-vascular disease, a danger of a
high-cholesterol diet, plays a part in about 60 percent of the
deaths recorded in New Orleans each year. He said a recent study
showed the percentage of New Orleans residents with dangerously
high cholesterol levels dropped in the last year from 68 percent to
66 percent.
   ``It may not be a significant amount, but it is a wee bit,''
said Lutz.
   Lutz said he believes people in the area are changing to
healthier cooking methods and cutting down on fried foods.
   ``Basic nutritional changes are taking the place of the
Creole-Cajun cuisine for which we're so famous,'' he said.
