<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     05-11 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Says Short-Range Nuclear Arms Could be Eliminated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Short-range nuclear arms could be
eliminated from Europe if the United States and Soviet Union agree
on reducing conventional forces, a leading politician in the
governing coalition said Thursday.
   West Germany seeks East-West negotiations on reductions in the
battlefield nuclear weapons, most of which probably would be used
on its territory in case of war, but the United States and Britain
are opposed.
   Officials in Bonn said West German leaders, who have pressed
NATO for a more favorable attitude toward reforms in the Soviet
bloc, would discuss superpower relations with Eduard A.
Shevardnadze, the Soviet foreign minister.
   Shevardnadze met with Secretary of State James A. Baker III in
Moscow on Thursday and is to visit Bonn on Friday.
   About eliminating short-range weapons, Otto Lambsdorff said in a
radio interview: ``This is not possible today, but it could be if
conventional forces in Europe were reduced to levels each side
requires for defense.''
   Lambsdorff is chairman of the liberal Free Democratic Party,
junior partner in Chancellor Helmut Kohl's coalition.
   Kohl and Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher, also a Free
Democrat, have called for speedy East-West negotiations to reduce
short-range weapons. The United States and Britain say the weapons
are an essential part of the Western alliance's efense strategy.
   Genscher flew to London on Thursday for more talks on the matter
with British counterpart, Sir Geoffrey Howe.
   In a meeting two weeks ago, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was
unable to convince Kohl to drop his demand for negotiations, which
has split the alliance just before a NATO summit scheduled for
Brussels later in May.
   In Moscow, Baker rejected a proposal by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev that the superpowers negotiate reductions in the
short-range weapons.
   NATO has 88 Lance missile launchers, most of them based in West
Germany. The missiles now have a range of 75 miles, but
modernization would increase that to about 250.
   Shevardnadze is expected to address many topics during his visit
to Bonn, including disarmament and relations between the two
countries. He will meet with both Kohl and Genscher.
   Before meeting with Shevardnadze, Genscher will see Baker at a
meeting of NATO officials Friday in Brussels.
   A federal government source said: ``We expect Shevardnadze will
be reporting on the current state of Soviet-American relations.
This area is very important and interesting for us.''
   In remarks to Parliament on April 27, Kohl said the West
``should support reform processes in all Warsaw Pact countries. I
urge our European and American friends to help carry out this
policy and agree on a common approach.''
</TEXT>
