<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-11 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Never mind that the sky was filled with
gray clouds. Martin Z. Mollusk saw his shadow on Thursday, which
means summer will arrive a week early.
   The hermit crab performs an annual ritual similar in spirit to
that of Pennsylvania's Punxsutawney Phil, who is said to herald six
more weeks of winter whenever he sees his shadow on Groundhog Day.
   Tracy French, Miss Ocean City, carried the crustacean mascot to
the beach on a tiny decorated throne. To symbolize Ocean City's
commitment to clean beaches, the throne was set upon a container of
recyclable materials such as aluminum cans and glass bottles.
   With toddlers performing a hula around him and some devoted fans
and curious onlookers standing nearby, Martin crept out of his
shell and saw his shadow _ or so says Mark Soifer, the city's
imaginative public relations director.
   ``It was overcast, so no one thought he would see his shadow,''
Soifer said. ``But trust me _ there was an itsy-bitsy, teeny-weeny
area of sun that came through.''
   Soifer said the omen that summer will arrive a week ahead of its
normal June 21 date was authenticated by Gus the Amazing Weather
Dog, another Ocean City mascot. The dachshund also performs an
annual ritual. He buries Martin immediately after the event.
   Martin, however, was again rescued and returned to his ``heated
solarium,'' an aquarium tank in Soifer's office, until next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elementary school pupils set free
7,000 ladybugs in what their principal called an ecological
alternative to an annual balloon launch.
   Balloons, with notes attached, are often released by school and
community groups eager to see how far their messages will travel.
Many wind up in fields and wetlands, where the balloons can be
fatal to foraging wildlife.
   The idea to launch ladybugs came from Agnes Clift, a school
volunteer who works at a gardening shop that sells ladybugs as an
alternative to pesticides. Clift said she bought seven 1,000-bug
bags and donated them to the school.
   Chamberlin School pupils prepared for the launch by reading
about ladybugs and discussing them in class. On Wednesday morning,
they took small plastic cupfuls of the bugs into the schoolyard,
where the insects flew away or were set on tree trunks or blades of
grass.
   ``I think they're neat because they crawl all over and they're
good for everything,'' said Jason Lockwood, 7.
   ``It's gross. They feel funny,'' said 6-year-old Lucas Dusablon.
   ``It's a new tradition that we're starting,'' principal Rick
Marcotte said. ``It went great. We'll do it again next year.''
</TEXT>
