<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CapitolAide     05-11 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capitol Aide,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>John Mack, as Speaker's Aide, Was a Powerful Figure on Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John P. Mack, who resigned Thursday as a
legislative aide in the face of widespread public criticism over
his brutal 1973 attack on a woman, was a powerful figure in the
tightknit world on Capitol Hill.
   As a key assistant to House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, Mack
was a visible staffer, often seen buttonholing legislators on the
House floor. Taking orders from his boss, Mack sometimes ran
closed-door meetings for Democrats, guided policy and sat behind a
large desk near his mentor's office.
   ``When people looked at John Mack on the floor, they saw and
heard the speaker,'' said Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass. ``He really ran
the procedural part of meetings,'' added Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark.
   Mack was ``not only a professional but a good friend. And I
think that expresses the views of many of my colleagues,'' said
Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., the majority whip, in a guide to
congressional staffers, ``The Almanac of the Unelected.''
   Coelho and Mack were even investors together in Dairy Management
Associates, a business in Merced, Calif., Coelho's hometown,
according to David Dreyer, Coelho's spokesman. The company is
developing a system for managing dairy herds.
   Mack's desk was empty Thursday, he'd cleared it out overnight,
but the 35-year-old former aide's presence seemed to dominate the
House where he'd worked since his release on parole in 1975 from
the Fairfax County jail in Virginia.
   ``Everybody is very depressed around here,'' said Rep. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif.
   Though Mack was sentenced to 15 years in the Virginia State
Penitentiary for the malicious wounding of Pamela Small, he served
less than 27 months in jail before going to work in Wright's office
as a mail clerk for $9,000 a year. Mack's brother was married to
Wright's daughter.
   By the time The Washington Post printed a long story last week
detailing Mack's attack on Small with a hammer and knife, he was
one of the highest-paid staffers on Capitol Hill, earning nearly
$87,000 a year as the executive director of the Congressional
Democratic Steering and Policy Committee, the majority party's
policy-making group.
   ``He was a super-staffer,'' said Andrea Camp, a spokeswoman for
Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo.
   Mack, who frequently worked 12-hour days, is married to an aide
to Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass. They have two children.
   Rep. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, co-chairman of the Congressional
Caucus for Women's Issues, said she thought it wrong that Mack
should hold such an influential job when he ``clearly violated the
law, didn't finish his sentence and didn't pay restitution'' to
Small.
   Snowe drew a distinction between employment on Capitol Hill and
elsewhere.
   ``We make public law; that makes a big difference,'' she said.
Snowe drafted a letter asking Wright to reconsider Mack's job, but
the aide resigned before she sent it.
   ``I believe in rehabilitation, but not when it leads to such a
high position,'' said Schroeder, the other co-chair of the women's
caucus.
   Rep. Charles Wilson, D-Texas, said there is ``obviously
resistance to someone being a success.''
   ``We all believe in rehabilitation, that's everyone'e goal,'' he
said. But society wants rehabilitated convicts to be ``carpenters
and plumbers,'' not high-ranking congressional aides, he said.
   ``Apparently there was outrage among women members'' of
Congress, said Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan.
   ``There was an immediate reaction that went nationwide,'' said
Anthony, chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee. ``I can understand the emotional outcry ... I heard it
from my staff ... we heard it in congressional committees.''
   But the former prosecutor said that under the country's criminal
justice system, Mack had paid his debt.
   Even so, Anthony said, ``society is not quite willing to forgive
at a certain level.''
   In a statement on his resignation, Mack said he had planned as
early as last December ``to seek opportunities in private life.''
   Anthony doubted Mack would have any trouble in the outside
world. ``He will land a comparable job someplace,'' the Arkansas
Democrat said. ``He's a bright lad that's gained invaluable work
experience.''
</TEXT>
