<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     05-11 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. to Airlift 33,000 Namibian Exiles; SWAPO Guerrilla Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 33,000 Namibian exiles have
signed up to return home in a massive airlift that is part of a
United Nations plan to bring independence to this mineral-rich
territory, a U.N. official said Thursday.
   Also on Thursday, the territorial government announced security
forces killed a black nationalist guerrilla, raising to 313 the
number of insurgents the South African-led forces say they have
killed since an unexpected April 1 incursion from Angola.
   Nicolas Bwakira, chief representative in Namibia for the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees, said a five-week repatriation will
start May 22, provided the South African-appointed territorial
authorities implement an amnesty and repeal racist laws.
   Both steps are called for in the U.N. plan to end 74 years of
South African rule. South Africa has agreed to grant independence
as part of a regional agreement calling for the withdrawal of
50,000 Cuban troops from Angola.
   Most exiles have lived in Angola or Zambia since fleeing Namibia
during a 23-year guerrilla war waged by the South-West Africa
People's Organization.
   Bwakira said some exiles will return from Angola on foot, but
most will be flown back.
   They will be given food rations and cooking utensils and
encouraged to leave U.N.-supervised reception centers within a week
of arrival, said Bwakira, of Burundi, Central Africa.
   Namibian churches are to provide long-term care for 1,500
orphans, elderly and disabled returnees.
   At a separate news conference, a government spokesman announced
the killing of a SWAPO guerrilla but gave no details.
   He said the fighter was among 1,600 guerrillas who infiltrated
from Angola after April 1. Pretoria says the incursion violates the
U.N. plan. SWAPO was not a signatory to the accord signed by
Angola, Cuba and South Africa.
   Saturday marks the end of a two-week period in which U.N. and
security force officials were to verify whether the guerrillas have
withdrawn. South Africa says its troops will be confined to base
only if a total SWAPO pullout is confirmed. This will be discussed
at a meeting Monday with Angolan and Cuban officials.
   The guerrillas are to return home, unarmed, with the refugees.
   It is estimated there are perhaps 58,000 Namibian exiles.
Bwakira said 32,950 have registered to be repatriated. Others may
register later or decide after independence, scheduled early next
year.
   Most exiles support SWAPO and Bwakira said the U.N. monitoring
force in Namibia will seek to ensure their return takes place
``without fear of intimidation, harassment or prosecution.''
   The repatriation will cost $38 million, of which $31 million
already has been pledged by Western governments, Bwakira said. It
includes $10 million from Nordic countries, $5 million from the
United States and $1 million from Canada.
</TEXT>
