<FIRST>u a PM-MidgetmanTest 2ndLd-Writethru a0666 05-11 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Midgetman Test, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0666,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmits to fix overline.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Midgetman Missile Goes Off Course, Is Destroyed During First Test
Launch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with missile destroyed after it
went off course, picking up at the 4th graf previous, `The Midgetman.'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unarmed Midgetman
missile went off course and was destroyed today during the first
test flight of the controversial weapon system, the program
director said.
   The missile began to tumble about 70 seconds into the flight
while its second stage was firing and the range safety officer
issued a destruct command, Maj. Gen. Ed Barry told reporters.
   But he called the launch a ``qualified success'' because the
flight test met about 50 percent of its objectives.
   The intercontinental ballistic missile, designed to be fired
from a truck launcher, blasted off from a concrete pad at 11 a.m.
PDT.
   The missile was supposed to deliver a dummy warhead to a test
range about 4,600 miles away in the Kwajalein Atoll.
   The Midgetman, formally the Small Intercontinental Ballistic
Missile, is designed to carry a single nuclear warhead to a target
up to 6,900 miles away.
   The three-stage missile weighs 37,000 pounds, stands about 52
feet tall and is 46 inches in diameter.
   The weapon is at the center of a controversy over whether the
United States should develop one or two mobile nuclear missiles to
deter the Soviet Union from attempting a first strike against
missiles inside silos.
   The Soviet Union has deployed two such ``land-mobile'' missiles,
the United States none.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney would prefer to develop only one _
a version of the huge, 10-warhead MX that could be carried and
launched from a rail car. Democratic leaders on Capitol Hill prefer
the smaller, more mobile Midgetman.
   President Bush recently decided, however, to pursue development
of both the MX and Midgetman.
   The major contractors on the Midgetman include Morton Thiokol
Inc. and Martin Marietta Corp.
</TEXT>
