<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Media     05-11 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Media,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada, U.S. Accuse East Bloc of Impeding Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. delegates to a forum on press freedom accused
four East bloc nations Thursday of doing little to further the
cause, and Canada urged the nations to drop what it called their
``same tired old excuses.''
   The 35-nation forum brought together Canada, the United States
and every European country except Albania to monitor compliance of
an accord on improving the information flow between East and West.
   The U.S. and Canadian delegations concluded that Czechoslovakia,
Romania, East Germany and Bulgaria had shown little progress in
fulfilling their commitments to the accord, signed in Vienna in
January.
   Czechoslovakia responded to the charges in its concluding
statement at the month-long Information Forum, saying the West was
not looking at the full picture.
   Chief U.S. delegate Leonard H. Marks told The Associated Press
that ``very little progress'' had been made with the four East bloc
countries.
   ``We didn't expect to solve all problems, but I don't feel we
accomplished as much as I'd like to have,'' said the former head of
the U.S. Information Agency.
   Canadian Ambassador William Bauer said in a speech that some
nations remain in a dark age, where the only ``correct facts'' were
the government's, contacts with foreigners are taboo, and free
communication does not exist.
   ``The London meeting has, unfortunately, only reinforced our
view that such backward practices remain the norm in some
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe countries,'' he
said, referring to the four nations.
   ``When these countries were justly criticized,'' Bauer said,
``we were treated to the same tired old arguments'' that criticism
was internal interference or deliberately confrontational.
   The security conference ended in January in Vienna with
agreements committing the 35 signatories to improve the flow of
information and improve working conditions for journalists.
   Czechoslovakian chief delegate Dusan Spacil, the only one of the
four to speak Thursday, said in his concluding statement that
``confrontation or bias or disinformation ... is
counterproductive.''
   He said his country was undergoing a ``transitory period'' of
instituting reform and a ``new system in all spheres'' would come
into effect Jan. 1 next year.
   Bauer said the Czechoslovaks had lied about the circumstances of
an arrest of a British Broadcasting Corp. reporter May 1 during
coverage of a dissident protest, saying he had no identity papers
despite the fact that they were holding his passport at the time.
   He and other delegates said reluctance by some East bloc
countries to repeat a Vienna promise that all the forum's
undertakings were binding had kept a final communique from being
composed.
   Instead, as called for under the accord, all proposals made at
the forum were to be passed to the security conference for
consideration.
   Soviet chief delegate Boris Pyadyshev, a magazine editor,
expressed overall satisfaction with the forum, saying it had
brought the participants to a ``new level of understanding.'' He
refused to comment on criticism of his East bloc neighbors.
   Bauer and Marks said they saw encouraging signs of change in
Hungary, Poland, and the Soviet Union, but emphasized this did not
mean those countries had completely lived up to their commitments.
</TEXT>
