<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1713EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-JobTraining     05-11 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Job Training,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Seeks Retargeting of Training Money to Teens And Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Thursday proposed
rewriting the nation's premier job-training program to target most
spending on the unskilled poor and teen-agers and to hinge some
federal money on improvements in state training and education
efforts.
   The program was co-authored by Vice President Dan Quayle when he
was a member of the Senate.
   The suggested amendments to the Job Training Partnership Act
answer most criticisms of the program and are substantially in line
with changes proposed by several congressional Democrats, leading
Republicans and Democrats alike to predict passage of a revised
JTPA this year.
   ``There is an urgent need for more than job training,'' Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole said in outlining the administration
proposal to the Senate subcommittee on employment and productivity.
``Many desperately need basic skills training, literacy and
remedial education.''
   Although the proposed amendments would significantly redirect
the program, Mrs. Dole said they are needed because of the changing
demographics of the American workforce and not because of major
flaws in the initial legislation.
   ``Its record on advancing the employability of disadvantaged
youth and adults, and returning dislocated workers to the economic
mainstream has been unprecedented,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``But JTPA can
be made even better.''
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, called JTPA ``the singularly important
work of this committee during the Reagan years.'' But he agreed
with Mrs. Dole that the recession-spawned program needs to be
reworked to address current labor shortages, particularly in
high-skills fields.
   The chairman of the subcommittee, Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., has
introduced a package of similar amendments and expressed confidence
minor differences in the approaches would be resolved.
   ``I think we're going to get a good bill out of this committee
that we're all going to be able to agree on,'' Simon said.
   JTPA is by far the nation's largest training program, receiving
$2.4 billion this year to serve an estimated 1.9 million people.
Bush has requested stable spending for next year.
   Labor Department officials have said the proposed amendments
would increase per-person training costs and therefore cause some
modest reduction in service levels. Mrs. Dole, however, said those
reductions likely could be offset if states did a better job of
coordinating federal, state and other education, training and
counseling programs.
   Current JTPA spending formulas send two-thirds of the money to
areas based on their unemployment rates. The amendments would make
the concentration of economically disadvantaged the overriding
factor in spending decisions.
   Also, youth training programs now scattered throughout sections
of JTPA that also deal with adult training would be collected into
a separate entity, which Mrs. Dole said would allow dramatic
improvements in efforts to curb high youth unemployment,
particularly in inner cities.
   During her testimony, Mrs. Dole was flanked by three
participants in JTPA-funded programs. They sparked applause from
subcommittee members when they discussed their troubled childhoods
and achievements made possible by the training and education they
were receiving. They also met briefly later with President Bush at
the White House.
   Also among the changes proposed by the administration:
   _Rewriting eligibility requirements so that in addition to being
economically disadvantaged, all youths and half the adults seeking
enrollment in JTPA programs would need to have additional barriers
to employment such as literacy or basic skills deficiences. Teen
parents and the homeless also would be given preference.
   _Rewriting program guidelines to encourage more thorough
training, including deletion of provisions that weigh a program's
success by the number of placements it makes. Such provisions have
been criticized for encouraging programs to select applicants who
already have marketable skills so that they can be placed in jobs
quickly.
   _Requiring, for the first time, that JTPA funding for summer
jobs programs go only to youths who are enrolled in an approved
education or training program during the school year.
   _Requiring individual assessments of all prospective trainees
and for those accepted into programs, an individually tailored
program to meet the distinct education, training and placement
needs of each trainee.
   _Establishing grants for states that set clear goals for their
training programs and submit to the Labor Department plans that
demonstrate improved coordination between training and related
programs.
</TEXT>
