<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Shaw     05-11 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Shaw,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trumpeter Woody Shaw Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz trumpeter Woody Shaw died at Bellevue
Hospital, where he had been in a coma since he was hit by a subway
train in February. He was 44.
   Shaw, who lost his sight to degenerative eye disease several
years ago, fell from a subway platform into a train's path on Feb.
27. Surgeons were unable to reattach his left arm, which was nearly
severed at the elbow. He died of complications Wednesday.
   Herman Shaw II, who was born in Laurinburg, N.C., and grew up in
Newark, N.J., was influenced by trumpeter Freddie Hubbard.
   He took up trumpet in sixth grade and later worked for Willie
Bobo and Eric Dolphy, who invited him to join him in Paris. After
Dolphy died, Shaw worked abroad for several years. He was in Art
Blakey's Jazz Messengers in 1971 and '72 then settled in San
Francisco where he led a group with Bobby Hutcherson.
   By 1977, Shaw was in New York leading small groups playing bebop
with infusions of ``free jazz.'' Despite playing rapid melodies,
Shaw maintained a sweet tone.
   A number of musicians, including Wynton Marsalis, George Benson,
Freddie Hubbard and others who had worked with Shaw, held an
all-night benefit for him after the subway accident.
   Shaw is survived by his parents, Herman and Rosalie Shaw of
Newark; and a son, Louis Armstrong Shaw.
</TEXT>
