<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia     05-11 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenians Mass to Demand Freedom for Activists, Parliament Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300,000 Armenians, chanting and carrying
Armenian flags, massed Thursday in Yerevan to demand action on the
disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh and freedom for imprisoned
nationalists, activists said.
   The situation in Nagorno-Karabakh, where unrest broke out again
recently after four months of calm, was called ``tense and even
explosive,'' activist Martin Martirosian said in a telephone
interview after the protest in the Armenian capital.
   He said speakers at the demonstration, which was officially
condoned, called for a session of the Armenian parliament to
address the status of the disputed region. If no session is held by
May 18, they recommended a general strike, he said.
   The crowd also demanded the ``liberation, immediately and
without too much talk,'' of 13 Armenian activists under arrest,
said Rafael Popoyan, another activist contacted by telephone. Most
of the 13 are members of the Karabakh Committee, which organized
repeated protests about the region.
   People at the demonstration chanted ``Committee, committee,''
and ``Session, session,'' Popoyan said.
   The recent unrest in Nagorno-Karabakh involved strikes and
clashes between Armenians and Azerbaijanis, including a village
brawl fought by 200 people.
   Nagorno-Karabakh became the flashpoint for tensions between the
two peoples last year, when the Armenians, who are generally
Christian and make up three-quarters of the region's 162,000
inhabitants, began demanding that their homeland be transferred
from the rule of largely Moslem Azerbaijan and annexed by Armenia.
   After more than 90 people died in unrest there, the region was
placed under special administrative control by Moscow, but
Armenians consider the ``current government has not justified
itself, everything it does goes against the will of Armenian
Karabakh residents,'' said Popoyan.
   Speakers at the meeting described how more and more Azerbaijanis
were being settled in Nagorno-Karabakh, threatening the Armenian
majority and its claim to the region, Popoyan said.
   He said beginning Friday, meetings will be held at Armenian
workplaces to pass resolutions demanding the parliamentary session
and threatening a strike if it is not held.
   Meanwhile, in the neighboring Caucasus republic of Georgia,
small groups circulated through the capital of Tbilisi carrying
signs demanding the release of Georgian political prisoners, an
activist said.
   Manana Gamsakhurdia, wife of jailed political dissident Zviad
Gamsakhurdia, said three of the protesters were detained and one
remained in jail Thursday night.
   They were calling for the release of six activists arrested in
connection with ethnic unrest April 9 that left 20 dead.
   Zviad Gamsakhurdia, who was among those arrested after the clash
between Soviet troops and pro-independence protesters, is in poor
health, but officials have not let him move from his cell to the
prison infirmary, Manana Gamsakhurdia said in a telephone interview.
   She also said strikes were spreading in the Georgian region of
Abkhazia, where Abkhazians, although a minority in their own
region, have begun demanding secession from Georgia.
   Many Georgian residents of Abkhazia have gone on strike to
protest the Abkhazian demkands, she said.
</TEXT>
