<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 2213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RenewableEnergy     05-11 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Renewable Energy,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Renewable Energy Supplies To Double By 2000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Renewable energy sources, such as hydro and
solar power, could provide as much as 80 percent of the nation's
energy needs by the year 2010 if federal aid were accelerated, an
environmental group said in a study published Thursday.
   ``Renewable energy technologies offer one of the most promising
components of any strategy to mitigate the trend toward climate
change ...,'' the study said.
   Public Citizen, the study's sponsor, said the potential for
renewable energy can only be reached if the Energy Department
spends substantially more on research and development.
   The group, which strongly advocates reduced reliance on nuclear
power and fossil fuels that are linked to the trend toward global
climate warming, said the Energy Department budget for renewables
should be restored to the 1985 level of $263 million. The current
budget provides $115.6 million, and the Bush administration has
proposed cutting that to $86.5 million in the next fiscal year.
   Renewable energy sources currently supply about 8 percent of
total U.S. energy needs, including imports of electricity generated
from Canadian hydro plants, the study said. The figure could rise
to 19 percent by the year 2000, and to as high as 80 percent by
2010 if prices for conventional energy sources go up, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
