<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--CanadaMeasles     05-11 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Canada Measles,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Measles Caution Issued For Travelers To Quebec</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. health officials Thursday advised American
travelers to Quebec to make sure their measles shots are up to date
following a measles outbreak in there.
   More than 1,600 cases of measles have been reported in Quebec
since late December, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control said.
Five hundred cases have occurred in the metropolitan Montreal area.
   Two-thirds of the Montreal cases occurred in school-age
children; Quebec, unlike most locations in the United States, does
not require measles vaccinations for pupils.
   The CDC recommends that all people 15 months and older who were
born after 1956 should receive measles vaccinations. In addition,
travelers abroad in that age group should receive a booster shot
unless there is a medical reason why they shouldn't.
   ``All persons planning to travel to Quebec or to other areas
with ongoing measles activity, including those (measles-prone)
areas within the United States, should ensure that their measles
vaccination status is adequate,'' the Atlanta-based CDC said in its
weekly report.
</TEXT>
