<DOCNO> AP890511-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 2214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SavingsBonds     05-11 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savings Bonds,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Down 2nd Time in 7 Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S. Savings Bonds fell 11.1 percent
to $634 million in April, the last month before an increase in the
interest rate paid on the bonds, the government said Thursday.
   The Treasury Department said sales in April were off $79 million
from March, when sales had risen 3.2 percent. The drop, however,
was only the second in the first seven months of the government's
fiscal year, which began Oct. 1.
   On May 1, the government increased the rate on the bonds to 7.81
percent, up from 7.35 percent offered during the previous six
months. The new rate will be effective through Oct. 31.
   As of April 30, the total value of savings bonds held by
Americans was $112.69 billion, a record high and up 7 percent from
a year ago. Sales for the fiscal year so far totaled $4.65 billion.
</TEXT>
