<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1745EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0615 05-11 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0615,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shelling After Fifth Cease-Fire Proclamation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with shelling, casualties, purported
statement from kidnappers. Pick up 16th pvs, `After meeting...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners lobbed shells at two
Christian harbors Thursday, killing at least two people hours after
Arab League envoys called a new cease-fire to halt two months of
fierce artillery battles.
   Police said at least three rockets hit two adjacent apartments
in Bkirki, a mile southeast of the port of Jounieh, killing two
people, including a 10-year-old girl.
   A police spokesman said on condition of anonymity that eight
people were wounded, all relatives of Maronite Catholic Patriarch
Nasrallah Sfeir.
   The casualties raised the toll to 359 people killed and 1,393
wounded in the two-month battle, the latest round of fighting in
Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war. Nearly all the casualties have
been civilians.
   Police reported 20 people killed and 62 wounded by rockets,
howitzer shells and mortar fire before the truce deadline Thursday
afternoon.
   Also Thursday, rockets fired from multi-barreled launchers in
Syrian-policed west Beirut fell on Jounieh and Byblos, another port
in the Christian enclave north of the capital. No casualties were
reported.
   In another development, a statement purportedly signed by an
Iranian-backed extremist group believed to hold two American
hostages warned against the deployment of Arab observers to monitor
the latest cease-fire.
   The typewritten Arabic-language statement, signed by the Islamic
Jihad, was delivered to a western news agency in Moslem west
Beirut. There was no authenticating picture of Terry Anderson or
Thomas Sutherland, who are held by the group.
   Islamic Jihad repeatedly has said that statements attributed to
it are not genuine unless accompanied by a hostage picture or
videotape.
   Anderson, 41, the chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, was abducted March 16, 1985. He is the longest
held of the 16 foreigners missing and believed held hostage in
Lebanon.
   Sutherland, 57, acting dean of agriculture at the American
University of Beirut, was abducted June 9, 1985.
   The statement warned against the deployment of Arab observers
but did not mention any demands.
   Earlier, Lakhdar Ibrahimi, the Arab League assistant
secretary-general, told reporters the warring Christian and Moslem
factions had agreed on a truce set for 2:30 p.m.
   The league's four previous calls for a halt to the shelling had
little effect on the battle between Gen. Michel Aoun's Christian
army units and a Moslem alliance of Syrian troops and Druse
militiamen.
   Ibrahimi, an Algerian, and Abdel-Aziz Al-Jassem, a Kuwaiti
diplomat, have been trying to revive an April 28 cease-fire that
collapsed after only a few days.
   After meeting with acting Premier Salim Hoss, Ibrahimi said the
first objective is ``normalizing the situation in Lebanon'' so the
Arab League committee can try to end the civil war.
   Hoss has led a Moslem cabinet and Aoun a competing Christian
government since a political crisis in September. The army also
split, with Aoun leading the 20,000 Christians and Maj. Gen. Sami
Khatib taking command of the 22,000 Moslems.
   The Arab League team met with Aoun at the shell-scarred
presidential place in suburban Baabda, east of Beirut.
   A military spokesman at Aoun's headquarters said Syrian gunners
fired ``126 shells, most of them 240mm mortars, into the palace
before the Arab envoys' arrival.''
   Aoun, 53, lives in the palace bunker with his wife, Nadia, and
three daughters.
   On Wednesday, the delegation met in Damascus with Foreign
Minister Farouk Sharaa of Syria, which has 40,000 soldiers in
Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League and
is the country's main power broker.
   Aoun imposed a naval blockade March 6 on three illegal ports
operated by Moslem militias south of Beirut, and Walid Jumblatt's
Druse militia responded with artillery fire two days later.
   Syrian forces soon joined Jumblatt. Khatib's army troopers
helped seal off the 310-square mile Christian enclave and Aoun
declared a ``war of liberation'' to force Syria out of Lebanon.
   The government crisis began when the six-year term of President
Amin Gemayel expired in September and Parliament could not agree on
a successor. Gemayel appointed Aoun, the army commander, and
Moslems swore allegiance to Hoss, the incumbent premier.
   By unwritten agreement since independence from France in 1943,
the president is Christian, the premier Sunni Moslem and the
parliament speaker Shiite Moslem.
</TEXT>
