<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CrimePackage     05-11 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crime Package,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Import Assault Rifle Ban May Become Permanent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is considering stiffer
gun-control measures including a permanent ban on some
semi-automatic assault weapons for an anti-crime package to be
announced soon, administration sources said Thursday.
   The options being considered include making permanent the
temporary import ban on a variety of semi-automatic assault rifles
that was imposed in March and increasing criminal penalties for
illegal use of firearms, according to one of two sources, who both
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The administration is also studying increased penalties for the
illegal possession of semi-automatic weapons and their use in the
commission of crimes, according to another source.
   The proposals are in the final stages of review by White House
domestic policy chief Roger Porter. The anti-crime legislative
package is expected to be unveiled Monday by the president.
   Under consideration is a proposal that would bar people
sentenced to at least six months in jail for misdeanors from
purchasing guns, said the second source. Federal law currently bans
convicted felons from owning guns.
   Another measure under consideration is a proposal to link gun
dealers to a federal registry to determine if weapons purchasers
are convicted criminals, the second source said.
   Public concern about the use of military-style assault weapons,
such as the AK-47 used by a gunman to kill five children in a
Stockton, Calif. schoolyard last January, has prompted the
administration review of gun-control policies.
   In March, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms imposed a
temporary import ban on a variety of foreign-made semi-automatic
assault weapons while the agency determines if any of them are
being used for legitimate sporting purposes.
   Federal law prevents the importation of such weapons unless they
are used for target shooting or hunting.
   One of the options under consideration is a plan to permanently
ban 15 foreign and domestic-made military-style assault weapons,
the source said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
