<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Noriega     05-11 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Noriega,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Drug Agents May Examine Noriega Bank Records, Judges Rule</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. drug agents investigating Panamanian leader
Manuel Antonio Noriega will be allowed to examine records of his
bank accounts, two high court judges ruled Thursday.
   Customs and Excise Department officials unexpectedly discovered
the accounts and private documents in October during a raid on the
offices of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
   A lower court judge had barred the Customs and Excise agency
from releasing information on Noriega's accounts to U.S.
authorities.
   The documents will not be turned over for at least two weeks,
allowing the judges to prepare a written opinion and giving the
bank an opportunity to appeal.
   The ruling involved ``statements, ledgers, returned checks,
credit slips, withdrawal slips, application forms'' and other
documents involving accounts held by Noriega, his wife, two
daughters and a son-in-law.
   Andrews Collins, an attorney for Customs and Excise, had argued
the ban on turning over copies to U.S. agencies interfered with the
international fight against drug trafficking.
   Noriega was indicted in Florida on charges he took at least $4.6
million in payoffs from Colombia's Medellin drug cartel to protect
cocaine shipments, launder money, supply drug laboratories and
shelter the gang's leaders from law enforcement.
   A separate indictment in February 1988 accused Noriega of
conspiracy to import, distribute and attempt to import more than 1
million pounds of marijuana.
   Noriega, chief of the Defense Forces and Panama's de facto
ruler, denies the drug charges.
</TEXT>
