<FIRST>r a AM-Cocaine-BabyDeath     05-11 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine-Baby Death,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mom Charged in Baby's Cocaine-Linked Death: `I Loved Her'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman facing a manslaughter charge in
her baby's cocaine-related death says the case worsened the pain of
the ``worst time of my life.''
   Melanie Green's 2-day-old baby, Bianca, died Feb. 4. Authorities
blamed the death on prenatal brain damage caused by cocaine use
during pregnancy and charged the mother with involuntary
manslaughter and delivering a controlled substance to a minor.
   ``I loved her, I did,'' Ms. Green told the Chicago Tribune.
   Ms. Green, who had been without legal counsel, accepted an offer
of free representation from the American Civil Liberties Union,
ACLU spokeswoman Gwen Osborne said Thursday in Chicago.
   Winnebago County State's Attorney Paul Logli says he filed the
charges in an effort to protect children. But some legal,
public-health and medical officials say fear of prosecution could
prevent drug-abusing mothers-to-be from seeking help for themselves
and their fetuses.
   Ms. Green, 24, refused to discuss the allegations that her drug
abuse was responsible for her daughter's death. But her position on
what government officials should do in such cases was clear in the
interview Wednesday.
   ``They should help people,'' Ms. Green said. ``I tried to get
help, but I didn't get any.''
   She does not have a telephone and could not be reached to
elaborate, but her ACLU attorney, Colleen Connell, said most
drug-abuse treatment programs will not accept pregnant women.
   ``This prosecution represents an unprecedented intrusion on a
woman's constitutionally protected rights of privacy,'' Ms. Connell
said.
   Ms. Green was arrested Monday, more than three months after
Bianca's death, as she waited for her 6-year-old son, Damen, to
come home from school. She was freed on $3,500 bail Tuesday and
faces a May 31 court hearing.
   Ms. Green said she was with Bianca at Rockford Memorial Hospital
when the child died.
   ``It was the worst time of my life,'' she said, ``and this is
even worse.''
   A conviction on the involuntary manslaughter charge is
punishable by two to five years in prison. Ms. Green could face a
maximum 14-year sentence on the drug charge, Logli said.
</TEXT>
