<FIRST>r p AM-Bush-Personnel     05-11 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Personnel,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Picks FTC Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday announced his
selection of Janet Dempsey Steiger, a longtime personal friend, to
be chairman of the Federal Trade Commission.
   He said he would nominate her to succeed Daniel Oliver, the
current chairman.
   Since 1987, Ms. Steiger has been chairman of the national
Commission on Veterans Educational Policy. She is also a past
chairman of the Postal Rate Commission.
   Ms. Steiger, 50, is the widow of the late Rep. Bill Steiger,
R-Wis., who died in 1978. The couple were close friends of the
Bushes when Bush served in the House in the late 1960s, and Bush is
the godfather of their son, Bill, Jr.
   Bush said he would nominate her to a seven-year term. If
confirmed by the Senate, she will immediately be designated
chairman of the regulatory agency, according to a White House
statement.
   Bush also said he would nominate Deborah Kaye Owen, a Washington
attorney and former legal aide to then-President Reagan, to fill
another trade commission vacancy. She would succeed Margot E.
Machol.
   At the same time, Bush announced he will nominate James Franklin
Hill as assistant attorney general in charge of the Justice
Department's antitrust division.Hill, 56, is a Washington lawyer
who specializes in anti-trust advice.
   If confirmed by the Senate, he would succeed Charles F. Rule.
   The White House, in announcing Hill's selection, gave a list of
some of his major clients in his private practice. They include RJR
Tobacco, Safeway Stores, Inc.; Cyclops Corp., and the Detroit Auto
Dealers.
   Hill was chairman of the American Bar Association in 1987-88.
</TEXT>
