<DOCNO> AP890511-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Crisis     05-11 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Crisis,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's Response Measured in First Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faced with his first crisis as president,
George Bush has decided on a measured response to the tumultuous
situation in Panama, concerned that more decisive action could
imperil longer-term U.S. interests in the area.
   He said he was sending troops ``to protect the lives of American
citizens.'' But he ordered no direct military action and no new
economic sanctions against the government of Panamanian leader
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Bush warned of the consequences of failing to send a ``clear
signal'' to the ``enemies of constitutional rule'' in Panama and
elsewhere.
   But the seven points Bush outlined indicated that if Noriega is
to be overthrown, it will have to be primarily the work of
Panamanians and not Americans.
   The president obviously is hoping that other democratic nations
will close ranks against Noriega and that the Panamanian's
resulting isolation will encourage him to move on to other pursuits.
   Since Sunday's national election, a number of countries have
expressed varying degrees of indignation about the irregularities
reported by hundreds of international observers.
   These countries include Argentina, Guatemala, El Salvador, Peru,
Costa Rica, Spain, Great Britain, West Germany and Venezuela.
   And Venezuela is leading a campaign to have the Organization of
American States take a strong stand for democracy in Panama.
   If this fails to impress Noriega, he might still take note of
the most controversial step Bush announced _ the dispatch of 2,000
or more U.S. combat troops.
   Noriega may be concerned that the troops have a more aggressive
purpose in mind than the stated one of protecting American lives.
It is not unusual for a strong nation to try to achieve political
goals by projecting military power without actually using it.
   Bush backed away from a more pugnacious military response out of
concern that it could provoke anti-American uprisings in the
hemisphere. That approach might have succeeded in ousting Noriega
but the diplomatic costs would have been exorbitant.
   Slapping a trade embargo on Panama would have made the economy
there scream, but the impact would have been felt for years to come
_ long after Noriega's departure.
   So Bush is relying on rhetoric and diplomacy to weaken Noriega.
The State Department, after declaring that the opposition candidate
in Sunday's election, Guillermo Endara, won the election, is now
calling him ``president-elect.''
   It is a tactic aimed at robbing Noriega even further of any
claim to legitimacy.
   As for the diplomatic approach, the administration will be
lobbying hard over the next few days for a strong resolution at the
OAS foreign ministers meeting expected to start next Tuesday.
   Based on the regular OAS permanent council meeting on Wednesday,
the prospects are not bright.
   The U.S. representative, William Pryce, delivered a strong
attack on Noriega's perceived attempts to steal Sunday's election
but only three of the 30 other hemispheric countries joined in the
criticism _ Venezuela, Peru and El Salvador.
   But Bush indicated that his bag of anti-Noriega reprisals was
not exhausted in Thursday's speech. ``We do not rule out,'' he
said, ``further steps in the future.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for the
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
