<FIRST>r w AM-JudgeNixon-Impeach     05-11 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Judge Nixon-Impeach,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Names Panel for Judge Nixon Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders named 12 lawmakers Thursday to
a panel that will hear evidence in the impeachment trial of U.S.
District Judge Walter L. Nixon of Mississippi, currently serving a
five-year perjury term.
   The committee was named after House Judiciary Committee Chairman
Jack Brooks, D-Texas, came to the Senate and formally notified
lawmakers the House impeached Nixon on Wednesday on grounds he lied
to a federal grand jury.
   Standing before the Senate, Brooks read the three articles of
impeachment approved 417-0 and declared the House ``demands his
conviction and appropriate judgment thereon.'' The lawmakers then
voted to summon Nixon, now imprisoned at Eglin Air Force Base in
Florida, to answer the charges.
   He faces a trial in the Senate that will decide whether he
should be ousted from the bench and deprived of the $89,500 annual
salary that he still collects as a federal judge. He becomes
eligible for parole in November and has indicated a desire to
return to his courtroom and resume hearing trials.
   Appointed to the evidence-hearing committee were Sens. Wyche
Fowler, D-Ga.; Howell Heflin, D-Ala.; Timothy E. Wirth, D-Colo.;
Harry Reid, D-Nev.; Charles Robb, D-Va.; Herbert H. Kohl, D-Wis.;
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah; John C. Danforth, R-Mo.; John H. Chafee,
R-R.I.; Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska; James M. Jeffords, R-Vt.; and
Connie Mack, R-Fla.
   The panel plans to meet Tuesday to get organized.
   The evidence committee is similar to one preparing to hear
evidence against federal District Judge Alcee L. Hastings of
Florida, who stands accused of conspiring to get a $150,000 bribe
from two defendants.
   He was acquitted in 1983, but the House impeached him last year.
Lawmakers said there was ample evidence he took part in the plot,
lied at his trial and, in an unrelated matter, improperly disclosed
wiretap information.
   U.S. District Judge Harry Claiborne of Nevada was impeached by
the House in 1986 while serving a tax evasion sentence. The Senate
removed him from the bench.
   A jury convicted Nixon of perjury for denying in 1984 before
both a federal grand jury and Justice Department investigators that
he intervened in a narcotics case involving the son of Hattiesburg,
Miss., business executive Wiley Fairchild.
   Fairchild helped Nixon obtain a lucrative oil and gas investment
and investigators say the judge talked with a prosecutor about the
drug case.
</TEXT>
