<FIRST>r a AM-People-Letterman-Gumbel     05-11 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Letterman-Gumbel,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gumbel Reads Top-10 List: This Must Be for Real</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Today'' co-host Bryant Gumbel, showing a bit
of trepidation, made his first appearance Thursday on the turf of
late-night talk-show host David Letterman since the two began
feuding four years ago.
   Gumbel's unannounced visit to NBC's ``Late Night with David
Letterman'' came at the top of the show as Letterman was reading
the night's customary top-10 list _ this one of questions asked
prospective NBC employees.
   Number 7 in the countdown list was, ``Any problem car-pooling
with Bryant?'' Number 4 was, ``Want to join squad doing inventory
of Bryant Gumbel's suits?'' whereupon bandleader Paul Shaffer
complained that Letterman should lay off Gumbel, because ``he might
get mad.''
   Letterman said he would prove Gumbel could take a joke, went to
a studio door and brought Gumbel into the studio _ after Gumbel
hesitated and pointed at the floor: ``This studio?'' he said. ``Is
this the line of doubt?''
   Gumbel read the rest of the list, including No. 2, ``You
wouldn't leak a guy's memo, would you?'' a reference to the
now-infamous memo Gumbel wrote to the ``Today'' producer
complaining about most of his colleagues on the show.
   Letterman noted how long it had been since Gumbel had been on
the show. ``What, did you change your phone?'' he asked.
   ``I get lost,'' said Gumbel.
   The two shook hands and Gumbel left. ``I told you he wasn't
upset,'' Letterman told Shaffer.
   ``You two are the Jagger-Richards of television,'' observed
Shaffer, referring to the rocky relationship of ex-Rolling Stones
Mick Jagger and Keith Richards.
   The Gumbel-Letterman patchup apparently is genuine. A spokesman
for the show said during an afternoon run-through, the two tossed a
football and were ``very amiable.''
   Their feud began when Letterman interrupted a live, prime-time
``Today'' special by shouting from a window. Gumbel said the stunt
was unprofessional.
   Letterman said Gumbel had no sense of humor, and besides, he had
the ``Today'' producer's permission for the practical joke.
