<FIRST>u a AM-Avon-Amway-Crumel 1stLd-Writethru a0702 05-11 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon-Amway-Crumel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0702,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dual Amway-Avon Distributor Hopes Avon Lets Amway Buy It</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Avon's stock..., to UPDATE with closing stock
price. Also moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rhunetta Crumel is one person who thinks Avon
Products Inc. should not be fighting so hard against Amway Corp.'s
offer to buy it for more than $2 billion.
   Opportunity is knocking for Avon, says Mrs. Crumel, who has
reason to know: She is both an Avon representative and an Amway
distributor.
   The takeover battle between the two giants of direct sales will
directly affect nearly 3 million people worldwide, roughly 1.5
million representing Avon and more than 1 million from Amway.
   Avon's stock fell 37{ cents a share to $39.50, still slightly
above Amway's $39-a-share offering price, on the New York Stock
Exchange on Thursday. The spread indicated speculators were betting
a higher bid would emerge from Amway or another suitor.
   Avon is attempting to portray Amway as a maverick company that
has had numerous brushes with the law and sweeps up recruits to its
sales force through exploitative business evangelism.
   In a federal lawsuit this week, Avon said Amway has paid fines
of more than $20 million in connection with charges involving
customs duties and recruiting of distributors.
   Amway ``touts with religious fervor the development of a
multi-layered distribution scheme in which the people at the top of
the pyramid become wealthy through sales by those below them of any
and every product known to man,'' the lawsuit says.
   Not true, said Mrs. Crumel, of Berkeley Heights, N.J., who quit
her job at Exxon Corp. five years ago to devote more time to her
Amway distributorship. People who dislike Amway simply don't
understand it, she said.
   ``There are two things you can't penetrate. The first is
ignorance and the second is laziness,'' she said.
   Avon said its board would evaluate Amway's offer but noted that
the board has said previously that the company is not for sale.
   In the latest development, Amway said Thursday that if it
acquired Avon it would sell off Avon's higher-priced retail-store
fragrance lines, stripping the company down to the manufacture and
direct sales of perfumes, cosmetics, toiletries and household items.
   Avon had no response to the statement, made in a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing.
   ``They would be beautiful together,'' Mrs. Crumel said in a
phone interview from her northern New Jersey home after Amway made
its takeover offer Wednesday.
   Mrs. Crumel thinks Amway distributors would benefit by adding
Avon to their product line, while Avon could learn from Amway's
rah-rah approach to recruiting and caring for its distributors.
   Amway is no pyramid as Avon charges, Mrs. Crumel said.
   Although recruiters get a percentage of their recruits' sales,
the recruits can easily end up making more money than the
recruiters, she said.
   Mrs. Crumel said big-ticket items and the bonus structure make
it easier to make money as an Amway distributor. And she said Amway
takes care of its people better.
   Avon treated its representatives as ``stepchildren'' while it
went on an ill-fated diversification drive, William Nicholson,
Amway's chief operating officer, said in an interview.
   In fact, Avon lost more than $400 million last year from the
expense of retrenching by selling most of its health care
businesses to focus on its core businesses of beauty and direct
sales.
   Kathryn Gaume, a Berkeley Heights resident who sells only Avon,
said she knows little about Amway and is not sure she likes what
she has heard.
   No problem, said Mrs. Crumel.
   ``For the people who are willing to hang around and learn what
Amway is all about, I think they'd be very happy.''
</TEXT>
