<FIRST>r w AM-IowaRepairs 330   05-11 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa Repairs, 330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Going To Sea Without Repairs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battleship Iowa, on which 47 sailors died
last month in a gun turret explosion, will proceed with its next
regular deployment this summer without undergoing repairs, the Navy
said Thursday.
   But a decision has been made to fix the damage after it returns,
a spokesman added.
   The service, in a brief statement, said the battleship will be
departing in June on a scheduled deployment to the Mediterranean
Sea along with a number of other warships.
   ``The ship is fully operational except for the No. 2 gun turret,
and had already been scheduled to go to the Norfolk, Va., Naval
Shipyard for post-deployment repairs'' after returning from the
Mediterranean, the Navy said.
   Since it will take several months to obtain all the necessary
repair parts, ``turret No. 2 will not be repaired prior to
deployment.''
   ``But it is now the Navy's intention to repair the turret,''
said Lt. Cmdr. Jim Kudla, a spokesman.
   ``The engineering survey team indicates the damage to the ship
was contained in turret No. 2, and all other systems on the ship _
including the engineering plant _ are in excellent condition and
fully capable of supporting the upcoming deployment,'' the Navy
concluded. ``The Iowa remains one of the most powerful and durable
ships afloat.''
   The Navy and Pentagon announced last week the damage to the huge
battleship could be repaired for an estimated $15 million to $20
million. At the time, however, officials declined to say with
certainty the turret would be fixed and if so, when.
   There had been some doubt about repairs because of the vessel's
age. The Iowa was commissioned in 1943 during World War II and no
vessel of its type has been built since that war.
   Forty-seven sailors died on April 19 inside the No. 2 gun turret
while loading a 16-inch gun with powder.
   The huge battleship still has two other turrets, each with three
16-inch guns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
