<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-11 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northeast, Plains, Texas Receive Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell in the Plains and especially in Maine on Thursday, and
Florida had both a record high temperature and a record low for the
date.
   Thunderstorms developed ahead of a cold front crossing New
Mexico, producing showers and thunderstorms in west-central Texas
and the possibility of tornadoes in parts of New Mexico, Texas and
Colorado.
   Rain showers fell across the Northeast from the upper Ohio
Valley to New England. Flood watches continued for parts of western
New York state, and were issued for New Hampshire and western Maine.
   Wet snow fell over some of the higher elevations of western New
York state. Franklinville, N.Y., reported an inch of snow on the
ground early Thursday morning.
   Much of the northern and central Plains had cloudy skies, and
scattered showers soaked parts of northern Oklahoma, central Kansas
and southeastern Nebraska.
   Rainfall totals for the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
nearly an inch at Portland and New Brunswick, Maine, two-thirds of
an inch at Bangor, Maine, and six-tenths of an inch at Brownsville,
Texas.
   Clouds and rain kept temperatures in the 40s and 50s in much of
the Northeast, while 80s and lower 90s heated up southern Florida
and southern Texas. Miami had a record high of 93 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 37
degrees at Jamestown, N.Y., to 92 degrees at Miami. The nation's
low Thursday morning was a record 25 degrees at Marquette, Mich.
   Other record low temperatures for the date included 51 at
Apalachicola, Fla., 42 at Birmingham, Ala., 44 at Huntsville, Ala.,
and 47 at Montgomery, Ala.
   Friday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
across the northern Rockies, the high country to the west and much
of the Great Plains. Numerous showers also were predicted from the
Ohio Valley and the lower Great Lakes region across the middle and
northern Atlantic Coast states.
   Temperatures were forecast to remain below 70 degrees in much of
the West and from the Great Lakes region and northern Atlantic
Coast states to North Carolina and eastern Tennessee, with highs in
the 50s from Lower Michigan and the upper Ohio Valley into western
New England, and from northern Arizona to the northern Rockies.
Temperatures should warm into the 80s from southern New Mexico
through much of Texas and Louisiana to southern Florida.
</TEXT>
