<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Namibia     05-11 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Plans to Double Police Supervisory Force in Namibia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
plans to double the U.N. police force supervising Namibia's
transition to independence, the British ambassador said Thursday.
   At a briefing for the Security Council, Perez de Cuellar
``proposed to increase the number of (U.N.) police in Namibia'' to
1,000, Sir Crispin Tickell told reporters after the session.
Tickell is council president for May.
   The current authorized size of the police contingent of the U.N.
Transition Assistance Group in Namibia is 500.
   Tickell also said Perez de Cuellar plans to increase the
authority of Martti Ahtissari, his special representative in
Namibia, by giving the Finnish envoy an executive assistant.
   Namibia's local police force, trained by South Africa, is
responsible for law and order while the territory goes through a
one-year transition to independence under U.N. sponsorship.
   Perez de Cuellar originally recommended 500 U.N. supervisors,
but in early April the local police clashed with about 1,900
guerrillas who crossed the border from bases in Angola.
   The U.N. police and military observers in northern Namibia did
not have enough personnel to monitor the Namibian police and South
Africa soldiers, who left their bases to confront the guerrillas.
   South African troops are to return to their bases Saturday.
   In early November, Namibians will to vote for a assembly to
write a constitution for the territory, also called South-West
Africa.
   U.N. personnel in Namibia also include 4,650 peacekeeping
troops, more than 760 civilian administrators and more than 800
people hired locally. At least 600 monitors from several nations
are to be on hand for the elections.
   South Africa captured South-West Africa from Germany in World
War I and governed it under a League of Nations mandate abrogated
by the United Nations in 1966.
   In December, South Africa finally signed accords with Angola and
Cuba agreeing independence for Namibia if 50,000 Cuban troops
stationed in Angola were sent home by mid-1991.
</TEXT>
