<FIRST>r a AM-RacketeeringSentences     05-11 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racketeering Sentences,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scarfo Gets 55 Years, Leonetti 45 in Racketeering Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mob boss Nicodemo ``Little Nicky'' Scarfo
was sentenced Thursday to a maximum 55 years in federal prison and
fined $500,000 in a racketeering conspiracy that included 13
murders and attempted killings.
   He was described by the government as ``a remorseless and
profoundly evil man.''
   Scarfo, 59, and 16 other members of his Philadelphia-southern
New Jersey Mafia gang were convicted last November.
   The government said Scarfo ran the mob from his home in Atlantic
City, N.J., and was ``the leader of one of the most important and
powerful'' of 24 La Costra Nostra families in the country. As a
member of the Mafia's national commission, he ``became one of the
most powerful criminals in the United States,'' Prosecutor David
Fritchey said in court.
   ``The end of this mob family hasn't happened yet, but it is
severely crippled,'' he said.
   Scarfo stood impassively, declining to address the court, and
merely shrugged his shoulders when the sentence was handed down.
   Afterward, his lawyer, Robert Simone, told a reporter: ``Nicky
doesn't blame, or have ill will, toward the judge or the proscution
because what else were they to do with the false information they
got. His beef is against those who lied about him in the
courtroom,'' referring to mobsters who turned government informants.
   Earlier in the day, U.S. District Judge Franklin Van Antwerpen
sentenced Scarfo's nephew, Philip Leonetti of Margate, N.J., who
was identified as mob underboss, to the maximum 45 years. The judge
rejected a plea for probation after noting Leonetti was involved in
four murders, an attempted murder and 15 extortions.
   For the other defendants, sentences ranged from 3{ years to 45
years.
   Scarfo was found guilty of participating in eight murders, four
attempted murders, 17 extortions and two drug deals plus bookmaking
and loansharking. He was not accused in a ninth murder.
   The judge directed that Scarfo serve his racketeering sentence
after he completes a 14-year federal term he's now serving in a $1
million extortion attempt and a life sentence imposed by a
Pennsylvania judge last month in a murder case.
   ``He should never again be free to prey upon society,'' Fritchey
urged the judge before sentencing.

</TEXT>
