<FIRST>r w AM-TestBan     05-11 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Test Ban,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Urge Test Ban Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150 lawmakers urged President Bush
on Thursday to begin negotiations with the Soviet Union on the
phase-out of nuclear weapons tests as part of a treaty banning the
process by 1995.
   ``A test ban would prevent the Soviet Union from developing new
types of nuclear warheads or bombs that might threaten our future
security, such as so-called `third generation' nuclear weapons,''
the 142 House members and 23 senators said in a letter to Bush.
   The Bush administration has not yet indicated where it stands on
nuclear testing, although it is expected to continue the policy of
the Reagan administration, which opposed additional testing limits.
   The lawmakers said the Bush administration has an opportunity to
act and a ban ``would significantly advance our nation's
longstanding interest in preventing the proliferation of nuclear
weapons to other countries.''
   They noted that the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty comes up
for renewal in 1995.
   Among the recommendations included in the three-page letter was
allowing the United States and the Soviet Union a limited period of
time to conduct an agreed number of tests to check their arsenals,
progressively lower both the permitted size and number of nuclear
tests to limit testing of new types of nuclear warheads or bombs
and install a network of seismic monitoring stations in the United
States and Soviet Union to verify compliance with the limits.
   The final recommendation is a call for negotiating a formal
U.S.-Soviet comprehensive test ban treaty that could be signed by
all nations and will take effect from 1995 to 2000.
</TEXT>
