<FIRST>r a AM-Texans-Hightower     05-11 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texans-Hightower,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Stay Texas House Knuckled Under to Chemical Lobby</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State House members who voted to water down
the agriculture commissioner's power to regulate pesticides
knuckled under to chemical industry lobbyists, environmentalists
and others charged Thursday.
   Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower's aggressive enforcement
of pesticide rules has angered some chemical and farm interests,
environmentalists said. The commissioner is elected in Texas, not
appointed.
   ``This ... is a slap in the face to all those ordinary people
who can't afford high-priced lobbyists,'' said Brigid Shea of Texas
Clean Water Action.
   ``When you look at this ... ask yourself this question: Would
the chemical lobby hire a cadre of people, spend hundreds of
thousands of dollars and almost two years' time to pass a bill to
better protect the public, or to better protect their profits?''
she said.
   A spokesman for the Texas Agricultural Chemicals Association,
Jon Fisher, disputed the charge and said environmentalists had
rejected offers to compromise on pesticide regulation.
   ``We have, since last fall, offered to negotiate a way to
regulate pesticides that would be in the interests of the people of
this state and the future. Because they refused to negotiate,
because they indicated to me they had commitments that would not
allow them to negotiate, we did not get involved. We were not
involved in what happened in the House,'' he said.
   The House gave final approval Thursday to ``sunset'' legislation
that would continue the Agriculture Department for 12 more years.
   But the House also added an amendment Wednesday to take
pesticide regulation away from Hightower and give it to a
six-member board that would include the commissioner and five
others.
   The bill was sent back to the Senate for consideration of House
amendments. If rejected there, the issue would go to a conference
committee with members from both chambers.
   DeDe Armentrout, regional director of the National Audubon
Society, said controversy over Democrat Hightower _ whose
department Republican Gov. Bill Clements could abolish by vetoing
the sunset review bill _ was hurting the public.
   ``Eighty-eight legislators placed higher importance on placating
a big-monied chemical lobby and an uncaring governor at the end of
his career than in protecting citizens against exposure to
dangerous pesticides,'' Ms. Armentrout said.
   The proposed pesticide board would also include the state
chemist, the Texas Tech University agriculture school dean, the
dean of the University of Texas School of Public Health, a state
Health Department epidemiology official and a Texas Water
Commission official.
</TEXT>
