<FIRST>r w AM-HUDProbe     05-11 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Probe Criticized By Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
  The investigation by HUD Inspector General Paul
A. Adams into a federal low-income housing renovation program came
under fire Thursday on Capitol Hill from legislators who questioned
the conclusions that there was no evidence of criminal wrongdoing.
   Adams was also criticized for waiting until a day before former
Secretary of Housing and Urban Development Samuel Pierce was
scheduled to leave the department to interview him and for singling
out for culpability Thomas T. Demery, the former assistant
secretary for housing who was responsible for administration of the
program.
   Adams and Demery told the House Banking housing about their
roles in the HUD Section 8 Moderate Rehablitation Program and the
subsequent investigation of its selection and allocation process.
   Two weeks ago, Jack Kemp, the current HUD secretary, suspended
more than $100 million in fiscal 1989 spending for project under
the program.
   Kemp said Adams' investigation had uncovered a system that ``was
undocumented, ignored existing standards and regulations, and was
based on the perception and reality of favoritism and abuse of
non-public information'' through which former HUD appointees and
other former government officials won lucrative consultanting
contracts.
   ``Why would you have waited ... until Jan 19 of this year to
interview the HUD secretary Samuel Pierce who was going out of
office the next day?'' queried Rep. Henry Gonzalez, D-Texas, the
subcommittee's chairman, noting that Adams' probe had begun almost
a year earlir.
   Adams said his investigation did not immediately turn up any
evidence of Pierce's possible involvement and he said ``it was just
a matter of scheduling interviews.''
   But Demery insisted, as he had another hearing earlier this
week, that problems existed in the program before he gained his
post in October 1986 and spending decisions were ``discretionary''
for Pierce
   In January 1987, Demery said a selection committee was set up
that included himself; Deborah Gore Dean, former executive
assistant to Pierce; and an undersecretary for policy.
   But Demery conceded Pierce had final approval over any
recommendations made by the group.
   The HUD inspector general's investigation cover activities in
the program from January 1984 through November 1988.
   Gonzalez also asked why Adams made no ``specific recommendations
regarding possible violations of law'' by former HUD officials.
   Adams answered that his office had consulted with the Justice
Department throughout the investigation and found no evidence laws
had been violated.
   ``I find a disturbing indication in the documents that because
these allocation formulas and the laws that pertain to HUD are not
criminal statutes, that the conspiracies that go on here of
individuals working together in order to go around established
procedures are treated as if they are not criminal matters,'' said
Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn.
   But the Justice Department is reviewing the report, Adams added.
   Rep. Joseph Kennedy, D-Mass described Demery as ``one of the few
people that we could ever talk to at HUD'' during the previous
administration.
   But Kennedy later took Demery to task because of his hesitancy
to name Pierce as the HUD official directly responsible for the
alleged abuse and mismanagement in the program and he said the
inspector general's conclusions might ``compromise'' any future
investigation.
   Rep. Marci Kaptur, D-Ohio, indicated she might request a special
prosecutor to investigate the program.
</TEXT>
