<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Panama 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 1039</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Support Bush on Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 21st graf pvs, bgng: `Cranston said,'
to include Claiborne Pell reax. Picks up 22nd graf, `Noriega is'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican and Democratic leadership of
Congress gave president Bush a solid vote of approval Thursday for
``a measured, careful and deliberate''' response to election fraud
in Panama and the brutality of its military ruler, Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   But some legislators said there is strong pressure on the
president _ which he has so far rejected _ to either invade Panama
or scrap the treaties turning the Panama Canal over to Panama by
the end of the century.
   They rallied behind the course Bush did choose, reinforcing U.S.
forces in Panama with an additional 2,000 combat troops and moving
to protect the 51,000 American civilians in the country.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas acknowleged that
many members of Congress believe Bush did not go far enough and
tougher action is needed to drive Noriega from power.
   But he hinted that tougher military steps may be needed
depending on the flow of events in Panama and said Bush's future
options are quite limited.
   ``It gets a little tighter from here on if nothing happens'' and
Noriega refuses to go, Dole said.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., said the people of Panama may be on
the verge of settling the dispute on their own.
   But he also declared the United States has the right to ``to
keep all further military options opening for response to potential
crises.''
   ``We're drawing a much tighter noose around Noriega's neck with
every one of these unified actions,'' Lugar said.
   In a joint statement, the bipartisan leadership of Congress
expressed strong support ``for the president's action today in
taking measured and deliberate steps to assist the Panamanian
people in restoring democracy to Panama.''
   The congressional leaders also urged the democratic governments
of the hemisphere to condemn Noriega's actions in ``the strongest
possible terms.''
   ``It is the responsibility of freedom loving men and women
throughout the world to speak out in support of the expressed
democratic aspirations of the beseiged people of Panama,'' the
statement said.
   It was signed by House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas; Senate
Majority leader George Mitchell, D-Maine; House Majority Leader Tom
Foley, D-Wash.; House Minority Leader Robert H. Michel, R-Ill., and
Dole.
   At a news conference, Mitchell said the president had taken a
``prudent defensive measure.''
   But he said he had told Bush there will be those ``who think
this does not go far enough.''
   Dole said the measures have a dual purpose: protect American
lives and ``put the heat on Noriega.''
   ``We would hope that the Panamanian people and international
concern and outrage would have an impact on Gen. Noriega,'' Dole
said.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., the Senate's deputy Democratic
leader, said there is ``general support in Congress for the steps
the president has taken.''
   He said that at a meeting with members of Congress, Bush had
``rejected advice to invade Panama or to break the treaty with
Panama.''
   Although Cranston did not say who gave that advice, those
courses of action have been urged by several lawmakers.
   Cranston said that although there is no guarantee Bush's moves
will force Noriega's departure quickly, especially in light of the
staying power he has shown to date, ``they should reduce the
prospects that he will stay there a long, long time.''
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, questioned Bush's decision to withdraw U.S.
Ambassador Arthur Davis.
   ``It is precisely when relations are at their worst that we need
an ambassador in country,'' Pell said. ``In this situation, the
continued presence of a U.S. ambassador could provide important
encouragement to the Panamanian opposition.''
   Pell said he supported the decision to withdraw dependents,
maintain sanctions and ``assert our treaty rights regarding the
Panama Canal.'' He warned, ``There is a risk, of course, that
increasing our troop strength could provide a convenient pretext
for Noriega to renew his accusations that the United States is
planning military intervention and to use that charge to take
further repressive actions.''
   Noriega is under indictment in the United States for narcotics
trafficking and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said the prospect the
indictment might be withdrawn should figure in any negotiations to
persuade Noriega to leave.
   ``I think that in order to get this guy out of Panama ... that
should be a part of the negotiations,'' McCain said.
   He said the situation is made tougher by the fact that Noriega
has made clear ``that his goon squads are perfectly willing to
beat, maim and kill people.''
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., the Senate's president pro tem,
saying he found the conduct of the Panamanian presidential
elections ``saddening and maddening,'' said the United States
should now embark on a diplomatic offensive throughout Latin
America ``to isolate Noriega from the fruits of international
economic, political and diplomatic intercourse in this hemisphere.''
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said the United States ``has every
right to protect its people and protect its property.'' Gramm said
Bush's action has ``got to give'' Noriega more pause.
   ``He will sleep less well tonight,'' Gramm said.
   But Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said ``I'm not sure Gen. Noriega
will sleep at all tonight.'' Kerry said that in the past the United
States has underestimated Noriega, but the Panamanian leader
``senses the tide turning.''
   Kerry said that for the ``first time an entire, united,
bipartisan consensus policy has emerged.''
   ``The most important thing is that President Bush is reaching
out to Latin American allies. That's never happened before.''
   Kerry said he currently opposes dropping the drug charges
against Noriega, but said he wouldn't rule that out.
   ``If assets are given up, other things are achieved which
balance against it, I wouldn't negate any plea-bargaining,'' he
said. ``I have a problem with it, but I hope we don't get to that.
Let's see what the ingredients are at that time.''
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said he commended the president
for his action because he believes there was a ``tremendous degree
of pressure on the president to take actions that were more
strident.''
</TEXT>
