<FIRST>u a AM-USTroops-Panama     05-11 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US Troops-Panama,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops in California, Louisiana, North Carolina Ready for Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT ORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 1,000 infantry troops began
leaving Fort Ord Friday evening to join another 1,000 U.S. combat
soldiers ordered into Panama by President Bush, military officials
said.
   The Army's 7th Light Infantry Division at Fort Ord dispatched
880 combat troops and 100 cooks, medics and other support soldiers
to Travis Air Force Base, where they were to leave for Panama, Maj.
L.D. Walker, chief of public affairs for Fort Ord, said Thursday
afternoon.
   About 25 Army vehicles packed with troops began leaving the base
beginning at about 5:30 p.m. Travis is 160 miles northeast of Fort
Ord and 35 miles northeast of San Francisco.
   In addition, three companies consisting of 726 soldiers from
Fort Polk, La., and 165 Marines from Camp Lejeune, N.C., will be
among the 2,000 infantrymen sent to Panama, Department of Defense
officials said. Their departure time was not known.
   ``We are prepared to do our job,'' Maj. Terrance Hall, the
public affairs officer at Fort Polk, said at a news conference at
the base.
   Walker, said at a news conference there that the infantry troops
were being driven to Travis Air Force Base,
   The 7th, known as the Bayonet Division, is part of a highly
mobile outfit that carries most of its equipment on its back and is
designed for quick deployment anywhere in the world, base officials
said.
   Lt. Santos De La Rosa of Fort Ord said the base was placed on
alert Wednesday evening. The base is capable of dispatching
soldiers within 18 hours of such an alert, officials said.
   The 726 Fort Polk soldiers, comprising three 5th Army companies,
will be accompanied by 59 personnel carriers, six mortar carriers
and 106 support vehicles, said Lt. Cmdr. Jim Kudla at the Defense
Department in Washington
   The soldiers will convoy to Beaumont, Texas, where they will be
picked up by the USS Bellatrix, said Tony Garrett, press secretary
for U.S. Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La.
   The Bellatrix was reportedly anchored in the New Orleans area on
Thursday afternoon.
   In North Carolina, Marine Lt. Col. Keith Schneider said the 2nd
Marine Expeditionary Force leaving for Panama consists of 165
Marines and 18 light armored vehicles. The Marines will be flown
directly from Camp Lejeune to Panama.
   Bush ordered the additional troops into Panama ``to protect the
lives of American citizens'' following Wednesday's bloody attacks
by supporters and troops of military ruler Manuel Noriega against
the opposition's presidential candidate and his running mates. The
United States regards the opposition to be winners of Panama's
election.
   The 2,000 troops will augment the 10,000 U.S. forces already in
the country.
</TEXT>
