<FIRST>r a AM-Lab-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0775 05-11 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lab-Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0775,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disruption of Research Labs Feared after Fire Guts Mouse Breeding
Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10, `Dr. Richard..., with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
other comments from researchers. Picks up 11th graf pvs: `One worker ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCIS X. QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that gutted a breeding center
housing about 500,000 laboratory mice will cause a worldwide
disruption of laboratories researching AIDS, cancer and other
diseases, officials said Thursday.
   Kenneth Paigen, the incoming director of Jackson Laboratory,
pledged ``to get back up as fast as we possibly can'' as salvage
teams searched for living mice within the research center's
still-smoldering animal production facility.
   The laboratory, which distributes about 2 million mice annually
to researchers, is the world's leading non-profit supplier and
developer of mutant mice bred in hundreds of genetically identical
strains.
   About a half-million mice would be in the facility on any given
day, officials said, but there was no estimate of how many or what
types might have survived.
   Paigen said the center had saved its ``foundation stocks'' of
specially bred mice but warned that supply disruptions would hamper
researchers who need the mice to investigate cancer, AIDS and other
human diseases.
   ``Thousands of labs, literally all over the world, depend on us
for supplies of mice, genetically defined animals,'' Paigen said.
   ``I think it's safe to say we have some of everything, but how
much we have of anything is not clear right now,'' said Philip
Standel, director of animal production. The laboratory, located two
miles outside the picturesque resort village of Bar Harbor, housed
about 1,000 strains of mice, many of them rare.
   ``The impact is going to be terrific, really detrimental,'' said
Salome Waelsch, a professor of molecular genetics at the Albert
Einstein College of Medicine in New York.
   ``There is no way of restoring this facility by just importing
mice from elsewhere,'' said Waelsch, a member of the National
Academy of Science.
   Dr. Richard Sidman, a professor of neuropathology at the Harvard
Medical School and a senior research scientist at Children's
Hospital in Boston, predicted the fire would ``modify the pace of
research'' for up to a year.
   Philip Leder, chairman of the Genetics Department at the Harvard
Medical School, described Wednesday's fire at the Bar Harbor
complex as ``a tragedy.''
   While the lost mice can be replenished eventually, Leder said,
``it's just going to take a tremendous amount of energy, investment
and time.''
   State Fire Marshal Donald M. Bisset said the fire was accidental
and was apparently linked to ``a product that gave off flammable
vapors'' that was being used by renovation workers in the building.
   One worker suffered extensive burns in the fire and was listed
in satisfactory condition Thursday at Maine Medical Center in
Portland, said hospital spokeswoman Sharon Sturgeon.
   Two other construction workers injured in the fire remained in
the Mount Desert Island Hospital in Bar Harbor, where they were
listed in stable condition.
   Inside the laboratory's research center, which was not involved
in the fire, supervisory staff handled a steady stream of phone
calls from Jackson Laboratory customers, explaining that damage
assessments had only just begun.
   ``It's universities, it's hospitals, it's government agencies,
pharmaceuticals,'' said John Pomroy, an assistant manager.
   Paigen, who assumes the director's post full-time this summer,
vowed that the center would recover fully from the fire.
   ``The major decision we made, in fact we never considered an
alternative, is that we're rebuilding,'' he said.
</TEXT>
