<FIRST>r a AM-People-Bottoms     05-11 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Bottoms,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Timothy Bottoms Arrested for Investigation of Brandishing Gun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motorist accused actor Timothy Bottoms
of waving a Western-style pistol at him during a freeway clash, and
Bottoms was booked on two criminal charges, the California Highway
Patrol said Thursday.
   Frank Harwood, 38, of Meiners Oaks, called the CHP on his
cellular phone at about 4:30 p.m. Wednesday to report he had been
threatened as he drove his pickup truck on U.S. Highway 101 in
Ventura, CHP spokesman Jim Utter said.
   Traffic officers pulled over the station wagon belonging to
``The Last Picture Show'' actor about 12 miles farther north on the
highway, near the Ventura-Santa Barbara county line.
   Bottoms, 37, of Santa Barbara was booked for investigation of
brandishing a gun on a roadway, a felony, and carrying a loaded
weapon, a misdemeanor. He posted bail and was scheduled for
arraignment Monday in Municipal Court.
   Utter said he had only limited details of the freeway
confrontation. ``It would appear he (Bottoms) became involved in
the freeway incident either due to discourteous or possibly unsafe
driving,'' he said.
   Bottoms' arrest was routine and the gun was confiscated. ``It
was apparently a long-barreled, .22-caliber pistol,'' Utter said.
   Sandy Bresler, Bottoms' spokesman, said he would not even call
the actor to ask him to comment on the arrest. ``I have trouble
believing that's true,'' he said. ``It doesn't sound like the
Timothy Bottoms I know.''
   Bottoms made his film debut in 1971 in the movie ``Johnny Got
His Gun,'' the same year he appeared in ``The Last Picture Show.''
His other films include ``The Paper Chase'' (1973), ``The Other
Side of the Mountain Part II'' (1978) and ``Invaders From Mars''
(1986).
   Bottoms has also appeared in several television productions
including the mini-series ``East of Eden'' in 1981.
</TEXT>
