<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0685 05-11 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latin American Nations Criticize Panama For Voiding Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd pvs, `President Carlos...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with Mexico recalling ambassador. Pick up 4th pvs, `Costa Rica... INSERTS
3 grafs after 10th pvs, `Perez said...,' to UPDATE with Brazilian, Salvadoran
comment. Pick up 11th pvs, `International election...' Edits thereafter
to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BEARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Latin American nations denounced Panama for voiding its
election, but several said Thursday they opposed foreign
interference. Cuba backed Panama's government and said U.S.
intervention would provoke an ``explosive reaction.''
   President Bush said he was adding 2,000 soldiers to the 10,000
stationed in Panama to ``protect the lives of American citizens.''
   Mexico recalled its ambassador to Panama for consultations, the
Foreign Ministry said.
   President Carlos Andres Perez of Venezuela urged Latin American
nations to act together to protest vote fraud, and he called the
decision to nullify the count ``even worse than the fraud itself.''
   Costa Rica said: ``The election in which an entire people voted
with such hope, seeking their freedom without violence, has been
betrayed.''
   Britain joined the United States in demanding the resignation of
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, commander of Panama's 15,000 soldiers
and police, who has been the country's de facto ruler since 1983.
   A statement by the European Economic Community condemned ``the
repeated use of force and numerous acts of violence during the
electoral process, particularly the brutal physical aggression
against opposition leaders by bat-wielding thugs trained by the
country's defense forces.''
   It hinted at sanctions with the declaration: ``The EEC, whose
relations with the Latin American countries are based on consistent
and permanent respect for the principles and institutions of
democracy, cannot ignore the seriousness of these developments.''
   Perez said he was in ``constant consultations'' with Bush and
other leaders. He said he had called for an extraordinary meeting
of the permanent council of the Organization of American States to
consider action against Noriega.
   In Brazil, the Foreign Ministry said Thursday it would support
an emergency meeting of the OAS to find solutions to the Panamanian
crisis.
   Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte also said he would
petition OAS President Joao Baena Soares to convene an emergency
meeting.
   ``All the democratic presidents of Latin America see that there
was obvious fraud in Panama, and we must now raise our voices,'' he
said.
   International election observers, including former President
Jimmy Carter, said Endara had been leading Noriega's candidate,
Carlos Duque, by a 3-1 count when balloting was voided.
   In Buenos Aires, Argentine Foreign Minister Dante Caputo said
``what happened in Panama seems to us incredible and unacceptable.''
   The government of Peruvian President Alan Garcia said it
``denounces and rejects'' the nullification, which it called a
``maneuver against the will of the Panamanian people.''
   Peru also said, however, that it supported the fulfillment of
the Panama Canal Treaty, under which the United States will turn
over the canal to Panama by the year 2000.
   In Chile, the Foreign Ministry said President Augusto Pinochet's
government ``views with concern'' the violence and the voiding of
the balloting.
   ``We also view with concern a rise in interference by some
countries in Panama's internal affairs,'' the ministry added.
   Cuba's Foreign Ministry also said it opposed foreign
interference.
   The statement ``warns about the grave consequences for all of
the Latin American region and for the interests of relations
between Latin America and the United States (because) of the
unavoidable and explosive reaction that would take place among the
peoples of our America if there is a U.S. military action,''
reported Radio Rebelde, monitored in Miami.
   It did not offer details on what the consequences or reaction
would be. On Oct. 25, 1983, Cuban construction workers and a
handful of soldiers battled U.S. invaders on the Caribbean island
of Grenada but were overwhelmed as the United States ousted a
radical Grenadian army junta.
   On Wednesday, seven Latin American foreign ministers said the
turbulence following the Sunday election could further isolate the
country from the region's democracies.
   The statement was signed by the Group of Eight nations, which
actually has seven members _ Peru, Argentina, Uruguay, Brazil,
Venezuela, Colombia and Mexico. Panama was suspended after Noriega,
the nation's de facto ruler, engineered the ouster of elected
President Eric Delvalle in February 1988.
   Spain also condemned the voiding of the elections, and Britain
demanded Noriega resign.
   In Moscow, the official Tass news agency contended the
nullification was necessary because the opposition, ``directly
instigated by the United States,'' had attempted to rig the results.
   The decision to nullify the election ``appears to be
extraordinary, but the only correct one,'' it said.
   In Washington, presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater
called the Tass account ``very disappointing.''
   ``It certainly tends to throw cold water on many of the claims
of a new thinking, a new openness in foreign relations,'' Fitzwater
said.
</TEXT>
