<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 2315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ResearchProtest     05-11 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Research Protest,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amherst Board Upholds Controversial Anthrax Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town Board of Health refused Thursday
to ban controversial military-funded research at the University of
Massachusetts, research that local Quakers fear could be used in
germ warfare.
   The university has been wracked by three weeks of protests by
students and Amherst residents over Department of Defense-funded
research on campus, particularly microbiologist Curtis Thorne's
work with the anthrax bacteria.
   Campus police have arrested 151 people since the protests began.
Early Thursday morning, they removed and arrested a group of
students who had barricaded themselves in a campus building for 30
hours.
   Both the town health board and the UMass Faculty Senate held
special meetings Thursday to discuss the issue. The faculty agreed
to review university policy on campus research, which holds that
only non-classified research whose results can be made public may
be conducted.
   The health board, by a 3-0 vote, rejected a call by the American
Friends Service Committee's western Massachusetts chapter to halt
Thorne's research on anthrax, a disease of cattle and sheep that
can also be transmitted to humans.
   The Friends' spokesman, Ira Helfand, said the likelihood of a
laboratory accident that could spread the disease to the town is
slight but possible.
   Helfand also charged that Thorne's work on improving the vaccine
against the disease could be used offensively. He said the Pentagon
could inoculate U.S. forces against the disease while infecting
enemy soldiers.
   He also charged Thorne with working with new and dangerous
strains of the bacteria in what could be a violation of the 1972
international treaty banning biological weapons.
   Thorne, in a telephone interview Thursday, said he deliberately
chose to work with non-virulent strains of the bacteria and has no
reason to develop highly toxic strains of the bacteria, since the
military could already purchase them from a commercial laboratory.
   But, he said, an improved vaccine might protect in peacetime
U.S. soldiers who go to parts of the world such as Australia and
South America, where anthrax is endemic.
   Thorne said he has never had a safety problem and believes his
work does not have offensive military applications. ``If I didn't
feel confident about that, I wouldn't be doing it,'' he added.
   While recognizing that military-funded research on campus might
be undesirable, the health board sided with Thorne.
   ``I don't think there is any question that the opponents object
to the research because of the source of its funding and are using
this issue as a means to accomplish their ends,'' said chairman
Diana Stein, a biology professor at Mount Holyoke College. She said
the last anthrax death in a laboratory was 35 years ago.
   Initially Thorne's work, begun in 1966, was funded by the
National Institute of Health. For the past nine years it has been
financed by $1 million in grants from the Pentagon.
   About $11.6 million of the $57 million the 25,000-student
university received in grants during 1988 came from the Defense
Department.
   The Quakers said they will appeal the board's decision to the
state Department of Quality Environmental Engineering. They have
also placed an article before town meeting that would ban all
military-funded research at Amherst. The town will vote on that
question in late May or early June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890511-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 2255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a0805 05-11 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0805,0903</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Dependents Moved onto Military Bases; Opposition Defiant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to UPDATE with military dependents also
moving to bases. Pick up 3rd pvs, `Panamanian soldiers...' Minor editing
thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAN3,LA5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders Thursday rejected
the government's move to void the election and said the world
should unite to oust Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, whose thugs beat
them the day before.
   President Bush ordered U.S. military bases in Panama reinforced.
Dependents of military and U.S. Embassy staff members were moved to
the safety of Fort Clayton.
   Panamanian soldiers patrolled the city. U.S. military personnel
were advised to stay off the streets if possible and to wear only
civilian clothes in public.
   Bush said in Washington that about 2,000 soldiers would be added
to to the 10,000 stationed in Panama to ``protect the lives of
American citizens.'' About 21,300 U.S. civilians live in Panama,
many of them retired.
   There was no immediate reaction from the Panamanian military.
   Noriega, head of the 15,000-man Defense Forces, has been
Panama's de facto ruler since 1983. The United States has tried to
get him out through a variety of means, including economic
sanctions.
   Bush also recalled U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis and said U.S.
companies doing business in Panama will be asked to bring home
dependents. He said Americans in Panama would be asked to leave or
to move into one of the 10 U.S. military compounds.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, the opposition's candidate for first
vice president, issued an ``urgent call to Latin American and North
American and European governments to start a concerted, decisive
diplomatic and political action to help make the will of our people
prevail and to keep us from sinking deeper into savagery and
disaster.''
   He said this should be done by the Organization of American
States.
   Arias Calderon told a news conference he would not let the
government use fraud as an excuse for nullifying the elections when
the fraud was committed by the Panamanian military.
   On the deployment of additional U.S. troops, Arias Calderon
said: ``It is U.S. policy provoked by Noriega and not requested by
us.''
   A government statement Thursday denounced what it said was an
attempt to organize a coup in Panama organized in part by
Venezeuelan President Carlos Andres Perez.
   The release said those contacted about taking part included Col
Guillermo Wong, the chief of intelligence of Panama's military.
   There was no immediate response from Venezuela.
   U.S. reporters were barred from an Elections Tribunal press
conference Thursday. On a tape recording of the conference Yolanda
Pulice, head of the tribunal, said she did not know when new
elections might be called.
   ``For now what is more important is peace among Panamanians,''
she said. ``There will be decisisons later.''
   Many nations condemned the government's nullification of
Sunday's presidential election, which the government said Noriega's
candidate won and foreign observers said was a landslide for the
opposition.
   Noriega supporters with bats and metal pipes beat Guillermo
Endara, the opposition presidential candidates, and his running
mates for the two vice presidencies during a demonstration
Wednesday. Soldiers watched but did not interfere.
   The beatings occurred after soldiers intervened in the protest
of what the opposition calls the theft of Sunday's election.
   Endara remained hospitalized Thursday with a scalp wound that
required eight stitches. Doctors said his condition was stable with
no neurological complications.
   ``We won and we will continue to fight,'' said Guillermo Ford, a
vice presidential candidate who was beaten and thrown in jail.
   Ford, who had stitches over his eye and cheek, said he was
sentenced Wednesday night to a year in jail for inciting riot and
attacking soldiers, then freed a few hours later.
   He said the opposition wants to talk with the military, but that
would require getting rid of Noriega ``because Panama cannot have
two presidents.''
   The government said it was voiding the election because
irregularities and U.S. interference made it impossible to declare
a victor. It also cited stealing and buying of votes and missing
tally sheets.
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Cynthia Farrell said embassy dependents
were moved to Fort Clayton on Thursday. There are 152 embassy
dependents in Panama and 10,560 military dependents, 972 living off
base.
   ``You have these `Dignity Battallions' moving around town and
targeting people,'' Ms. Farrell said.
   Members of the ``Dignity Battallions,'' armed groups of Noriega
supporters, were involved in the melee Wednesday.
   Ambassador Davis and other officials said one of Endara's
bodyguards was killed and about 20 demonstrators were injured
Wednesday. The military said four soldiers were wounded.
   More than 300 international observers, including former
President Jimmy Carter, supported opposition claims that Endara won
by a 3-1 margin.
   When the election was voided, official results had shown
Noriega's handpicked candidate, Carlos Duque, leading by about 2-1.
   Washington began its campaign to remove Noriega after he
arranged the dismissal of President Eric Delvalle, who tried to
fire Noriega after the general was indicted in Florida on
drug-trafficking charges in February 1988. Noriega denies the
charges.
   Noriega claims the United States wants to get rid of him so it
can renege on the Panama Canal treaties, which turn the canal over
to Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
