<HEAD>Report: US Asks Thailand to Evacuate Workers From Libyan Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to ADD U.S. comment, CORRECTS spelling of Rabta.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington has asked Thailand to
evacuate 300 Thai workers from a Libyan plant the United States
alleges can produce poison gas, it was reported Thursday.
   ``The United States has threatened to bomb the area but has
promised it will inform Thailand before launching an attack,'' said
The Nation, a Thai newspaper.
   In Washington, the State Department said in a statement that the
United States has discussed with a number of governments, including
the Thailand, ``the dangers posed by Libya's chemical weapons
program, and have asked them not to contribute to its development.''
   ``We have information that there are a number of Thai workers
employed at the Rabta site,'' the statement said.
   A State Department source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
refused to confirm that the United States has asked Thailand to
evacuate its workers but said, ``The presence of the workers has
been a subject of discussion.''
   The Nation quoted an unidentified senior Thai government
official as saying Libya told the Thai ambassador in Rome that it
would expel all 75,000 Thai laborers from Libya if the 300 workers
were evacuated.
   Tripoli says the plant at Rabta, Libya, is a pharmaceutical
complex.
