<FIRST>r a AM-EcclesiaTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0828 05-11 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecclesia Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0828,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorneys in Ecclesia Trial Present Closing Arguments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Charged with ..., to UPDATE with jury beginning
deliberations.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor said Thursday that four
Ecclesia Athletic Association members acted in concert to beat to
death the 8-year-old daughter of the disciplinary group's founder.
   ``They all committed the crime of beating Dayna Broussard to
death,'' Clackamas County Deputy District Attorney Alfred J. French
III said in his closing statement.
   The jury began deliberations Thursday afternoon on the
first-degree manslaughter charges against Willie K. Chambers, 35,
of San Diego; Brian K. Brinson, 31; Constance Z. Jackson, 38; and
Frederick P. Doolittle, 28, all of Los Angeles.
   Prosecutors have said the girl was struck hundreds of times Oct.
13 as punishment for stealing food, and as an example to other
children who were staying in a farmhouse near Sandy, about 30 miles
southeast of Portland in the foothills of Mount Hood.
   Witnesses testified she was beaten with an electrical cord,
rubber hose, piece of plastic pipe, bamboo pole and weightlifting
belt.
   Most of the 53 other children were forced to watch the beating,
prosecutors said. Several testified that Dayna was slammed against
a wall, kicked, tripped, slapped, dropped on the floor, shoved,
bitten, spit upon and hung out a window.
   After Dayna's body was delivered to a fire station, the other
children, ranging in age from 1{ months to 16 years, were taken
into state custody. The children now are living in foster homes or
with relatives.
   The girl's father, Eldridge Broussard Jr., was in Los Angeles at
the time of her death. He did not attend the trial.
   Broussard, 35, has blamed negative news coverage for his
daughter's death. He denied that the children were beaten or
abused, saying they were only ``spanked.''
   Broussard formed Ecclesia at the Watts Christian Center in Los
Angeles to steer children away from drugs and crime and to motivate
them through tough discipline and athletic training.
   The children were brought to Oregon last summer while the Los
Angeles center was being renovated.
   French said the defendants' effort to discipline Dayna turned
into a ``contest of wills.''
   ``The wills of the four defendants prevailed that night, and
Dayna Broussard is dead,'' French said.
   Jack Bernstein, the attorney for Doolittle, responded that
French's selection of witnesses and evidence, including graphic
photographs of the dead girl's body, had been a calculated attempt
to misdirect jurors.
   ``The little children who were paraded before you were done to
inflame you and enrage you,'' Bernstein said.
   Bernstein said French called only a few of the children as
witnesses because others would have presented conflicting accounts
of what happened to Dayna.
   Both Bernstein and Ron Thom, the attorney for Brinson, argued
that French failed to prove their clients were guilty of
manslaughter.
   ``You won't like it,'' told jurors. ``I don't ask you to like
it. But you've got to follow the law.''
</TEXT>
