<FIRST>u f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-11 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0744</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House tax-writers rejected President Bush's
savings and loan bailout plan, approving an alternative that
threatens to swell the federal deficit over the next three years by
$43 billion to $50 billion and possibly force a veto showdown with
the White House.
   The House Ways and Means Committee, with 2 of 13 Republicans
joining its 23 Democrats, voted 25-11 Wednesday to include the
government's full $50 billion share of the most massive corporate
bailout in history in the fiscal 1989, 1990 and 1991 budgets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. got its foot in the door of Avon
Products Inc., offering more than $2 billion to buy its larger and
more conservative rival in person-to-person sales.
   Analysts predicted the $39-a-share cash offer Wednesday by
Amway, known for its sales force's evangelistic attitude, would
precipitate a drawn-out battle with Avon, made famous by its
genteel ``Avon Lady'' image of years past.
   Amway in partnership with Minneapolis investor Irwin Jacobs owns
10.3 percent of Avon's outstanding common shares, but Jacobs is not
participating in the purchase offer, Amway said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
approved rule changes designed to make the securities industry's
arbitration system more fair to disgruntled customers.
   By a 5-0 vote, the commission Wednesday authorized a series of
changes, spurred by complaints from unhappy investors who
discovered after the October 1987 stock crash that they had signed
away their right to sue their brokers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary G. Lynch, the driving force behind the
insider trading investigation that rocked Wall Street, said he is
leaving the Securities and Exchange Commission after four years as
its top cop.
   Lynch, a lanky, soft-spoken 38-year-old attorney who became the
SEC's youngest-ever enforcement director in early 1985, said
Wednesday he will step down in mid-July. He said he had no specific
plans after that.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted stock brokerage founder Boyd L.
Jefferies testified he engaged in four unlawful stock deals with
corporate takeover strategist Paul A. Bilzerian.
   Testifying at Bilzerian's securities fraud trial at federal
court in Manhattan on Wednesday, Jefferies, who said he only met
the Singer Co. chairman once, detailed their dealings in four stock
transactions in 1985 and 1986.
   The indictment alleges that Jefferies secretly held stock for
Bilzerian in four deals involving Cluett, Peabody &amp; Co., Hammerhill
Paper Co., H.H. Robertson Co., and Armco Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal bankruptcy court extended a bidding
deadline on Eastern Airlines for at least one potential suitor, as
a bidder for Eastern's profitable Northeast shuttle raised its
offer for that business.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland extended the Wednesday
deadline for an investor group led by Joseph Ritchie, a prominent
Chicago commodities trader, to give it more time to receive
financial information from Eastern.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup Co. settled a year-old dispute
with nine states over advertised claims that the company's soups
promote good health and may help prevent some types of cancer.
   Under terms of a court settlement announced Wednesday, the
nation's largest soup producer agreed to pay the states $35,000
each and to change certain advertising practices. The money will be
used by each state for consumer education and aid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Can Co. developed a secret and
sophisticated computer program used nationwide to deny longtime
employees pension benefits, a federal judge has ruled.
   In a sharply worded opinion Wednesday against the company, U.S.
District Judge H. Lee Sarokin directed Continental Can to begin
negotiating settlements with about 2,500 Continental workers. Costs
to the company could approach $500 million.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rebounded from an eight-day slide in lackluster
trading Wednesday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose
3.12 points to finish at 2,374.45.
   The dollar continued a minor retreat, digesting the gains that
took it to nine-month highs at the start of the week. Gold prices
were mixed.
   Bond prices edged down.
   Prices of frozen pork belly futures soared the permitted daily
limit of 2 cents a pound for the second straight day. Other
livestock and meat futures finished mixed; energy futures were
widely mixed; precious metals were lower; and grains and soybeans
were mixed.
</TEXT>
