<DOCNO> AP890511-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe     05-11 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top New York Futures Trader Subpoenaed In CFTC Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the most influential players in Wall
Street's commodity markets has been subpoenaed in the government
probe of possible trading abuses, but he said investigators
indicated he isn't a target.
   Paul Tudor Jones II, whose trading firm manages more than $500
million in commodity funds, said Wednesday he was cooperating with
the Commodity Futures Trading Commission in its civil investigation
of trading practices on four New York futures exchanges.
   Another trader, Craig W. Effron, has been subpoenaed by a
federal grand jury in a criminal investigation headed by Manhattan
U.S. attorney's office into possibly illegal trading practices on
the markets, his lawyer said Wednesday.
   Effron is the first trader to be publicly named as receiving a
grand jury subpoena. He reportedly is not a target of the criminal
probe.
   The inquiries are separate from a criminal investigation by the
Justice Department into allegedly widespread fraudulent trading
practices on the Chicago Board of Trade and Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, the nation's largest commodity markets.
   Jones, 34, is chairman of Tudor Investment Corp., which he
founded in 1984 and is considered the most prominent among more
than 50 traders from whom federal investigators have requested
information. The firm also was subpoenaed.
   The subpoenas, which reportedly were delivered last week, do not
imply any wrongdoing.
   Tudor president Mark Dalton issued a statement that Jones and
the firm ``were among the many traders and firms that received
civil subpoenas to provide information in connection with a CFTC
investigation of others.''
   ``Mr. Jones and Tudor understand that they are not the subject
of the investigation,'' he said. Dalton would not say whether the
government told the firm and Jones they were not targets.
   Market sources, who asked not to be named, also said Jones was
not a target.
   The CFTC reportedly is seeking information on Jones' dealings
with Mark B. Fisher and Effron, two futures traders who have been
mentioned as possible targets.
   U.S. Postal Service inspectors one week ago raided Fisher's
offices at the commodity exchanges as part of a federal grand jury
criminal investigation. His attorneys have denied any wrongdoing.
   Effron, 29, has been subpoenaed by the federal grand jury and
the CFTC, said his lawyer, Howard Schneider.
   ``In the grand jury probe they've indicated he is not a
target,'' Schneider said, ``and the CFTC hasn't indicated
anything.''
   Another reported target is Preston H. Semel, who runs a
brokerage in gold, silver and other commodities and was fined by
the New York Mercantile Exchange for an alleged trading scheme with
Fisher in 1985. Semel has refused to comment or provide the name of
his attorney.
   Jones, whose firm manages money for 15,000 customers, is a
director of the Futures Industry Association and board member of
the Cotton Exchange, where he reportedly made most of his money. He
also conducts ethics training classes with a former CFTC chairman
and is highly regarded in the industry.
   He runs a highly successful publicly offered futures fund, one
of what are known as commodity pools, in which a group of futures
investors pool funds run by money managers.
   A person familiar with the CFTC's order of investigation said
Wednesday it includes review of possible violations of rules
governing commodity pools. Under CFTC guidelines, those could
include use of customer funds for personal accounts or failing to
provide customers with necessary disclosure documents.
   The CFTC probe also reportedly examines violations that include
pre-arranged trading, use of advanced knowledge of customer trades
to trade for personal accounts and conducting of trades in order to
skirt tax obligations.
   The government has subpoenaed the Cotton Exchange, the New York
Mercantile Exchange, the Commodity Exchange and the Coffee, Sugar
and Cocoa Exchange seeking information on brokers. It also has
directly subpoenaed at least 26 traders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890511-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MidwestS&amp;Ls     05-11 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Midwest S&amp;Ls,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>District's Problems Described as `Quite Insignificant'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The problems remaining at savings and
loans in Iowa and four nearby states are insignificant when
compared with the troubles besetting the industry nationwide, a
federal regulator reports.
   ``Our members have a stronger position to work from than some
other regions,'' Thurman Connell, president of the Federal Home
Loan Bank of Des Moines, said in the bank's annual report. The Des
Moines office oversees thrift institutions in Iowa, Minnesota,
Missouri and North and South Dakota.
   The report also said that while overall operations were
unprofitable last year for the 176 savings and loans in the
district, combined outflows of deposits from those institutions
fell more than 25 percent from a year earlier and assets climbed to
record heights for a third straight year. It said that with most of
the district's previously insolvent thrifts in new, more secure
hands this year, there was an improved earnings outlook for 1989.
   The report was distributed as Congress wrestled with how to
finance the $50 billion cash infusion for savings and loan rescues
proposed by President Bush.
   ``Unfortunately for our five-state area, the president's plan
for resolving the troubles of the nation's thrift industry came
after the majority of District Eight insolvencies had been
resolved,'' Connell said. ``The remaining problems in the Eighth
District look quite insignificant when taken in a national
context.''
   The Des Moines district found new owners for 17 insolvent
thrifts last year, leaving just eight troubled institutions in the
region. Seven of those insolvent thrifts already have been placed
under federal conservatorship awaiting completion of congressional
action, and the eighth is scheduled for the same attention, said
Hassan Honarmand, a district spokesman.
   There are four Missouri problem thrifts, two in Iowa and one in
Minnesota now under the supervision of the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp.
   They are Midwest Federal Savings and Loan in Minneapolis; Sioux
Valley Savings and Loan of Cherokee and First Federal Savings and
Loan of Estherville in Iowa; and Blue Valley Savings and Loan in
Kansas City, Cass Federal Savings and Loan of St. Louis, Financial
Federal Savings and Loan of Joplin and First Federal Savings and
Loan of Southeast Missouri in Cape Girardeau all in Missouri.
   Honarmand said a state-chartered S&amp;L in Missouri, which he would
not further identify, would be placed under federal conservatorship
later this year.
   Nationwide, about 350 thrifts are listed as insolvent by the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board, while another 250 are described as
solvent but in need of government help. In 1988, 223 thrifts were
closed or rescued across the country.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank of Des Moines said 80 percent of its
member institutions were profitable last year and improved from
their performance of a year earlier. But widening losses at the
remaining institutions far offset those gains.
   Overall, thrifts in the Des Moines district posted a loss of 92
cents for each $100 in assets in 1988, close to the national
performance of a loss of 94 cents per $100.
   This widely recognized measure of profitability is called return
on average assets.
   For example, 43 thrifts in the district, representing the top 25
percent, posted what the agency called an ``exceptional'' return on
average assets of $1.10 for each $100. That compared with $1 in
profit for each $100 in assets a year earlier. But the bottom
quarter had combined losses of $4.06 for each $100 in assets in
1988, sharply higher than the overall losses of $1.40 for each $100
in assets for the same group in 1987.
   The district regulates 82 thrifts in Missouri, 45 in Iowa, 32 in
Minnesota, 12 in South Dakota and 6 in North Dakota.
   Connell said it appeared that consumer confidence has remained
fairly stable in the district.
   Despite the widespread coverage of the crisis in the thrift
industry, deposit outflows from member thrifts in the district fell
last year.
   Withdrawals exceeded deposits by $1.7 billion overall last year
in the district, but that was down from $2.3 billion in 1987. And
Honarmand said that when accumulated interest earnings were added
to the deposits remaining at district thrifts, there was a net
increase in deposits of $840 million last year.
   ``Most depositors are loyal to their local institutions and want
to continue doing business with them,'' Connell said. ``The bottom
line in the thrift industry is public confidence.''
</TEXT>
