<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   05-11 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bidder Gets Extension for Eastern Offer; America West Ups Shuttle
Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy court extended its bidding
deadline for Eastern Airlines for at least one potential suitor,
while a bidder for Eastern's lucrative Northeast shuttle raised its
offer and another airline offered to buy other assets.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland extended Wednesday's 5
p.m. EDT bidding deadline for an investor group led by Joseph
Ritchie, a prominent Chicago commodities trader, to give it more
time to receive financial information from strikebound Eastern.
   Separately, America West Airlines Inc. said it would pay a total
of $751 million for the Boston-New York-Washington shuttle and 10
Boeing 757 airliners, raising by $25 million the cash portion of
its initial $726 million bid.
   That price also would top a rival $365 million offer that
Eastern has accepted from developer Donald Trump for the shuttle.
   In another development, Eastern rival USAir Inc. offered $525
million for certain Eastern assets, including 15 Boeing 757s and
related equipment, ground facilities, airport landing slots and
three U.S.-Canadian routes.
   In a statement, USAir said its offer was for spare engines,
flight training simulators and other hardware related to the Boeing
757s; Eastern's maintenance hangars in Boston and Miami; airport
gates in 10 cities already served by USAir and its Piedmont
Airlines unit; and U.S.-Canadian routes between Pittsburgh and
Toronto, Baltimore-Washington and Ottawa, and Baltimore-Washington
and Montreal.
   Miami-based Eastern has been under Chapter 11 protection from
creditors since March 9, five days after the start of a Machinists
union strike supported by pilots and flight attendants that
virtually grounded the airline.
   The bankruptcy court must approve any sale of Eastern or any of
its businesses, such as the Northeast shuttle.
   Lifland has pushed for a sale as a means for returning the
carrier to full operations as soon as possible. Eastern insists the
airline is not for sale and is proceeding with a plan to rebuild as
a smaller carrier and raise $1.8 billion by selling aircraft and
other assets.
   The deal to sell the shuttle and its 21 Boeing 727 jetliners to
Trump still awaits the court's approval. Lifland scheduled a Monday
hearing on that deal.
   America West, a regional carrier based in Phoenix, Ariz., last
week submitted a $726 million offer for the shuttle and 10 Boeing
757 jetliners. Under its revised offer, America West stated it
would pay $415 million cash for the shuttle assets with the balance
paid in cash and assumption of obligations on the 10 airliners.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said in a phone interview from
Miami that although the airline had a deal with Trump, ``...we also
have a responsibility to evaluate other proposals'' and would
review the America West offer.
   Bruce Nobles, president of the Trump Shuttle, said the latest
America West offer did not affect Trump's position.
   ``We have a deal with Eastern,'' said Nobles. ``We have a blank
check sitting here waiting to be filled in.''
   Billionaire hotel executive Jay Pritzker already has proposed
buying all of Eastern for around $500 million, although he had not
previously submitted a formal offer, according to sources close to
the situation. An investor group led by William Howard, the former
chairman of Piedmont Airlines, also has expressed interest in
making a buyout proposal.
   The chairman of the committee representing Eastern's major
creditors confirmed Wednesday that bids were expected from the
Ritchie and Howard groups. Alan Boyd, chairman of Airbus Industrie
of North America, said neither consortium has detailed its
financing plans to the creditors.
   Neither Pritzker nor the Howard group would confirm whether they
had made firm proposals to the bankruptcy court by Wednesday.
   Another potential buyer who previously expressed interest,
takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn, had backed off a bit on Tuesday.
Trans World Airlines Inc., which is owned by Icahn, stated it
needed more time to discuss with its unions the feasibility of
integrating the TWA and Eastern workforces and was not prepared to
submit a formal bid for Eastern at this time.
   Icahn has held discussions with officials of Eastern's unions.
Last Friday, he informed the court of his interest in buying
Eastern's Philadelphia airport hub.
   Former baseball commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth, whose $464
million deal to buy Eastern collapsed in mid-April, was still
interested in acquiring the airline, sources close to Ueberroth
said Wednesday. However, it was unclear whether he would come forth
with a firm new buyout plan, the sources said.
   Following a recommendation by bankruptcy examiner David I.
Shapiro, Lifland decided that any bids submitted after Wednesday's
deadline would be disqualified except ``for good cause shown.''
   Lifland granted the two-day extension to Ritchie's group because
confidential Eastern financial data sought by the group was
accidentally sent to the wrong person, according to Harvey Miller,
Eastern's lead bankruptcy attorney. Ritchie is chairman of CRT
Group, a futures and options trading company based in Chicago.
   It was not immediately clear under what conditions Lifland would
accept late bids by others. Lifland, Shapiro and the principals of
the bidding groups did not return phone calls Wednesday seeking
comment.
</TEXT>
