<FIRST>r f PM-BrothelBuyout     05-11 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brothel Buyout,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mustang Ranch Stock Sale Halted After Marketing Efforts Stall</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Wallstreet one word is cq in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second attempt to turn America's
best-known house of ill repute into the country's first
publicly-owned bordello has stalled after the stock offering fell
$5 million short of its goal.
   Eric Walloga, whose American Wallstreet Securities Inc. is
underwriting the sale, said Wednesday his company had negotiated an
extension of the sale of stock in the Mustang Ranch until Oct. 31
to allow time to restructure the offer.
   In the meantime, the sale of common stock in Mustang Ranch, Inc.
has been halted and all the money received for the shares so far
will be returned to investors, Walloga said in a statement released
by his office in Tampa, Fla.
   ``The rules of the Securities and Exchange Commission ...
require that we make this move,'' he said. Walloga, the president
of American Wallstreet, was out of the office Wednesday and
unavailable for comment.
   Wednesday was the deadline for the three-month-old bid to take
the Mustang Ranch public through a $23.3 million stock offering at
$20 a share. Walloga said last week about 75 percent of the 1.165
million shares had been sold, leaving the company with a $5 million
shortfall.
   Walloga's statement said an amendment would be filed with the
SEC and the states that have approved sale of the stock to reflect
the terms of the new deal, which Walloga said would change the
types of securities Mustang Ranch Inc. would offer.
   ``No details of the newly structured offering could be released
at this time pending a response from the SEC to a request for an
interpretive ruling concerning a technical issue which arose in
developing the amendment to the offering,'' the statement said.
   Peter Perry, a Reno attorney and vice president of Mustang Ranch
Inc., said in the statement he expected the amendment to the
registration to be filed with the SEC by June 15.
   Perry would not comment specifically on the offer, citing SEC
rules which forbid parties in a stock offering to discuss them.
   Mustang Ranch Inc. is an investors' group composed primarily of
Reno businessmen and attorneys who are making a second attempt to
turn the brothel public.
   A 1985 bid by Strong Point, Inc., led by John Davis of Irvine,
Calif., fell through after failing to generate enough interest in
the $18 million proposal.
   The money raised in the current sale was to have provided $13
million to buy the 102-room brothel and its 440 acres of land from
Joe and Sally Conforte, $5 million in exchange for the Confortes'
promise not to set up a competing brothel and $5.3 million for
expansion, improvements and working capital.
   Conforte has been trying to sell the brothel 10 miles east of
Reno since 1985 when he was released from prison after serving 18
months on a tax conviction.
   He has said he expects most of the money from the sale to go to
the federal government in payment of his long-standing tax debt
plus the hefty interest and penalties it has run up.
</TEXT>
