<DOCNO> AP890511-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Hammer'sArt Bjt   05-11 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hammer's Art, Bjt,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholder Suits Say Millions in Oxy Money Wasted on Chairman's
Art</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Occidental Petroleum Corp. Chairman Armand
Hammer _ whose art collection includes works by Leonardo da Vinci
and Impressionists _ is wasting millions of dollars in company
funds on ``self-aggrandizing'' plans for a Hammer Museum of Art,
shareholders charged in two lawsuits.
   The suits, which became public Wednesday in Delaware Chancery
Court, seek court orders blocking further Occidental spending on
the planned museum, requiring return of money already committed and
canceling Hammer's employment contract with Occidental.
   ``Defendant Dr. Hammer has breached his duty of loyalty to
Occidental and its stockholders by instigating and forcing
Occidental to participate in his personal plan of
self-aggrandizement in creating his own personal museum,'' one suit
says.
   The 91-year-old Hammer, who carefully cultivates a media image
of international philanthropist and unofficial business envoy to
the Soviet Union, will fight the allegations as ``totally without
merit,'' a company spokesman said.
   The lawsuits, filed in the state where the oil-and-chemical
giant is incorporated, name both Occidental and its directors,
including Hammer, as defendants.
   The actions center on a first-quarter expense of $36 million to
purchase an annuity to fund the planned museum, on rent-free use of
company office space for museum purposes and on a corporate
commitment to fund construction of a building for the museum at a
cost estimated at $30 million to $50 million.
   Requests for a Hammer response were referred to Philadelphia
attorney Bruce Kauffman, who represents a special committee of the
Occidental board that approved the museum support.
   Kauffman said Occidental directors acted well within the law and
in keeping with their duty to the corporation in approving
charitable spending that would enhance the company's standing in
the community.
   ``All kinds of companies choose to spread their good will in
different ways,'' Kauffman said. ``We choose to spread our good
will in a way that will benefit hundreds of thousands of people. To
say for one minute that this is not going to benefit Occidental is,
in my opinion, just ridiculous.''
   One suit was filed by Alan R. Kahn, trustee for the estate of
Samuel Adason Jaffe, which holds 700 Occidental shares; the other
by Joseph Sullivan and Alan I. Brody, who describe themselves as
Occidental shareholders without detailing their holdings.
   They seek injunctions that, among other things, would bar
further Occidental support of the museum, including rent-free use
of company buildings; cancel compensation to Hammer; and require an
accounting of any losses the company incurred in connection with
the museum.
   They also allege that proxy material mailed to shareholders for
the company's upcoming annual meeting was misleading about the $36
million expenditure for the museum, including it as unallocated
corporate expenses.
   The Sullivan-Brody suit paints a particularly unflattering
portrait of Occidental's chairman and chief executive officer in
detailing a dispute with the Los Angeles County Museum of Art over
the future of his personal collection, said to be worth $250
million to $400 million.
   The collection includes works by Dutch, Flemish, German and
Italian masters; Impressionist works and a codex, or book of notes
and drawings by da Vinci.
   Last year, Hammer canceled what the museum portrayed as a
promise to donate his art to the county when museum officials
rejected conditions including posting a full-length portrait of the
industrialist at the entrance to the exhibit.
   Other conditions unacceptable to the museum, according the suit:
That the collection be kept intact forever and displayed under
Hammer's name; that names of other museum benefactors be removed
from galleries displaying Hammer's art; that the collection get a
special curator answerable to a Hammer foundation rather than to
the museum.
   The dispute led to Hammer's plan to build his own museum, the
suit says, adding: ``Unlike other wealthy collectors, Dr. Hammer
does not plan to build `his own museum' with his own ample funds.
Rather, Dr. Hammer is requiring Occidental to provide substantially
all the financial support.''
   Company attorney Kauffman disputed at least part of that, noting
the considerable value of the collection Hammer intended to
contribute to the project.
   Hammer, whose 1987 pay was $1.9 million, has held sway over
Occidental since 1957.
   Based on contacts he made during a post-World War II medical
mercy mission in the Soviet Union, he served as unofficial envoy
for the United States government during the Cold War. As relations
have thawed in recent years, he has led a parade of American
businesses into the Soviet Union, setting up joint ventures for
chemical plants and the like.
   Hammer, who holds a medical degree, has used his connections and
company jet to get American doctors to the scene of various
disasters, including the Chernobyl nuclear accident and the
Armenian earthquake.
</TEXT>
