<FIRST>r f PM-BilzerianTrial     05-11 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bilzerian Trial,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boyd Jefferies Takes Witness Stand Against Bilzerian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted stock brokerage founder Boyd L.
Jefferies has taken the witness stand for the third time in a
federal criminal securities law trial, this time saying he engaged
in four unlawful stock deals with Paul A. Bilzerian.
   Testifying Wednesday at Bilzerian's securities fraud trial at
federal court in Manhattan, Jefferies, who said he spoke on the
phone often but only met once with the Singer Co. chairman,
detailed their dealings in four stock transactions in 1985 and 1986.
   Jefferies testified that on four occasions either Bilzerian or
Jefferies' account executive Michael Landy asked him to purchase
large blocks of stock either for or from Bilzerian to hide the
stock's ownership.
   Then the prosecutor, Assistant U.S. Attorney David Brodsky,
asked Jefferies if he considered each deal ``lawful or unlawful.''
   ``Unlawful,'' Jefferies said four times.
   The indictment alleges that Jefferies, who founded the Los
Angeles-based brokerage house, Jefferies &amp; Co., secretly held stock
for Bilzerian in four unsuccessful takeover transactions involving
Cluett, Peabody &amp; Co., Hammerhill Paper Co., H.H. Robertson Co.,
and Armco Inc.
   The ruse allegedly was used to help Bilzerian secretly
accumulate large stock positions in companies he later would
attempt to take over.
   But on cross examination, defense attorney Arthur Mathews asked
Jefferies if he intended ``to commit any crimes in any transactions
with Mr. Bilzerian?''
   ``No,'' replied Jefferies, who earlier said he pleaded guilty to
two felony counts in a plea bargain with prosecutors.
   Bilzerian, 38, of Tampa, Fla., is accused of conspiracy,
violating securities and tax laws and making false statements in
connection with four failed takeover attempts in 1985 and 1986.
   If convicted, Bilzerian faces a maximum pealty of five years in
jail and a $250,000 fine on each count.
   Jefferies, 58, turned government informant in 1987 after he was
turned in by convicted stock speculator Ivan F. Boesky, and has
pleaded guilty to two securities-related felonies.
   He said he faces a maximum 10 years in prison and $500,000 in
fines although prosecutors are supposed to detail his cooperation
to the sentencing judge. Jefferies and his lawyer have said they
don't expect him to serve any prison time.
   It was the third time Jefferies has testified for the government
in a securities fraud case. He twice took the witness stand in the
stock manipulation trial of GAF Corp. and its vice chairman, James
T. Sherwin. Twice that case ended in a mistrial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
