<FIRST>r f PM-Mail-OrderTaxes 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mail-Order Taxes, 1st Ld-Writethru,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan to Tax Mail-Order Sales Debated on Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, No so, to CORRECT no to not; picks up 9th
graf, ``Many of; also moved general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spiegel, Land's End and L.L. Bean addicts
beware _ the nation's governors want you to begin paying sales
taxes on your mail-order shopping sprees.
   Governors, joined by state legislators and mayors, are urging
Congress to overturn a 22-year-old Supreme Court decision and
require large mail-order companies to collect sales taxes n sales
to out-of-state customers.
   As a result of that ruling, North Dakota Gov. George Sinner told
a news conference Wednesday, hometown merchants are at a decided
disadvantage and states, cities and counties are losing more than
$1.5 billion a year in tax revenue.
   ``Because state sales taxes run from 5 percent to 8 percent of
the cost of the goods sold, the unfair tax advantage by
out-of-state firms in sales taxes is greater than the average
profit margin of Main Street merchants,'' Sinner said. In fact, he
added, the average hometown merchant's profit margin is less than 3
percent.
   Opponents of the proposal held their own news conference to warn
that consumers won't put up with it.
   ``This will have the maximum irritation effect on tens of
millions of consumers who would have to do the tax calculations
every time they order,'' said Robert Levering, vice president of
the Direct Marketing Association.
   Sen. Robert W. Kasten Jr., R-Wis., whose state is home to Land's
End, added that the bill ``unfairly targets the elderly, the
handicapped, farm families and the millions of consumers who rely
on mail-order purchases for many of their basic needs.''
   Not so, said the National Governors' Association, which chose to
emphasize the bill's effect on well-heeled yuppies:
   ``Many of the goods sold by mail-order firms are expensive,
high-quality, designer-type goods that appeal to young urban
professionals: pastel sweaters, $24 cotton T-shirts, fancy
briefcases, electronic gizmos and exercise or recreational
equipment,'' the association said in a written statement.
   The Supreme Court held in 1967 that a company could not be
required to collect sales taxes on purchases from an out-of-state
company unless that company had a retail outlet in the state.
   Sears and J.C. Penney, for example, collect sales taxes on
catalog orders because they have retail stores in every state. But
Land's End, the giant mail-order clothing company in Wisconsin,
collects no tax on out-of-state shipments because it has no other
outlets.
   The National Governors' Association, the National League of
Cities and other government organizations are supporting a bill to
require large companies to collect tax on shipments to any state in
which they regularly solicit business. Thus, if Land's End shipped
a catalog to Tennessee, that would be interpreted as soliciting and
the company would have to collect the state's sales tax on
Tennessee orders.
   The bill is sponsored by Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, chairman of
the House Judiciary Committee. It would apply only to the estimated
5 percent of mail-order outlets whose sales exceed $12.5 million a
year. But those 5 percent account for 70 percent of mail-order
sales.
   Similar legislation stalled last year, and opponents, led by the
Direct Marketing Association, are geared up for the renewed battle.
   ``If this legislation were to pass, direct marketers would be
saddled with tax collection duties for over 7,000 municipal and
state tax jurisdictions,'' said Levering. ``That means we can be
audited by every one of those jurisdictions, even where our
companies don't have physical presence (in a state) and don't
receive benefits.''
   Across the Capitol, at the session sponsored by backers of the
bill, James Goldberg, counsel for the National Association of
Retail Dealers of America, said most mail-order customers charge
purchases to their credit cards and so would not have to calculate
the sales tax.
</TEXT>
