<FIRST>r f PM-Canada-Economy     05-11 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Economy,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forecasts of Economic Slowdown Follow Release of 1989-90 Budget</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires; Dollar amounts U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal budget that critics say does not do
enough to tackle inflation and deficit spending has aggravated
fears of economic bust after years of sometimes booming growth.
   Finance Minister Michael Wilson is sticking to his view that
inflationary pressures can be reduced and that new budget gives the
central bank ``the scope to reduce interest rates more quickly than
would otherwise be the case.''
   However, the Conference Board of Canada, an Ottawa-based think
tank, says in its budget analysis that the risk of recession has
grown as a result of the fiscal decisions announced last month.
   ``We think the economy is going to be very, very soft for the
next six months,'' James Frank, the board's chief economist, told
the Globe and Mail newspaper.
   Since a second straight majority government of the Progressive
Conservative Party was elected in November, Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney, Wilson and other senior officials have led a steady
drumbeat calling for a reduction of government debt.
   Although the 1989-90 budget raises taxes and cuts federal
spending in areas from the military to rail service and child care,
it still leaves a deficit of $25.6 billion _ up slightly from the
previous year's $25.2 billion deficit.
   Wilson says the new budget is the first step in bringing the
annual deficit down to $12.6 billion in four years.
   However, achieving that goal may depend on a drop in interest
rates, continued economic growth, and tough tax policies.
   George Vasic of the Data Resources forecasting firm says
Mulroney missed the chance to make more progress on the budget
deficit at the outset of his second term, when election worries are
at their lowest.
   ``It's a major opportunity that was squandered,'' he said. ``We
feel that there's about a 40 percent chance of a recession between
now and the end of 1990.''
   He said, however, that slower growth is more likely.
   Warren Jestin, chief economist of Scotiabank, is more
optimistic. He predicts growth of 3 percent this year slowing to 2
percent or less in 1990.
   The Canadian economy has grown, at times dramatically, since the
end of the 1982 recession. The gross national product rose beyond
inflation by 4 percent in 1987 and 4.5 percent in 1988.
   Inflation has been running about 4 percent each year, but
concern that the economy was overheating prompted Bank of Canada
governor John Crow to increase interest rates over the past year to
their current 12 percent levels.
   Forecasts of recession or slowdown have surfaced persistently in
Canada since the stock market crash of 1987, in large part because
of the long expansion.
</TEXT>
