<FIRST>r f PM-SpendingBill-Drexel     05-11 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending Bill-Drexel,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Want to Use Drexel Burnham Fine for Drug Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street corruption may provide the
windfall the government needs to finance its efforts against
illegal drug traffickers, some members of Congress say.
   Leaders of the House Appropriations Committee said Wednesday
that they are weighing a plan that would channel $150 million to be
collected in fines from Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. this year into
federal anti-drug initiatives.
   Under the proposal, the money would be used to pay for prison
improvements, additional law officers, grants to state and local
governments and other programs during the last months of fiscal
1989, which ends Sept. 30.
   The appropriations panel would claim the extra spending is not
adding to the federal deficit because it would be financed with the
unanticipated fines.
   ``Thus, in my way of thinking, it's an offset for that
spending,'' said Rep. Neal Smith, D-Iowa, chairman of the
Appropriations justice subcommittee, who proposed the idea.
   Drexel Burnham agreed last December to pay $650 million in fines
and restitution and plead guilty to six felonies to settle
securities fraud charges brought by the U.S. attorney's office in
Manhattan.
   The plan is expected to meet opposition from some Democrats and
Republicans who likely will argue that with an potential deficit of
more than $160 billion this year, the Drexel fine can hardly be
considered unaccounted-for money.
   In addition, some lawmakers have argued that fines collected by
the Securities and Exchange Commission should be used to strengthen
that agency's law enforcement efforts.
   The proposal is part of an effort by the Appropriations
Committee to revamp a $4.7 billion domestic spending bill for this
year, a measure rejected by the House last month because ot its
high cost.
   The bill contained money for veterans, college students,
anti-drug efforts and other programs.
   Included in the package was $726 million in new spending
authority from Smith's subcommittee for anti-drug programs, about
$300 million of which would have actually been spent this year.
   To make the overall bill more appealing, the Appropriations
Committee would offset most new spending with cuts in other
programs, thus reducing the package's impact on the federal deficit.
   The Appropriations Committee hopes to bring the new version of
the spending bill to the House floor next week, and Smith said he
expects the use of the Drexel Burnham money to be included.
   ``There is a general approval by the members of the committee of
this approach, but there is no concrete agreement,'' he said.
   The chairmen of the 13 Appropriations subcommittees have agreed
to drop from the bill $250 million for reparations to
Japanese-Americans who were held in internment camps during World
War II, and most of $153 million that would have been used for the
homeless.
   The final package will be less than $4.7 billion, but the total
will not be determined until the subcommittee chairmen meet again
next Tuesday.
</TEXT>
