<DOCNO> AP890511-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0745EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RollingRock-Labels     05-11 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rolling Rock-Labels,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rolling Rock Nears Solution to Label Problem ^Eds: also on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The makers of Rolling Rock beer believe they
have steered around a bottleneck and are nearing a solution on how
to comply with a new law requiring warning labels on beer bottles.
   The law requires that alcoholic beverage containers carry labels
warning of possible adverse health effects from drinking wine,
liquor or beer by Nov. 18.
   But Pennsylvania's Latrobe Brewing Co.'s distinctive green
Rolling Rock bottles carry painted, rather than paper, labels.
   Therefore, the law would make as many as 1 million cases of
Rolling Rock _ each containing 24 bottles of beer _ obsolete
because the cost to alter them is prohibitive.
   The answer may be a grace period during which Latrobe would be
permitted to print the warning on bottle caps instead of on the
containers.
   ``We're a small player and we don't want to send out a message
that something special is being done for Latrobe,'' Albert
Spinelli, vice president of operations, said Wednesday.
   ``All we're looking for is a time period to phase out the
existing bottles as we bring new bottles in,'' he said. ``In the
meantime, we've had samples made up with the (warning) message on
the cap, and it's legible.''
   Writing the 41-word warning on the cap would be only a temporary
solution. Congress specified that the warning must appear on
containers and that the print on bottles 12 ounces and larger must
be at least two millimeters tall.
   The law also would affect Rolling Rock's seven-ounce bottles.
   Rolling Rock has refused to change to a paper label because it
feels the painted label gives it its distinctive identity.
   Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., has received permission from the House
Appropriations Committee to insert language in a spending bill that
would grant Rolling Rock a grace period, Murtha spokesman Bill
Allen said Wednesday. The bill is likely to be considered by the
House within a week.
   It is uncertain how long Latrobe might have to fully comply with
the law. Latrobe has said it could take 10 years before the 24
million bottles wear out, or get broken or lost, although the
brewery does not expect to win a grace period nearly that long.
   On the Senate side, Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the author of the
law, has indicated he wants to accommodate Latrobe officials if he
can, according to aides to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa.
   ``Everybody seems to agree this is a unique situation,'' Allen
said. ``Everybody seems agreeable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
