<FIRST>r f BC-Mobil-SouthAfrica     05-11 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mobil-South Africa,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Preparing For Strike To Protest Mobil's Pullout Tactics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The union representing most
black Mobil Corp. employees in South Africa said Thursday it is
preparing for a strike to protest the U.S. company's refusal to
negotiate terms of its planned pullout.
   Pat Horne, a spokeswoman for the Chemical Workers Industrial
Union, said a strike ballot was planned for next week.
   If approved, she said, a strike would be launched against Mobil
and other multinational companies that have not complied with a
union demand to negotiate terms favorable to workers in the event
of disinvestment from South Africa.
   Mobil, the largest U.S. company operating in South Africa,
announced April 28 that it was selling its holdings in the country
to the General Union Mining Corp., a conglomerate known as Gencor,
which owns a petroleum company.
   The sale price was not disclosed, and the ownership change will
not take effect until various financial arrangements are completed.
   Mobil said Gencor had pledged to continue the company's
employment policies and honor all existing agreements with the
union. But union officials nonetheless were angered, saying Mobil
had rebuffed past attempts to open negotiations by insisting there
were no plans for disinvestment.
   Of Mobil's 2,800 employees in South Africa, about 1,500 are
black, including about 1,200 represented by the chemical workers
union.
   The union had approached several foreign companies, including
Mobil, with a request for certain arrangements in the event of
disinvestment. Among the demands were 12-month advance notice,
guarentees of job security and full disclosure of the terms of sale.
   The union has applied to the Industrial Court for an order
halting the planned Mobil sale. A hearing on the application began
Tuesday, but the case was postponed until May 24 and Mobil
representatives said they would try to provide the union with full
information about the pullout.
   In a related development this week, a syndicate of black and
Indian businessmen from Natal Province, site of the main Mobil
refinery, said they would try to outbid Gencor for Mobil's assets.
   A spokesman for the group, Mangalpersaid Hariram, said the
businessmen had access to about $120 million.
   Scores of U.S. companies have withdrawn from South Africa in
recent years, citing economic considerations and pressure from the
anti-apartheid movement. Mobil Chairman Allen Murray said the
disinvestment dceision was motivated by ``business
considerations,'' including U.S. legislation which has made it more
difficult for American companies to make profits in South Africa.
</TEXT>
