<HEAD>WestPoint Pepperell Fires 150 Management Employees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point Pepperell Inc., as
anticipated, has announced it is cutting roughly 10 percent of its
high-level employees at the textile giant's headquarters.
   The company said Wednesday 150 employees would be dismissed in
an effort to speed decision-making and improve the company's
competitiveness following its $3 billion acquisition earlier this
year by Farley Industries Inc.
   No plant workers will be affected by the restructuring,
Pepperrell said.
   William Farley, chairman of Chicago-based Farley Industries,
said recently that cost-cutting measures at the corporate
headquarters would be coming as soon as possible.
   Dismissed workers will receive a minimum three months' severance
pay and company-paid medical, insurance and other workers' benefits
for a year.
   The restructuring will ``control overhead and remove layers of
bureaucracy between decisions and decision-makers, and allow us to
move faster in a fast-moving world,'' the company's statement said.
   ``WestPoint Pepperell will be stronger, leaner and more able to
deal with international competition,'' the statement said.
