<FIRST>r f PM-GeorgiaMarble     05-11 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Georgia Marble,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Marble to Be Sold for $325 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia Marble Co., which provided marble for the
Lincoln Memorial and part of the U.S. Capitol in Washington, has
agreed to be acquired by First Chicago Corp.'s venture capital unit
for about $325 million in cash.
   The acquisition is to be completed by the end of the month, the
companies said Wednesday.
   Georgia Marble was a unit of the Jim Walter Corp. until last
year, when Walter was acquired by the New York investment firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. for $2.44 billion.
   The First Chicago venture unit, owned by the First National Bank
of Chicago, participated in the deal for Walter, which is now known
as Hillsborough Holdings Corp. and is based in Tampa, Fla.
   Proceeds from the Georgia Marble sale are expected to be used to
help repay debt from the earlier deal.
   Sam Mencoff, vice president of the venture capital unit, said
discussions concerning the acquisition began in February. He said
no changes are planned for the 105-year-old Atlanta-based company.
   Georgia Marble had sales last year of $126 million. The company
does not release its earnings figures, but President A.L. Gay Jr.,
who will remain as top executive, said the company has ``been
profitable for many years.''
   Georgia Marble has about 1,100 employees, runs eight quarries in
the state and makes industrial fillers, landscaping and swimming
pool materials and other building materials.
   Georgia Marble's stone also was used in the construction of
Chicago's Field Museum and the New York Stock Exchange, Gay said.
</TEXT>
