<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 0955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Soviet-USPollutionAgreement     05-11 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Soviet-US Pollution Agreement,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Superpowers to Cooperate to Fight Oil Spills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Soviet Union formally
pledged Thursday to help each other fight pollution emergencies in
northern waters like the oil tanker spill that fouled sections of
Alaska's coastline this spring.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and U.S.
Secretary of State James A. Baker III signed the agreement on the
last day of Baker's two-day visit to Moscow. It pledges superpower
cooperation in combating spills of oil and other pollutants in the
Bering and Chukchi seas between Alaska and Siberia.
   The Soviet news agency Tass said the agreement provides for the
development of a ``joint plan of drastic measures'' in the event of
a spill. Each country is required to notify the other immediately
of a pollution emergency, and U.S. and Soviet officials will hold
joint exercises on fighting ocean pollution, Tass said.
   ``The signing of the agreement is a major step toward developing
Soviet-American cooperation in dealing with the consequences of
ecological disaster at sea,'' Oleg Khalimonov, an official in the
Soviet Merchant Marine Ministry, told Tass.
   ``The developed mechanism of interaction will allow specialists
to define within hours the scope of an accident, map out joint
measures to overcome its consequences and get down immediately to
their implementation,'' Khalimonov said. ``Earlier such procedures
took days and sometimes whole weeks.''
   Tass said the cooperation envisaged by the agreement began to
function even before Baker and Shevardnadze signed the formal
document. A Soviet ship designed to skim the surface of the sea was
hired to help clean up the oil spilled by an Exxon tanker off
Alaska in late March.
   However, Exxon officials, who were paying the Soviets $15,000 a
day for the aid, said Tuesday the ship was being sent home because
it was not designed to handle the hardened, taffylike mass the oil
spilled by the tanker has turned into.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
