<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Viacom     05-11 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Viacom,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boosted by Sales of Two Cable Systems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viacom Inc. Thursday reported earnings of nearly
$200 million for the first quarter, reflecting the sale of two
cable systems and an improvement from the previous year's
first-quarter loss.
   The communications and entertainment company said the earnings
of $199.1 million, or $3.73 a share, in the three months ended
March 31 compared with a loss of $61.1 million a year earlier.
   A pretax gain of $304.8 million on the sale of the Long Island
and Cleveland cable systems boosted earnings in the first quarter,
Viacom said. Some of the $545 million of proceeds from the sales
were used to repay a portion of Viacom's bank debt.
   First-quarter revenue amounted to $341.1 million, 16.4 percent
above the $293.1 million of revenue in the first three 1988 months.
   Viacom, which owns the Showtime movie channel and other cable
operations, said MTV networks were strong in advertising sales and
affiliate fees.
   Revenue and profit in the entertainment division benefited
significantly from the domestic syndication of the popular
television program, The Cosby Show, the company said.
   Viacom earlier this week filed suit against Time Inc. and Time's
Home Box Office and its other cable TV holdings. Viacom is seeking
$2.4 billion in damages because it says Time is engaging in unfair
practices that are undermining competition in the pay-TV business.
