<FIRST>u f PM-Avon-Amway 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon-Amway, 1st Ld-Writethru,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Repeats It Is Not For Sale After $2 Billion Amway Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs on Amway plan to sell retail fragrance business;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, Analysts predicted ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. said today it would sell Avon
Products Inc.'s prestige fragrance business if its attempt to buy
Avon for more than $2 billion succeeds.
   The business includes higher-priced perfumes like Giorgio
Beverly Hills, Oscar de la Renta, Cher, Valentino, Perry Ellis and
Deneuve, which are sold in stores instead of by Avon's
person-to-person sales force.
   Avon said the business is expected to run up sales of more than
$300 million this year. Spokesman John Cox said the company had no
comment on Amway's stated plan, which was in a filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Amway made its offer for Avon on Wednesday and urged its larger
rival to stop its ``knee-jerk, defensive activities.'' Avon said it
was not for sale, although its board of directors would evaluate
the offer.
   Analysts predicted a long battle, complicated by the culture
clash between Amway's patriotic, pep-rally style and its larger
rival's image as the home of the refined Avon Lady.
   Amway, in partnership with Minneapolis investor Irwin Jacobs,
owns 10.3 percent of Avon's outstanding common shares, but Jacobs
is not participating in the purchase offer, Amway said.
   Avon rose $3.87{ a share at $39.87{ in New York Stock Exchange
consolidated trading, above Amway's $39-a-share offer. The spread
between the stock price and Amway's offer indicated speculators
were betting a higher bid would emerge from Amway or another suitor.
   However, there also was speculation that Avon management would
succeed in blocking the takeover, or that Amway would not be able
to arrange financing for its offer.
   Analysts disagreed over whether a much higher bid for Avon was
justifiable. While some valued the stock at up to $50 a share,
Andrew Shore of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. valued Avon at no more
than about $41 a share based on its cash flow.
   Amway's bid places a value of $2.1 billion on Avon, based on
nearly 54 million outstanding Avon common shares. Amway would also
have to acquire 18 million preferred shares which could be
converted into common in the event of a takeover, adding about $700
million to the price.
   ``After careful consideration, we have concluded that our
respective businesses are complementary ...,'' Amway's letter said.
   Amway reserved the right to lower its offering price if Avon
took further defensive actions. It asked for a response to its
offer from the board of directors by 5 p.m. EDT on May 24.
   Amway assured Avon sufficient financing would be available in
the form of bank loans.
   In a letter responding to Amway released late Wednesday, Avon
repeated that it was not for sale but said the board ``will review
your proposal in due course, consistent with its fiduciary
responsibilities.''
   Avon spokesman John Cox also said Amway's proposal was
``conditional and unfinanced.''
   Avon sells cosmetics, toiletries and household products and
recorded worldwide sales of $3.06 billion last year. Most of its
1.5 million sales representatives are women who sell part-time,
either door-to-door or to friends and co-workers.
   Amway is a private consumer products sales company in Ada,
Mich., closely held by co-founders Jay Van Andel and Richard DeVos.
It has more than 1 million distributors and recorded retail sales
of $1.8 billion in its last fiscal year. In an effort to block a
possible bid, Avon this week filed a federal suit against the
partnership in U.S. District Court in Manhattan on the grounds that
Amway and Jacobs had not complied with federal securities laws
ownership disclosure requirements.
   Avon also has asked a New York state court to rule on the legal
validity of the company's shareholder rights stock plan, known as a
poison pill, aimed at making a hostile takeover prohibitively
expensive.
   William Nicholson, Amway's chief operating officer, said Amway
informed Jacobs as a courtesy that it was making a bid.
   Jacobs was traveling Wednesday and not reachable for comment, a
person in his office said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
