<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were modestly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, partly
in response to forecasts for rain in key crop-growing areas.
   The National Weather Service's new six-to-10 day outlook, issued
late Wednesday, calls for rain next week in the central Plains and
the western Corn Belt, two areas that have not shared in the
general recovery from last summer's drought.
   The soybean and corn markets also were pressured by expectations
for showers this weekend in the Midwest, analysts said.
   Additional selling of soybean futures stemmed from Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter's statement this morning that the
Agriculture Department has not decided whether to subsidize the
sale of U.S. soybean oil to the Soviet Union. The market had
expected a subsidized sale to be announced.
   Cautious trading was expected today ahead of this afternoon's
USDA revised estimates of the U.S. winter wheat crop, and of world
supply and demand for corn and soybeans.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 2{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.24 a bushel; corn was 1} cents
to 3{ cents lower with May at $2.77} a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
3 cents lower with May at $1.85 a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to
6\ cents lower with May at $7.52 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were lower in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .25 cent higher with June at
72.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .20 cent
higher wiith May at 77.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to
.32 cent lower with June at 48 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .80 cent to .90 cent lower with May at 35 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower on Wednesday while pork
futures advanced.
