<FIRST>u f PM-Minorco-GoldFields     05-11 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minorco-Gold Fields,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Won't Hold Minorco in Contempt for Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tangled takeover battle between the two of
the largest gold producers took another twist today as a federal
judge declined to hold Minorco S.A. in contempt of court _ for now.
   South African-controlled Minorco, largest gold producer in the
noncommunist world, has been trying to acquire rival British-based
Consolidated Gold Fields PLC since last fall.
   Gold Fields and its U.S. subsidiary, Newmont Mining Corp., sued
in New York to block the takeover and U.S. District Judge Michael
Mukasey issued an injunction _ blocking Minorco from acquiring more
Gold Fields shares on antitrust grounds.
   Minorco, incorporated in Luxembourg, already held almost 30
percent of Gold Fields' shares and has tenders for about 25 percent
more although Mukasey's injunction bars Minorco from buying those
shares.
   Gold Fields owns 49 percent of Newmont, the largest U.S. gold
producer.
   On Tuesday, Britain's Panel on Takeovers and Mergers ordered
Gold Fields to drop out of the American lawsuit, leaving Newmont as
the only obstacle to the $5.9 billion takeover. Minorco said it
would try to find a third-party bidder for Newmont.
   But Newmont asked Mukasey to hold Minorco in contempt, claiming
Minorco's maneuvering to try and find a buyer for Newmont, as a way
of forcing the American concern out of the litigation, violated
Mukasey's injunction.
   Mukasey, however, declined to find Minorco in contempt for the
time being.
   In a two-page order issued early today, Mukasey said he would
entertain another request to hold Minorco in contempt of court if
it attempted to alter Gold Fields' interest in Newmont so that it
couldn't vote its shares, which total 49.3 percent.
   Newmont expressed concerns at a hearing Wednesday that if
Minorco could get a third party to acquire a large stake in the
U.S. concern they could effectively force it to drop the law suit
blocking the takeover.
</TEXT>
