<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-JobTraining 2ndLd-Writethru   05-11 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Job Training, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Proposes Rewrite of Program Quayle Helped Draft</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new to raise time element, demand for state improvements,
add meeting with Bush planned; pickup pvs 5th graf, ``But JTPA''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration today proposed
rewriting the nation's major jobs training program, which was
co-authored by Vice President Dan Quayle, to direct most spending
to the poor and teen-agers.
   It also warned states that their programs will have to be
improved to receive federal support.
   ``For years, the government has been distributing money to youth
programs in a fragmented and piecemeal fashion, and sometimes
without clear expectations of what these youths should achieve,''
Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole told the Senate subcommittee on
employment and productivity.
   Mrs. Dole and three JTPA participants who attended the hearing
were meeting with President Bush this afternoon in a session
designed to demonstrate the president's support for the changes.
   The amendments would significantly change the Job Training
Partnership Act created by Quayle, then a Republican senator from
Indiana, and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy. Mrs. Dole said the revisions
were necessary because of the changing American workforce, not
because of any major flaws in the program.
   ``But JTPA can be made even better,'' she told the subcommittee,
which has jurisdiction over the act. ``Funds do not always reach
the individuals and areas who need help the most. In some
communities it is felt that the program does not always result in
good jobs and a higher standard of living.''
   The changes aim at ending a practice that has prompted criticism
of JTPA and other training programs, the ``creaming'' of applicants
with some marketable skills in order to place them quickly in jobs
with little future.
   They also would also separate youth-training efforts from the
various adult programs in which they are now found. And both the
state and federal governments would be required to do a far better
job coordinating training programs with education, counseling and
other services provided by federal, state and local governments.
   Most of the changes were recommended by an advisory panel named
by former Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin. Some also have been
suggested by subcommittee members, including the panel's chairman,
Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   Simon told Mrs. Dole he was sure that Democrats and Republicans
could work out minor differences in their approaches to amending
JTPA.
   ``I think we're going to get a good bill out of this committee
that we're all going to be able to agree on,'' he said.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, called JTPA ``the singularly important
work of this committee during the Reagan years,'' but said changing
work-force demographics made revisions necessary.
   Mrs. Dole dedicated most of her testimony to how the changes
would improve training for teen-agers, something she has said would
be among her highest priorities as secretary.
   She said all youths and half the adults seeking enrollment in
JTPA programs would need to overcome illiteracy, other basic skills
deficiencies or a poor school record. Teen parents and the homeless
also would be given preference.
   And, for the first time, employers who accepted JTPA money to
help pay for summer jobs for youths would be required to provide
some form of approved education or training.
   The changes, Mrs. Dole said, are designed to address projected
shortages in the labor force and the related ``skills gap''
exacerbating shortages for jobs in high-tech and other industries.
   Department officials have said the amendments, if approved,
likely would require a modest reduction in the number of people
served by JTPA. Mrs. Dole made no reference to that in her prepared
testimony.
   The federal government allocated $2.4 billion for JTPA this year
and Bush has requested stable funding for next year. JTPA programs
are expected to serve 1.9 million people this year.
   Because most of the money is spent to support programs
administered by state and local agencies, the proposed changes
include a number of guidelines those agencies would have to meet
before being deemed eligible for JTPA funding.
   At the state and local level, the proposed changes would for the
first time require individual assessments of prospective trainees
and, for those accepted into the programs, an individually tailored
program to meet the distinct education, training and placement
needs of each trainee.
   Removed would be guidelines that encouraged rapid job placement,
something JTPA critics have said leads to ``creaming'' and
placement of trainees in low-skill jobs with few career
possibilities.
   Instead, program administrators would be encouraged to offer
more thorough training, with their efforts monitored through a
follow-up survey to determine a trainee's progress in the job
market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
