<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-GrandMet     05-11 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Grand Met,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports 27 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC, the British food and
liquor group that acquired U.S. food giant Pillsbury Co., on
Thursday reported a 27 percent gain in earnings for the first half
of the year.
   The improvement came on strong gains in all of the company's
major areas of activity, particularly in foods.
   Grant Met said earnings for the six months to March 31 came to
205 million pounds or $342 million, compared with 161 million
pounds in the comparable 1988 period.
   Earnings per share came to 22.9 pence or 38 cents, vs. 18.4
pence a year earlier, the company said.
   Sales jumped 40 percent to $4.04 billion pounds or $6.7 billion,
with Pillsbury accounting for $1.3 billion of that figure. The year
earlier sales totaled 2.88 billion pounds.
   Pillsbury, acquired for $5.7 billion in a takeover completed
Jan. 4, has ``firmly established Grand Metropolitan as a major
international operator in food and in retailing,'' said Grand Met
Chairman Allen Sheppard.
   Grand Met described Pillsbury's contribution as expectedly good,
helping to triple earnings in the foods division to 106 million
pounds or $177 million. Sales in the food units more than doubled
to 1.24 billion pounds.
   Earnings were strong in the company's other major areas of
business as well.
   Grand Met does not report quarterly results, which aren't
required under British law.
</TEXT>
