<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 2200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-FutureInvestments Adv14   05-11 1125</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Future Investments, Adv14,1158</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday May 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>What's Left to Invest In? Today's Dreams May Be Tomorrow's Gold Mine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Graphic in AP Access under VENTCAP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   LaVonne Raney took a chance in a fledgling electronics firm
she'd read about and bought a few shares at $15 each.
   The time was the early '60s. The company was Teledyne Inc. Since
then, its stock has shattered the stratosphere, trading lately at
around $350 a share even after several splits.
   ``That was my biggest winner. It took three of us around the
world twice,'' recalled Mrs. Raney, of Columbus, Ohio, an amateur
stock dabbler who has long since cashed her Teledyne treasure.
   There may not be any Teledynes left in the twilight of the 20th
century. But that hasn't stopped investors from pouring billions of
dollars into what they see as potential gold mines _ startup
businesses with products and services ranging from robot cashiers
to toxic-waste neutralizers.
   A California company, for example, is working on a system that
would prevent waste through recycling. Another is trying to perfect
chemical-free purified water from industrial sewage.
   Others see riches in warehouse-like stores of the future that
eliminate the middleman or take customer orders via sophisticated
computers.
   ``Hitting it right usually requires a combination of foresight
and luck,'' said Dennis Sughrue, a researcher at Needham,
Mass.-based Venture Economics Inc., which tracks trends in
speculative investments.
   The foresight-luck mix was electronics in the '60s and computers
in the 70s. People who foresaw that a company hatched in someone's
garage would grow into today's Apple Computer Inc., for example,
would have multiplied their investment many times over.
   But investing in high-risk businesses is not for the timid. Like
the professional poker plays say, don't bet what you can't afford
to lose.
   ``For every Apple ... there are probably 30 to 40 other
companies you could lose money on,'' said Barry R. Feirstein,
managing director of Equitable Capital Management Corp. ``It's very
difficult for an individual investor ... to get in the ground floor
of something unless it's an industry he knows.''
   Even Mrs. Raney, who profited enormously by beating the crowd on
Teledyne, admits she stumbled into it and prefers to invest in more
proven companies.
   Professional venture capitalists aren't flocking to any
particular industry. A report by Venture Economics shows that all
the nearly $4 billion put in young companies in 1987 _ the latest
year for which complete data was available _ was spread out, with
no industry getting more than 15 percent.
   Experts envision growth in specific sectors in communications,
consumer products and services, computer hardware and software and
medicine, the Venture Economics data shows. Other areas receiving
adventurous-investor interest include electronics, industrial
products, biotechnology and energy.
   ``Within each industry there's a narrowly focused niche, and if
you hit it right you can make it big,'' said Sughrue.
   Finding that niche is the hard part. ``We look at probably 500
to 800 business plans a year from people coming to us with ideas,''
said John B. Mumford, managing general partner at Crosspoint
Venture Partners of Los Altos, Calif.
   ``In addition, we go to a lot of trade shows, industry meetings,
read literature in a variety of areas and try to forecast where
opportunites may be,'' he said.
   The maturing population of baby boomers, born between 1946 and
1964, are likely to play an important role in what's valuable in
the future.
   Cheryl Russell, editor-in-chief of American Demographics
magazine and author of ``100 Predictions for the Baby Boom,'' says
middle-aged boomers will transform the United States into a more
conservative, affluent nation, with the home the center of life.
   Here are a few key growth areas as seen by forward-thinking
investment professionals:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Automation</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Severe labor shortages mean machines could replace humans for
tasks that range from cashiering to burger flipping to gasoline
dispensing. Sughrue says Checkrobot Inc. of Deerfield Beach, Fla.,
has developed an automated supermarket checkout system, and ByVideo
Inc. of Sunnyvale, Calif., is developing a system that can take
retail sales orders.
   Feirstein says automated bank-teller machine makers such as
Diebold Inc. of Canton, Ohio, also could expand in this field.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Communications</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Services Digital Networks, which allow voices,
computer data and video signals to be transmitted over the same
phone lines through digital signals, are growing rapidly. The
underlying technology should make video conferences more common,
for example. Giants such as International Business Machines Corp.
and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. are dominating but smaller
companies like Parigain Technologies of Torrance, Calif., could
emerge as leaders, said Mumford.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Computers</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Predictions are tough because technology cycles shift quickly.
Timothy P. Bajarin, executive vice president of Creative Strategies
Research International of San Jose, Calif., said the trend today is
toward smaller computers with greater capabilities and bigger
memories. Prairietek Inc. of Boulder, Colo., is an example of a
little-known company working in this area, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Health Care</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation is growing so rapidly in health care that many
corporate planners are aggressively seeking ways to cut costs. Look
for an emergence in mail order prescriptions from pharmaceutical
giants such as Baxter International Inc. of Deerfield, Ill.,
Feirstein said. Specialized treatment may also become more
prevalent. Mumford said he's backing a Concord, Calif., company
known as NeuroCare Corp., developing non-hospital rehabilitation
for patients who've suffered head injuries.
   Biotechnology treatments for afflictions ranging from cancer to
AIDS should become more common in the middle to late 1990s, many
experts say.
   ``They're taking a lot of the things developed over the past 10
years and now using them both for disease treatment and
diagnostics,'' said Mumford. Poised for possible growth, experts
say, are companies like Biosurface Technology Inc. of Cambridge,
Mass., which is developing synthetic skin.
   This area is especially risky. San Francisco-based Genentech
Inc.'s stock skyrocketed before slumping on slower-than-expected
sales of its blood clot dissolving drug, TPA.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Retail</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Mumford says tomorrow's consumers will want exceptionally cheap
prices, superior services or both. He and others see an emergence
in warehouse distributors that cut prices by selling directly to
customers. ``Investments in that area nearly doubled from '86 to
'87,'' said Sughrue. Staples, a Newton, Mass., retailer that sells
bargain office supplies warehouse-style, is already becoming
popular.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Waste Management</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Pollution issues ranging from the global warming trend to
solid-waste disposal are becoming more acute. Experts say companies
such as Clean Harbors Inc. of Braintree, Mass. stand to do well.
But Mumford says waste prevention is a potential gold mine. Athens
Corp. in Oceanside, Calif., for example, is developing a chemical
process that recycles hazardous wastes, and National Water
Management Co. of San Jose, Calif., is devising a system that
purifies industrial wastewater without using chemicals.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Feb. 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
