<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     05-11 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firm In Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong demand in the absence of central bank
intervention drove the U.S. dollar higher against the major
currencies in European trading on Thursday.
   Gold prices also rose after dipping in Asia.
   Dealers said the news that U.S. retail sales in April rose by a
lower than expected 0.4 percent failed to shake confidence in the
American currency.
   One London dealer said the day's performance confirmed the
underlying demand for dollars and the market's reluctance to sell
them.
   The central banks again made no effort at a concerted
intervention to bring the dollar's exchange rate down by selling
dollars, although dealers said they can be expected to enter the
market if the dollar rises much above 1.92 West German marks.
   The dealers said the absence of intervention suggests that the
central banks tacitly acknowledged their sales of dollars had been
unable to bring the exchange rate down.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6655 late Thursday, cheaper
for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.6717.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Wednesday's late rates: 1.9135 West German marks, up from 1.9047;
1.7060 Swiss francs, up from 1.6925; 6.4665 French francs, up from
6.4645; 2.1580 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1500; 1,395.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,390.125; 1.1870 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1849.
   Gold bullion prices improved slightly in Europe. Gold traded
late in London, the major market, at a bid price of $379.00 a troy
ounce, up from $377.25. The late bid price in Zurich was $378.20,
up from $376.75.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $377.25, down from $378.25.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.66 a troy
ounce, down from $5.68.
</TEXT>
