<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     05-11 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose-Fell $2.9 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 468 money market mutual
funds rose $2.9 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to $307.06 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $1.2 billion increase in the funds' assets
the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund
trade group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $304.17 billion in the week
ended May 3, 1989.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 232 general purpose funds rose $1.03 billion to $100.80
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds increased $573.5 million
to $129.47 billion, and assets of 141 institutional funds rose
$1.29 billion to $76.80 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds in the
week ended Tuesday was 9.15 percent, unchanged from the previous
week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade journal
based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 9.17 percent from 9.16 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
unchanged at 34 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts was to
6.63 percent as of Wednesday, unchanged from a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged from a week earlier at 5.15 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 9.31
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 9.34 the
previous week. Yields were 9.48 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
9.51 percent; 9.27 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 9.32 percent;
and 9.18 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 9.20 percent.
</TEXT>
