<FIRST>u f AM-Avon-Amway 1stLd-Writethru f0194 05-11 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon-Amway, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0194,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amway Intends to Sell Avon's Retail Unit if Takeover Succeeds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 17th graf to UPDATE with closing stock price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. plans to spin off Avon Products
Inc.'s retail operation, comprising the popular Giorgio perfume and
other fragrances, if its $2 billion takeover bid for Avon succeeds,
Amway said Thursday.
   The company disclosed in a document submitted to the Securities
and Exchange Commission that it would retain Avon's worldwide
direct selling division if acquires its much larger rival.
   Put up for sale would be the business responsible for fragrances
Avon owns that are sold by department stores and other retailers,
but not by the independent sales representatives who offer Avon's
makeup, toiletries and jewelry.
   Amway also said it would continue Avon's strategy of selling its
interests in the health care services field.
   The retail operation includes higher-priced, ``prestige''
perfumes such as Giorgio Beverly Hills, Red, and Uninhibited by
Cher. Avon expects to more than $300 million in retail division
sales this year.
   Most of Avon's sales, which totaled $3.06 billion in 1988, are
made through an international sales force of about 1.5 million
representatives.
   William Nicholson, Amway's chief operating officer, said in a
telephone interview that several parties have expressed interest in
buying the Avon retail division. He declined to identify them.
   Several consumer products companies have stated their intentions
to expand and a well-established, successful prestige perfume line
might be a lucrative addition.
   Nicholson said Amway finds Avon an attractive takeover prospect
partly because ownerhip of Avon would open the door to markets
Amway has been trying to enter.
   ``Avon is well established in some international markets that'd
we'd love to get into,'' he said, naming Mexico and Brazil as
examples.
   Latin American countries have sufficient incomes to support
significant growth in their direct sales markets. So far, Amway is
operating only in Guatemala and Panama, he said.
   Amway also was motivated to pursue Avon by the opportunity to
turn Avon's sales representatives into distributors of a wider
array of products.
   Amway, a privately held company based in Ada, Mich., has about 1
million distributors around the world selling Amway household,
personal care and environmental products. Amway distributors also
sell Tandy computer gear, MCI Communications services, office
coffee making equipment and other brand name products.
   Nicholson said Avon has failed so far to capitalize on its
cosmetics business and broaden it into a full health and beauty
aids operation. Amway's cosmetic interests represent only a small
portion of the company's operations so an acquisition of Avon would
cause little duplication.
   Amway's $39-a-share takeover proposal places a value of about
$2.1 billion on the company based on nearly 54 million outstanding
Avon common shares. Amway also would have to acquire 18 million
preferred shares which could be converted into common in the event
of a takeover, adding about $700 million to the price.
   Speculators on Wall Street have indicated they believe that a
higher bid may be forthcoming.
   Avon shares closed at $39.50, off 37{ cents, in consolidated New
York Stock Exchange trading Thursday, after gaining $3.87{ on
Wednesday.
   Avon Chairman James Preston has said repeatedly the company is
not for sale but has said Avon's board would give Amway's offer
consideration.
   To bolster its defense against Amway, Avon has sued Amway and
its investment partner Irwin Jacobs. The partnership has said they
own about 10.3 percent of Avon common stock.
   Jacobs, a Minneapolis investor, is not involved in Amway's
takeover offer. But in its SEC filing, Amway said Jacobs may
``explore the possibility of purchasing'' some of Avon's assets if
the takeover succeeds but ``no agreement, arrangement or
understanding has been reached.''
   Avon spokesman John Cox said the company had no comment on
information in Amway's filing.
   Nicholson said Amway is awaiting a response from Avon.
   ``We believe that the board will invite us in for discussion and
we're waiting for that invitation,'' Nicholson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
