<FIRST>u f AM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru f0218 05-11 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0218,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Minimum Wage Bill; Both Sides Mull Post-Veto Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf with Mrs. Dole reax after 5th graf pvs, There
is ...; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted Thursday to raise the minimum
wage to $4.55 an hour by October 1991, leaving only a final Senate
vote before the bill goes to President Bush, who has promised to
veto it.
   In the first major domestic policy dispute of the Bush
administration, neither house of Congress has backed down despite
Bush's insistence that the minimum should be raised only to $4.25
by January 1992 _ and then only if the proposal allows employers to
pay a lower ``training wage'' to new workers for six months.
   The minimum is now $3.35, where it has been since 1981.
   The only congressional action still required is a Senate vote on
the bill drafted by House-Senate negotiators, and that could come
as early as next week.
   There is virtually no doubt that Bush will follow through on his
promise to veto the measure and the 247-172 House vote for passage
suggested the Democrats remain short of the two-thirds majority it
would need to override the president.
   ``The House insisted on sending President Bush a bill that would
cost hundreds of thousands of Americans their opportunity to work _
a bill he most certainly will veto,'' Labor Secretary Elizabeth
Dole said shortly after the House vote.
   Still, Democratic leaders in both chambers have promised to
attempt an override.
   In the meantime, Democrats hope to bring public pressure on the
White House by characterizing Bush's position as unfair to the
working poor and by juxtaposing his veto threat with his plan to
spend billions of dollars to rescue troubled savings and loans and
his proposal to lower capital gains tax rates.
   ``The wealthiest of the wealthy would get tax breaks big enough
to hire two minimum wage workers each to take care of their gardens
or do their laundry,'' said Rep. William D. Ford, D-Mich. ``Is this
the Bush full employment program?''
   Speaker Jim Wright said the ``meager increase'' included in the
legislation still would leave the minimum wage trailing inflation
increases since the wage floor last was raised.
   ``Today we seek to provide fairness for the working poor of this
country,'' Wright said. ``There are at least 4 million of them who
receive no more than the minimum wage.''
   Republicans, however, said Democrats were passing up an
opportunity to increase the minimum wage by accepting Bush's more
modest offer and instead had decided on waging a political battle
with the White House for control of the domestic-policy agenda.
   The Republicans also reiterated their contention that raising
the minimum wage without also establishing a six-month subminimum
for newly hired workers would trigger massive job losses.
   ``The bottom line is it will cost at least 650,000 new jobs in
three years, the very people that we want to bring into the
workforce to help them become productive members of society,'' Rep.
Steve Bartlett, R-Texas, said of the bill passed Thursday. ``There
can be no further compromise that throws people out of work.
President Bush has offered the compromise.''
   Bush had proposed raising the minumum wage to $4.25 an hour by
January 1992 provided employers could pay new hires the ``training
wage'' for six months.
   In rejecting that offer, Democratic leaders said Bush's proposed
increase was too small and also assailed his ``training wage''
because the provision requires no actual training. In their final
bill, Democrats allowed workers with less than 60 days of work
experience to be paid a subminimum.
   In the Senate, much like the House, sponsors have more than
enough votes to gain passage of the measure but seem short of the
two-thirds majority needed to override a veto.
   ``If he vetoes it, then he has declared the end of the
honeymoon,'' said Rep. Austin Murphy, D-Pa..
   The result of a veto, Murphy said, will be action on a lengthy
list of Democrat-sponsored bills dealing with such issues as
parental leave, child care and mandatory health insurance.
   ``A veto would tell other members there is no reason to say the
president is trying to get along,'' said Murphy. ``That would
undoubtedly cause the sponsors of those bills to demand that they
advance.''
   But administration aides have said one of the reasons Bush will
veto the minimum-wage bill is to assert his position on domestic
policy to prevent the Democrats' agenda from gaining momentum.
   Business and labor groups plan media campaigns and other
lobbying efforts to pressure lawmakers considered to be potential
swing votes in an attempted veto override.
   Proponents of the bill also are trying to draft another minimum
wage bill for quick consideration should they lose the veto fight,
which appears likely.
</TEXT>
