<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-11 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained value against most major
currencies Thursday despite further evidence of a slowdown in U.S.
economic growth.
   Gold prices rose, partly in response to the tension in Panama.
   Foreign-exchange dealers said demand for dollars appeared
unaffected by a Commerce Department report that retail sales rose
by only 0.4 percent in April. Economists said the weak sales figure
showed the extent to which higher interest rates and inflation are
discouraging consumer spending.
   Lee Stalzer, an assistant vice president at Amsterdam Rotterdam
Bank, said there was no indication that central banks intervened in
the currency markets to influence exchange rates.
   ``Until we get some concerted intervention, where they really
mean business, the dollar will continue to go up,'' she said.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6655 late Thursday, cheaper
for buyers than late Wednesday's $1.6717. Sterling weakened against
the dollar in New York, ending the day at $1.6645 compared with
$1.6740 on Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Wednesday's
late rates included: 1.9160 West German marks, up from 1.9020;
135.37 Japanese yen, up from 134.41; 1.7080 Swiss francs, up from
1.6921; 1.1870 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1843; 6.4755 French
francs, up from 6.4220; and 1,395.75 Italian lire, up from 1,385.25.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Wednesday's
late rates: 1.9135 West German marks, up from 1.9047; 1.7060 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6925; 6.4665 French francs, up from 6.4645;
2.1580 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1500; 1,395.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,390.125; and 1.1870 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1849.
   Gold prices were bid higher as traders considered the
implications of President Bush's decision to send combat troops to
Panama. Frequently during times of political unrest or other
uncertainty, investors buy gold as a safe haven for their money.
   Bush said he was sending 2,000 combat troops to Panama and
evacuating U.S. dependents to protect Americans from the violence
that started after the country's presidential elections.
   Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid of $379.40 for a
troy ounce of gold bullion at 4 p.m. EDT, up from late Wednesday's
bid of $376.60. Earlier gold bullion for current delivery rose
$3.30 a troy ounce to $381 on the Commodity Exchange in New York.
   Gold bullion prices improved slightly in Europe. Gold traded
late in London, the major market, at a bid price of $379.00 a troy
ounce, up from $377.25. The late bid price in Zurich, Switzerland,
was $378.20, up from $376.75.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $377.25, down from $378.25.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled
at $5.65 a troy ounce, up from $5.607 Wednesday. Silver bullion
traded late in London at a bid $5.66 a troy ounce, down from $5.68.
</TEXT>
