<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-11 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The energy futures market rebounded sharply
Thursday on technical factors, with gasoline prices showing
particular strength.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, settled
54 cents higher at $20.06 a barrel. The contract had fallen 24
cents on Wednesday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for June delivery jumped 2.56 cents to
67.28 cents a gallon after losing 0.80 cent on Wednesday. June
heating oil, which rose 0.49 cent Wednesday, settled at 48.68 cents
a gallon, up another 1.20 cents.
   Longer-term contracts showed smaller gains.
   Richard Redoglia, a vice president at Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures, said the gains resulted from a technical reaction to a
sharp decline in prices in previous sessions as well as from
concern over the political situation in Panama following Sunday's
presidential election.
   ``The market has just found itself in a real nervous position,''
Redoglia said.
   Some of the concern may be unfounded in terms of endangering the
supply of oil. Although Alaskan crude moves through a pipeline in
Panama en route to the Gulf Coast, analysts noted that the volume
of oil carried is not significant.
   Gains in gasoline prices were particularly strong. Traders said
prices that were knocked down in previous sessions presented
investors with an incentive to buy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
