<DOCNO> AP890511-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-89 1906EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     05-11 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply fell in the week ended May 1, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 fell to a seasonally
adjusted $3,071.3 billion from $3,082.1 billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, fell to a seasonally adjusted
$3,953.2 billion from $3,965.5 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, fell to a
seasonally adjusted $781.7 billion from $786.9 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   The Fed in February reaffirmed a provisional target for 1989 of
3 percent to 7 percent growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent
growth in M3. The Fed has not set a target for M1 growth since
early 1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,076.9 billion, a 1.6
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous
13 weeks. M3 averaged $3,969.4 billion, up 3.7 percent, while M1
fell 1.1 percent to an average of $787.3 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window, excluding extended credit,
averaged $522 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, down from
$687 million the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve said net free reserves totaled $670 million
in the two weeks ended May 3, up from net borrowed reserves of $377
million in the two weeks ended April 19.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $290.2 billion in the two-week period ended May
3, up from $288.3 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
