<HEAD>Energy Futures Soar On Panama Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-12 pvs, Wheat and... with 5 new gravs to RECAST
and CLARIFY. Picks up 13th graf pvs, The USDA's...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures prices climbed back above $20 a barrel
Thursday and petroleum-product prices soared in a rally bolstered
by President Bush's decision to send combat troops to Panama.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures fell; precious
metals advanced; cattle prices rose and pork futures were mixed.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude settled unchanged to 54 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in June at $20.06 a barrel; heating oil was .07 cent to
1.20 cents higher with June at 48.68 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .80 cent to 2.56 cents higher with June at 67.28 cents
a gallon.
   June crude, which reached a recent high of $21.60 a barrel on
April 26, dropped below $20 on Monday.
   Technical factors played a large role in Thursday's surge but
the Panamanian situation ``seemed to take on more importance as the
day wore on,'' said Jerry Samuels, an analyst with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Traders fear a military conflict in Panama could affect the
daily movement of 400,000 barrels of crude through the Panama Canal.
   Unconfirmed reports that Bush planned to send troops to Panama
circulated during the trading session. After the close Bush said he
was sending about 2,000 troops and evacuating dependents to protect
Americans in the turmoil arising from a presidential election that
the White House condemned as ``electoral theft'' by Gen. Manuel
Noriega.
   Soybean futures ended sharply lower on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid forecasts of rain and disappointment over the
government's reluctance to subsidize a sale of U.S. soybean oil to
the Soviet Union.
   Wheat and corn futures also retreated.
   The National Weather Service's new six-to-10-day outlook, issued
late Wednesday, calls for rain next week in the central Plains and
the western Corn Belt, two areas that have not shared in the
general recovery from last summer's drought.
   Soybean and corn futures also were pressured by expectations for
showers this weekend in the Midwest, analysts said.
   Additional selling of soybean futures stemmed from Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter's statement Thursday morning that the
USDA had not decided whether to subsidize the sale of U.S. soybean
oil to the Soviet Union. The market had expected a subsidized sale
to be announced.
   After the markets closed, the Agriculture Department issued a
report estimating 1989 U.S. winter wheat production at a decade low
of 1.43 billion bushels.
   The USDA's winter wheat estimate represented an 8 percent drop
from last year's harvest of 1.56 billion bushels. The report was
expected to prompt new buying of wheat futures on the Board of
Trade on Friday.
   Wheat settled 1} cents lower to 1{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.28 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 3\ cents lower with May at $2.76\ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents
lower to { cent higher with May at $1.84{ a bushel; soybeans were
6} cents to 10\ cents lower with May at $7.51{ a bushel.
   The rise in oil prices spurred a moderate advance in
precious-metal prices, which tend to increase with signs of higher
inflation.
   Gold settled $2.30 to $3.30 higher with June at $382.10 a troy
ounce; silver was 3.8 cents to 4.8 cents higher with July at $5.735
a troy ounce.
   Most cattle futures ended slightly higher in light trading after
weakening earlier in the session. Pork futures settled mostly lower
amid profit-taking after two days of steep gains.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .30 cent higher with June at
72.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .28 cent
higher with May at 77.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent
lower to .07 cent higher with June at 48 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .75 cent lower to .45 cent higher with May at 35.05
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
