<SECOND>AM-USAir-Jets,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir Sells 20 Jets to McDonnell Douglas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir Group Inc. said Thursday it has sold its
entire fleet of 20 BAC 1-11 jetliners to McDonnell Douglas Corp. as
part of a deal in which the airline will buy $1.3 billion in new
aircraft from the manufacturer.
   The purchase price was undisclosed.
   Ten of the twin-engine, 74-seat planes will be leased back to
USAir by McDonnell Douglas until early August, when the aircraft
type will be phased out of USAir's fleet after 24 years of service.
   USAir recently bought 20 MD-82 jets from McDonnell Douglas, with
an option to buy 20 more.
   A subsidiary will continue to stock BAC 1-11 spare parts and
offer training on its BAC 1-11 simulator _ the only one in North
and South America, the company said.
   USAir acquired most of its BAC 1-11s in 1972 when its
predecessor company, Allegheny Airlines, merged with the former
Mohawk Airlines.
