<FIRST>r f BC-PillsburySales     05-11 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pillsbury Sales,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Met Selling Pillsbury Units in Latin America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC is selling five food
processing units in Latin America as it continues to streamline
Pillsbury Co., which Grand Met bought earlier this year for $5.7
billion.
   On the sale block are a flour mill and pasta plant near Caracas,
Venezuela; two consumer foods plants in Guatemala City, Guatemala;
and a minority holding in a flour mill in San Salvador, El Salvador.
   Together they accounted for about $40 million in sales last year
in Pillsbury's $500 million International Foods division, the
company said.
   Pillsbury Chairman Ian A. Martin said the Latin American
interests are not strongly linked to the company's branded foods
businesses, ``and thus do not fit our long-term strategy.''
   Since January, Grand Met has fired 550 workers at Pillsbury
headquarters in Minneapolis and an equal number of non-restaurant
workers throughout the Burger King system, said Larry Haeg, a
Pillsbury spokesman.
   London-based Grand Met also sold Pillsbury's Azteca Mexican
Foods business and its S&amp;A Restaurant Corp., which included the
chains of Steak &amp; Ale and Bennigan's.
   In addition, Grand Met has shut down a pizza plant in Joplin,
Mo., a frozen fish plant in Santa Fe Springs, Calif., a sweet
potato plant in Turkey, N.C., and a potato side dish plant in Grand
Forks, N.D., Haeg said.
   The production from those plants has been shifted to other
Pillsbury plants, he said.
   Haeg declined to say what the asking price is for the Latin
American units.
   ``We'll consider all serious offers,'' he said.
