<FIRST>u f Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   05-11 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down in Tokyo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei, dollar quotes.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar hit an eight-month high against the
Japanese yen Friday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange were sharply lower.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 89.14-point
gainer Thursday, ended the morning session at 33,839.36 points,
down 242.13 points, or 0.7 percent.
   After opening at 135.40 yen, up 0.85 yen from Thursday's close
of 134.55 yen, the dollar moved in a range of 135.40-.65 yen. The
currency was being traded at 135.48 yen at midday.
   It was the first time that the dollar traded at the 135.65 level
since Sept. 6.
   Traders said the dollar's surge followed overnight gains against
most major currencies, including the Japanese yen, on overseas
markets.
   The dollar's rise was triggered by a decision Thursday by U.S.
President George Bush to send more U.S. troops to Panama to help
protect the 51,000 American civilians living in that country, said
a trader at the Bank of Tokyo, who spoke anonymously. There are
10,000 troops already based at U.S. installations along the Panama
Canal.
   The U.S. currency is regarded as a safe haven in times of
international tension.
   In a press confernce Friday morning, Finance Minister Tatsuo
Maruyama said he was not alarmed by the dollar's surge. ``The
dollar was bought due partly to its (potential) strength at the
time of an emergency such as confusion,'' over the Panamanian
presidential election, Maruyama said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, share prices declined on a broad
front due to concerns over the yen's fall and the possibility of a
discount rate hike.
   Some Japanese economists have said the nation's monetary
authorities are waiting to assess price data due later this month
before deciding on the timing for cutting the discount rate, which
now stands at a post-World War II low of 2.5 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
